{"title_page": "Aitken Spence", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name   = Aitken Spence\n|logo   = Aitken Spence logo.png\n|type   = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{Colombo Stock Exchange|SPEN.N0000}}\n|foundation = 1868\n| founder   = Patrick Gordon Spence<br>Thomas Clark<br>Edward Aitken<br>S.R. Aitken\n|location    = [[Colombo]], [[Sri Lanka]]\n|key_people        = [[Harry Jayawardena]]<br> (Chairman),<br> Rajan Brito <br>(Deputy Chairman and<br> Managing Director),<br> Rohan Fernando (Director),<br> Stasshani Jayawardena(Director)\n| area_served      = [[Sri Lanka]], [[Maldives]], [[Bangladesh]],<br>[[India]], [[South Africa]], [[Oman]], [[Fiji]], [[Mozambique]]\n|industry       = [[Leisure industry|Leisure]]<br>[[Transportation]] & [[Logistics]]<br>[[Power Generation]]<br>[[Information Technology]]<br>[[Financial Services]]<br>[[Business Process Outsourcing|BPO]]<br>[[Knowledge Process Outsourcing|KPO]]<br>[[Printing]]<br>[[Apparel]]<br>[[Plantations|Plantation Services]]<br>[[Real Estate Development|Property Development]]\n|products = \n|revenue = {{increase}} US$ 338.9 million <small>(2017/18)</small>\n|operating_income = {{profit}} US$ 3.5 million <small>(2017/18)</small>\n|net_income = {{profit}} US$ 33.1 million <small>(2017/18)</small>\n|assets = {{profit}} US$ 693.1 million <small>(2017/18)</small>\n|equity = {{profit}} US$ 361.7 million <small>(2017/18)</small>\n|num_employees = 13,533 (2018)\n|homepage = [http://www.aitkenspence.com Official Website] |\n}}\n'''Aitken Spence PLC''' ({{lang-si|[[:si:\u0d91\u0dba\u0dd2\u0da7\u0dca\u0d9a\u0dd2\u0db1\u0dca \u0dc3\u0dca\u0db4\u0dd9\u0db1\u0dca\u0dc3\u0dca|\u0d91\u0dba\u0dd2\u0da7\u0dca\u0d9a\u0dd2\u0db1\u0dca \u0dc3\u0dca\u0db4\u0dd9\u0db1\u0dca\u0dc3\u0dca]]}}; {{lang-ta|[[:ta:\u0b8e\u0baf\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0bb8\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc6\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0bb8\u0bcd|\u0b8e\u0baf\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0bb8\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc6\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0bb8\u0bcd]]}}) is a Sri Lankan [[Blue chip (stock market)|blue chip]] [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]]<ref name=bluechip>{{cite news | title = Aitken Spence\u2019s 9 month profits up 24% to Rs. 3 b | newspaper = Daily FT | location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 16 February 2012 | url = http://www.ft.lk/2012/02/14/aitken-spences-9-month-profits-up-24-to-rs-3-b/ | accessdate = 14 February 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131216213315/http://www.ft.lk/2012/02/14/aitken-spences-9-month-profits-up-24-to-rs-3-b/ | archive-date = 16 December 2013 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> with operations in South Asia, the Middle East, Africa and the Pacific.<ref name=\"dnprofile\">{{cite news | title = Aitken Spence posts Rs 1.7b profit in 1H | newspaper = Daily News | location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 5 November 2011 | url = http://www.dailynews.lk/2011/11/05/bus05.asp | accessdate = 10 January 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130218224018/http://www.dailynews.lk/2011/11/05/bus05.asp | archive-date = 18 February 2013 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"fijiPortMgmt\">{{cite news | title = Aitken Spence takes control of Fijian ports | publisher = Port Technology International | location = | date = 31 July 2013 | url = http://www.porttechnology.org/news/aitken_spence_takes_control_of_fijian_ports/ | accessdate=1 August 2013 }}</ref>  Listed in the [[Colombo Stock Exchange]] since 1983, it has major interests in hotels, travel, maritime services and logistics.<ref name=\"dnprofile\"/> The group also has a significant presence in printing, plantations, power generation, financial services, IT, BPO/KPO sector,  elevator agency services, garments, and property development.<ref name=\"dnprofile\"/>\n\nAitken Spence has been recognised by [[Forbes]] as one of the most successful publicly traded companies with annual sales under US$1 billion outside of the United States, for three consecutive years.<ref name=\"ASabout\">{{cite web| last = Aitken Spence| title = About Us| publisher = Aitken Spence| url = http://www.aitkenspence.com/about_us/hotels_logistics_power_sri_lanka.asp| accessdate = 17 January 2012| archive-url = https://archive.is/20120720111535/http://www.aitkenspence.com/about_us/hotels_logistics_power_sri_lanka.asp| archive-date = 20 July 2012| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref> In 2012, Aitken Spence was adjudged the top winner of the Best Corporate Citizen Award in 2017 and 2012 presented by the [[Ceylon Chamber of Commerce]] and has retained the title for 11 consecutive years.<ref name=\"BCCA2012\">{{cite news | title = Aitken Spence bags Best Corporate Citizen Award 2012 | newspaper = Daily Mirror | location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 13 November 2012 | url = http://www.dailymirror.lk/business/other/23439-aitken-spence-wins-best-corporate-citizen-award-2012-.html| accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"BCCA2017\">{{cite news | title = Aitken Spence wins Best Corporate Citizen Award 2017 | newspaper = Daily FT | location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 30 November 2017 | url = http://www.ft.lk/front-page/Aitken-Spence-wins--Best-Corporate-Citizen-Sustainability-Award-2017-/44-644258| accessdate= 17 January 2018}}</ref> The company is one of the first signatories to the UN's [[United Nations Global Compact|Global Compact]] in Sri Lanka.<ref name=\"UNGC\">{{cite web |title= UNGC Participants and Stakeholders |url= http://www.unglobalcompact.org/participants/search?commit=t&country%5B%5D=111&page=1&per_page=250|accessdate=11 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Patrick G. Spence.jpg|thumb|Patrick G. Spence]]\nWhilst the roots of Aitken Spence can be dated back to Wilson & Archer Partnership of the 1830s in the early [[British Ceylon|British Colonial Ceylon]], the company began to take its current form after the signing of a formal partnership agreement between Thomas Clark and Patrick Gordon Spence\u2014Scottish merchants and shipping agents<ref name=\"Trading\">{{cite book | last = Wright | first = Arnold |title= Twentieth Century Impressions of Ceylon: Its History, People, Commerce.. |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=eUF_rS8FEoIC&pg=PA437 |accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref> in [[Galle]]\u2014on 1 September 1868, wherein Clark Spence & Co. was established.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\">{{cite web| last = Aitken Spence| year = 2011| title = Aitken Spence Company Annual Report 2010-2011: Time Line| pages = 182\u2013183| url = http://www.aitkenspence.com/pdf/ar2011/aitken_spence_company_annual_report_2010_2011.pdf| accessdate = 17 January 2012| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131216214018/http://www.aitkenspence.com/pdf/ar2011/aitken_spence_company_annual_report_2010_2011.pdf| archive-date = 16 December 2013| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"FoundingHistory\">{{cite news | title = The Rootage of Insurance in Sri Lanka | author = M.Z.M. Nazim | newspaper = The Island | location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 17 November 2009 | url = http://www.island.lk/2009/11/17/business8.html | accessdate=17 November 2011}}</ref> Clark Spence & Co.'s trading segment at this stage included exports of [[graphite|natural vein graphite]] (plumbago), gems, hides, [[Caesalpinia sappan|Sappan wood]], [[ebony]], coffee, coconut oil, [[coir|coir yarn, bristle fibre]], arrack,  and [[citronella oil]] to [[United Kingdom]], [[Continental Europe]], [[United States of America]] and [[Australia]]; and imports of [[Burma|Burmese]] rice and coal for [[Steamboat|steamer ship]] [[Fuel oil#Bunker fuel|bunkers]].<ref name=\"earlytrade\">{{cite web| last = Aitken Spence| year = 2005| title = Aitken Spence Company Annual Report 2004-2005: A Brief Historical Outlook| pages = 126/128| url = http://www.aitkenspence.com/pdf/aitken_spence_2004_05_annual%20_report.pdf| accessdate = 17 January 2012| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090205175707/http://aitkenspence.com/pdf/aitken_spence_2004_05_annual%20_report.pdf| archive-date = 5 February 2009| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April 1871, Patrick Gordon Spence, secured Clark Spence & Co. as the sole agent of Lloyd's of London in [[Ceylon]].<ref name=\"FoundingHistory\"/> In order to service the Agency for the [[Lloyd's|Lloyd's of London]] for the [[Port of Colombo]], Clark Spence & Co. partnered with Britton, Aitken & Co. to open a branch office in [[Colombo]]. On New Year's Day, 1873, E.C. Britton opted out of the Britton, Aitken & Co. partnership, resulting in Patrick Gordon Spence, Edward Aitken and S.R. Aitken coming together to form Aitken Spence & Co. to manage the operations in Colombo, whilst Clark Spence & Co. continued in partnership to operate in Galle.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/><ref name=\"FoundingHistory\"/> In 1876, Aitken Spence & Co. obtained the Lloyds agency from Clark Spence & Co.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/> Aitken Spence had also obtained the local agency of [[Morgan Crucible| Morgan Crucible Company]] for trading in plumbago.<ref name=\"Trading\" /> As Colombo became the commercial capital of Sri Lanka, Aitken Spence & Co became more prominent and subsequently its partner company, Clark Spence & Co. originally based in Galle, became a subsidiary of Aitken Spence & Co.<ref name=\"LMDcorporateHistory\">{{cite web| last = Lanka Monthly Digest (LMD)| year = 2013| title = Corporate Heritage: Aitken Spence| url = http://lmd.lk/2013/12/26/corporate-heritage-profiles-9/| accessdate = 15 April 2014| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140415080257/http://lmd.lk/2013/12/26/corporate-heritage-profiles-9/| archive-date = 15 April 2014| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:Edward Aitken.jpg|thumb|Edward Aitken]]\nBy the 1880s, Aitken Spence had also secured the shipping agencies [[:nl:Koninklijke Rotterdamsche Lloyd|Koninklijke Rotterdamsche Lloyd]] and [[Netherland Line|Stoomvaart Maatschappij Nederland]] for Ceylon.<ref name=\"dutchshipping\">{{cite web | last = Lorck| year = 1912| title= Isles of the East: An Illustrated Guide. | url = https://archive.org/stream/cu31924010584682/cu31924010584682_djvu.txt| accessdate=23 December 2012}}</ref> The company moved into plantations sector as an agency house in the early 1900s and with the onset of the Great Depression, began to withdraw from its trading business. In 1918, Aitken Spence purchased the [[Lloyd's Building, Colombo|Freudenberg Building]] in Colombo, and made it its company headquarters having renamed the building as Lloyds Building. As a pioneer in port operations, Aitken Spence was entrusted in coordinating the Operations of Colombo Port during the Second World War.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/><ref name=\"FoundingHistory\"/>\n\nAitken Spence became a Private Company in 1952.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/> In its centenary year, 1968, it appointed its first Sri Lankan Chairman,<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/> E.L. Van Langenberg.<ref name=\"Heritage\">{{cite web |last= Aitken Spence |title= Our Heritage |url= http://www.aitkenspence.com/about_us/shipping_tourism_insurance_industry_sri_lanka.asp |accessdate= 17 January 2012 |archive-url= https://archive.is/20130117151217/http://www.aitkenspence.com/about_us/shipping_tourism_insurance_industry_sri_lanka.asp |archive-date= 17 January 2013 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref> By 1971, as Sri Lanka was preparing to end British dominion and declare as [[Sri Lanka#Independence|republic]], the company became a wholly Sri Lankan owned entity.<ref name=\"CompanyOwner\">{{cite book | last = Shalini Perera | year = 2011| title= Corporate Ownership and Control | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=VXT36YV6RBIC&pg=PA124 | accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> In 1972, it began to offer shares to its executives, thereby broad basing its ownership. The company eventually moved on from this model and in 1983 offered its shares to the general public on the [[Colombo Stock Exchange]] with an issued share capital of Rs. 51 million.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/><ref name=\"LMDcover\">{{cite news | title = Aitken Spence Historic Milestones | newspaper = LMD | location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = September 2005 | url = http://lmd.lk/archives/2005/September/cov7.htm | accessdate = 12 October 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130406154554/http://lmd.lk/archives/2005/September/cov7.htm | archive-date = 6 April 2013 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nDuring the early 1960s and early 1970s, Insurance and Plantations sectors\u2014which were core business segments of Aitken Spence, where the company had been well established at the time\u2014were nationalized.<ref name=\"Nationalized\">{{cite news |title= Changing of the guard at Aitken Spence|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/011230/bus3.html|newspaper= The Sunday Times |date= 30 December 2001|accessdate= 5 April 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Nationalization\">{{cite news|title= R. Sivaratnam retires after 40 years at Aitken Spence|url= http://www.priu.gov.lk/news_update/features/20020103sivaratnam_retires.htm|newspaper= Daily News|date= 1 January 2002|accessdate= 12 November 2015|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160304081255/http://www.priu.gov.lk/news_update/features/20020103sivaratnam_retires.htm|archive-date= 4 March 2016|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> However, the Group's [[marine insurance]] segment (including its Lloyd Agency) continued to operate as it did not fall within the purview of nationalization.\n\nDespite the setbacks from nationalization, in realizing the then government's thrust to boost tourism, Aitken Spence launched its tourism segment in 1972 with investments in its first hotel (Neptune Hotel in Beruwala, Sri Lanka opened in 1974).<ref name=\"Nationalized\"/> The company then entered into Aviation in 1974 (as general sales agent for [[Singapore Airlines]] in Sri Lanka).<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/> In consolidating its travel agency business that had begun with the launch of Aitken Spence Hotels in 1974, Aitken Spence set up Aitken Spence Travels in 1977 as inbound and outbound tour operators in Sri Lanka and as agents for [[Eurail]] and Britrail.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/><ref name=\"TravelsFormation\">{{cite news|title= Prema Cooray : A long and colourful journey|url= http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2002/12/15/bus17.html|newspaper= The Sunday Observer|date= 15 December 2002|accessdate= 15 May 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150924111825/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2002/12/15/bus17.html|archive-date= 24 September 2015|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> Tourism is now a core business segment of Aitken Spence.\n\nWith Sri Lanka adopting open market economic policies focused on export led growth in 1977, Aitken Spence forayed further into new business segments : Container and allied services in 1979; Garments and apparels in 1979;<ref name=\"garmentsweb\">{{cite web|url= http://www.aitkenspence.com/strategic_investments/garment_manufacture_in_sri_lanka.asp|title= Garment Manufacture|accessdate= October 9, 2012|archive-url= https://archive.is/20130116093005/http://www.aitkenspence.com/strategic_investments/garment_manufacture_in_sri_lanka.asp|archive-date= 16 January 2013|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> International courier service agency with [[Thomas Nationwide Transport|TNT]] in 1981;<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/> and Elevators in 1989 as agent of [[Otis Elevator Company|OTIS]].<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/> With insurance sector being deregulated in the 1980s, the Group played a pivotal role in the resurgence of private sector insuarance as a proponent of the National Insurance Corporation and Union Assuarance Ltd, stakes in which Aitken Spence subsequently divested. Aitken Spence reentered Plantations sector, when the sector was reprivatized in 1992,  through its stake in Udapussellawa Plantation PLC that was later divested.\n\nIn response to the Power Crisis in Sri Lanka in 1996, Aitken Spence began to explore investment opportunities in power generation sector, with first two power plants coming online in 2002.<ref name=\"jvjp\">{{cite news |title= CEB grid to get 20 mega watt boost |url= http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2002/03/10/bus01.html |newspaper= The Sunday Observer |date= 10 March 2002 |accessdate= 9 October 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150924111719/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2002/03/10/bus01.html |archive-date= 24 September 2015 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The Group also maintained container vessel operations, with acquisition of five ships in a joint venture with Ceyline Group in 2003, which it later divested in 2008. In 2010, in continuing its partnership with Ceyline Group, Aitken Spence invested in [[Colombo International Nautical and Engineering College|CINEC]], Sri Lanka's largest private higher education institution. In 2004, Aitken Spence Travels partnered with [[TUI Group]] of Germany to form a joint venture that is the largest leisure, travel and tourism company in the world.\n\nAitken Spence was the first Sri Lankan resort operator to embark on overseas resort operations having acquired Bathala Island Resort of [[Maldives]] in 1993.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/><ref name=\"TourismInnovation\">{{cite news |title= Kandalama, Club Rannhali my indelible moments|url= http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=62856|newspaper= The Island |date= 2 October 2012|accessdate= 15 May 2014}}</ref> In 1996, Aitken Spence entered [[Bangladesh]] through Aitken Spence Cargo with its shipping services.<ref>{{cite web| last = Aitken Spence Cargo| title = About Ace Cargo| url = http://www.acecargo.lk/about-acecargo.html| accessdate = 17 January 2012| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20111229145231/http://www.acecargo.lk/about-acecargo.html| archive-date = 29 December 2011| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref> A decade later, in 2006, Aitken Spence entered the Indian hospitality sector, having secured management contracts for five hotel properties in [[India]].<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/> On the same year, the company broke new ground by becoming the first Sri Lankan company to venture into port efficiency management outside of Sri Lanka, when it undertook to improve efficiency of ports in the African continent.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/><ref>{{cite news |title= Sri Lanka Aitken Spence to make Mozambique port efficient |url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?nid=1702158326 |newspaper= Lanka Business Online |date= 12 June 2011 |accessdate= 21 March 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20121123224538/http://lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?nid=1702158326 |archive-date= 23 November 2012 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The company increased its global presence even further by obtaining the management of four hotel properties in [[Oman]] in 2007.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/> In 2013, Aitken Spence announced its proposed venture into [[Fiji]] to manage the Ports of [[Suva]] and [[Lautoka]] in a public private partnership with the Government of Fiji.<ref name=\"fijiPortMgmt\"/><ref name=FijiPort>{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence PLC takes over the management of two major ports in Fiji |url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/130505/business-times/aitken-spence-plc-takes-over-the-management-of-two-major-ports-in-fiji-42782.html |newspaper= The Sunday Times |date= 5 May 2013 |accessdate=6 May 2013}}</ref> The Group has expressed interest to further diversify its investments in Fiji, venturing into hospitality, power and printing sectors.<ref name=FijiDiversity>{{cite news |title= Company plans for more investment in Fiji |url= http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=293963 |newspaper= The Fiji Times Online |date= 4 February 2015 |accessdate= 7 February 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150207204809/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=293963 |archive-date= 7 February 2015 |url-status= dead }}</ref> Currently, the company has operations in eight countries (Sri Lanka, Maldives, Bangladesh, India, South Africa, Oman, Fiji and Myanmar), spanning several continents<ref>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Company Annual Report 2017-2018:Our Network |pages = 8, 28\u201333 | url = http://aitkenspence.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Aitken-Spence-PLC-AR-2017-18.pdf | accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref> with 13,000 employees.<ref>{{cite video|year=2018|title=Corporate Video|url=http://www.aitkenspence.com/about_us/hotels_logistics_power_sri_lanka.asp|publisher=Aitken Spence|accessdate=21 March 2012|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120720111535/http://www.aitkenspence.com/about_us/hotels_logistics_power_sri_lanka.asp|archive-date=20 July 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=ARKeyEvents>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Annual Report Key Events 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=18 June 2018 |url= http://aitkenspence.com/annualreport/#KeyEvents}}</ref>\n\n== Governance structure ==\nAitken Spence is governed by the chairman and the board of directors and is managed by the Group Management Committee.<ref name=\"Management\">{{cite web | last = Aitken Spence| year = 2018| title= Aitken Spence Company Annual Report 2017-2018: Board of Directors and Board of Management  | url = http://aitkenspence.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Aitken-Spence-PLC-AR-2017-18.pdf | accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Chairman and Board of Directors ===\nThe current chairman of Aitken Spence is [[Harry Jayawardena|Mr. Harry Jayawardena]]. He is the founder director and current chairman/managing director of the Stassen Group of Companies \u2013 a diversified group in exports and import trade, the chairman of Lanka Milk Foods (CWE) PLC, Browns Beach Hotels PLC, Balangoda Plantations PLC, Madulsima Plantations PLC, Melstacorp PLC, Ambewela Livestock Company Ltd, Lanka Bell Ltd and also the current chairman of the [[Distilleries Company of Sri Lanka|Distilleries Company of Sri Lanka (DCSL) PLC]].<ref name=\"Management\"/>\n\nThe current panel of board directors includes Dr. Parakrama Dissanayake, deputy chairman/managing director; and executive directors Dr. Rohan Fernando, and Ms. Stasshani Jayawardena; and the non-executive directors Mr. Rajan Brito, Mr. G.C. Wickremasinghe, Mr. Charles Gomez, Mr. Niranjan Deva Aditya and Mr. Rajan Asirwatham.<ref name=\"Management\"/><ref>{{cite web |title= Stasshani Jayawardena Appointed to the Aitken Spence PLC Board |url= http://aitkenspenceplc.wordpress.com// |date= 29 November 2013 |accessdate= 30 November 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131210041408/http://aitkenspenceplc.wordpress.com/ |archive-date= 10 December 2013 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n[[File:Aitken Spence Towers.JPG|thumb|x200px|Aitken Spence Towers, Corporate Headquarters of Aitken Spence Group, in Colombo. 02.]]\n\n=== Group Management Committee ===\nGroup Management Committee is headed by Dr. Parakrama Dissanayke. The other members of the Group Management Committee are Dr. Rohan Fernando,  Ms. Stasshani Jayawardena, Ms. Nilanthi Sivapragasam, Mr. Rohan Pandithakorralage, Ms. Nimmi Guneratne, Mr. Susith Jayawickrama,  Mr. Dinesh Mendis, Mr. Prasanna Karunathilake, Mr. Leel Wickremarachchi, Mr. Nalin Jayasundera, Mr. Iqram Cuttilan, Mr. Janaka Gunawardena, Mr. Jerome Brohier, Mr.Vasantha Kudaliyanage, Mr. Calude Jayantha Fernando and Mr. Chaminda Hidurangala<ref name=\"AR2017\">{{cite web | last = Aitken Spence| year = 2014| title= Aitken Spence Company Annual Report 2017-2018 | url = http://aitkenspence.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Aitken-Spence-PLC-AR-2017-18.pdf | accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Corporate sustainability==\n\nAitken Spence PLC was adjudged the winner of the Best Corporate Citizen Sustainability Award 2018, 2017 and 2012 conducted by the [[Ceylon Chamber of Commerce]]. The company has been ranked among the Top 10 Corporate Citizens for an unprecedented 13 consecutive years.<ref name=\"Best Corporate Citizen\">{{cite news |url= http://www.ft.lk/front-page/Aitken-Spence-wins--Best-Corporate-Citizen-Sustainability-Award-2017-/44-644258|title= Best Corporate Citizen Sustainability Award |date= 29 November 2017|accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref> Aitken Spence PLC won multiple category awards such as for Employee Relations and Community Relations, Triple Bottom Line Award for its work on Environmental Sustainability and was awarded the sector based sustainability champions for Diversified Holdings.<ref>{{cite news |title=Best Corporate Citizen Award |newspaper=The Island |date=29 November 2017 |accessdate=7 February 2018 |url= http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=175776}}</ref>\n\nAitken Spence's sustainability framework has been rated Platinum by STING Corporate Accountability Index 2018 for the 6th consecutive year and has been ranked among the top three companies in the index since 2011.<ref>{{cite news |title=Aitken Spence Rated Platinum |newspaper=Daily News |date=21 March 2018 |accessdate=26 March 2018  |url= http://www.dailynews.lk/2018/03/21/business/146074/aitken-spence-rated-platinum-consecutively-corporate-accountability}}</ref> Published by LMD bi-annually, the index rated the top 50 companies from the LMD 100 (excluding investment companies) as well as key state-owned enterprises on a holistic and integrated model covering corporate responsibility, sustainability and governance.\n\nAs a result of the company's long-standing engagement with the local network of the [[United Nations Global Compact|UN Global Compact]], Aitken Spence has been admitted to the board and the steering committee of the Sri Lanka Network.<ref name=\"GCNCrole\">{{cite web |url= https://aitkenspenceplc.wordpress.com/2011/11/ |title= Aitken Spence Recognized as a Best Corporate Citizen for the Sixth Year Running |accessdate=13 October 2012}}</ref> The company reports 'Advanced\u2019 in the UNGC Communication on Progress (COP) which indicates that the company qualifies as GC Active and, in addition, cover the company's implementation of advanced criteria and best practices.<ref name=\"UNGC COP\">{{cite web |url= https://www.unglobalcompact.org/participation/report/cop/ |title= The Communication on Progress (COP) in Brief |accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"UNGC Advanced COP\">{{cite web |url= https://www.unglobalcompact.org/participation/report/cop/create-and-submit/advanced?page=1&per_page=250/ |title= Total number of GC Advanced COPs received |accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> Dr. Rohan Fernando, head of plantations and business development at Aitken Spence, was the former chairman of the Global Compact Sri Lanka Network.<ref name=\"GCNCchair\">{{cite news|url= http://www.dailynews.lk/2011/05/16/bus18.asp|title= Environmental trusteeship essential for sustainability|date= 16 May 2011|accessdate= 13 October 2012|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110821060434/http://www.dailynews.lk/2011/05/16/bus18.asp|archive-date= 21 August 2011|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAitken Spence is amongst the first 38 companies in the world to endorse the Women's Empowerment Principles, a joint initiative of [[UN Women]] and UN Global Compact to promote gender equality in business, and the first company to do so in Sri Lanka.<ref name=\"wep\">{{cite web|url= http://www.dailynews.lk/2010/06/22/bus04.asp|title= Aitken Spence signs UN's Women's Empowerment Principles|date= 22 June 2010|accessdate= 13 October 2012|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100625132344/http://www.dailynews.lk/2010/06/22/bus04.asp|archive-date= 25 June 2010|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"wepsite\">{{cite web |url= http://weprinciples.org/Site/CeosSpeak/ |title= CEOs Speak |accessdate=13 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nAitken Spence is also one of the first companies in Sri Lanka to pledge its support to the Caring for Climate initiative, which is a joint effort by [[UNEP]], [[United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change|UNFCCC]] and [[United Nations Global Compact|UNGC]] to promote positive climate action in business.<ref name=\"careclimate\">{{cite web |url= http://www.unglobalcompact.org/docs/news_events/8.1/caring_for_climate.pdf |title= Caring for Climate: The Business Leadership Platform| date = June 2010 |accessdate=13 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"climate\">{{cite web | url=http://www.caringforclimate.org/about-list.php | title=Caring for Climate: List of Signatories }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, Aitken Spence launched '''Empowering Sri Lanka First''', an English and IT teaching program for children from its neighbouring communities as its flagship corporate community engagement initiative. The program enrols eight-year-old students for weekend English classes (180 children currently enrolled in pilot phase from Dambulla, Ahungalla, and Mawaramandiya) for a period of three years. The curriculum of the English program has been custom designed by [[British Council]] to complement Sri Lanka's local school syllabus and teachers from local communities trained on interactive [[pedagogy]]. Aitken Spence has announced its plans to commence the IT component of the program in September 2013.<ref name=\"ESLF\">{{cite news|title= Aitken Spence launches \u2018Empowering Sri Lanka First\u2019|url= http://www.ft.lk/2013/07/27/aitken-spence-launches-empowering-sri-lanka-first/|date= 27 July 2013|accessdate= 4 August 2013|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131216211018/http://www.ft.lk/2013/07/27/aitken-spence-launches-empowering-sri-lanka-first/|archive-date= 16 December 2013|url-status= dead}}</ref> The project was recognized with a merit award at the Best Sustainability Projects Awards 2014.<ref name=\"BCCSA2014\">{{cite news|url= http://www.ft.lk/2014/11/26/mas-intimate-wins-coveted-best-corporate-citizen-sustainability-award-2014/|title= MAS Intimate wins coveted Best Corporate Citizen Sustainability Award 2014|date= 26 November 2014|accessdate= 26 November 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141128220722/http://www.ft.lk/2014/11/26/mas-intimate-wins-coveted-best-corporate-citizen-sustainability-award-2014/|archive-date= 28 November 2014|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n\nAs part of a broadbased diversification strategy, the sector embarked on a landmark project in the country's waste to energy sphere. Seen as a vital and much needed solution for the waste disposal crisis within Colombo city limits, the proposed project involves the construction of a 10MW waste-toenergy plant at Muthurajawela. The plant will be fuelled by waste collected from the Colombo Municipal Area, which was previously dumped in Meethotamulla. The plant is equipped to convert between 600 \u2013 800 metric tonnes of municipal solid waste daily to electricity.<ref name=\"waste to energy\">{{cite news |title= The first waste-to-energy initiative in Sri Lanka |url= http://www.ft.lk/article/634380/Two-waste-to-energy-plants-to-get-off-the-ground-today/ | date= 10 August 2017 |accessdate= 9 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Sri Lanka's first waste to energy plant\">{{cite news |title= HNB partners up as lead banker to Sri Lanka's first waste-to-energy plant |url= http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=170297/ | date= 20 August 2017 |accessdate=30 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Hotels ==\n\nAitken Spence operates a chain of 21 hotels and resorts in four countries: Sri Lanka, Maldives, India and Oman and currently is the largest hotel room inventory owned by a Sri Lankan resort company with a room inventory of over 2600 rooms of capacity.<ref name=ASHR>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Hotels Annual Report Strategy and Prospects 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence Hotels |accessdate=16 June 2018 |url= https://www.aitkenspencehotels.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/ASH1718.pdf}}</ref> Its portfolio includes beach resorts and water villas, [[Ayurveda]] holiday resorts, and eco and culture resorts<ref name=hotelweb>{{cite web |title= Hotels |last= Aitken Spence |url= http://www.aitkenspence.com/hotels/hotels_in_sri_lanka_and_maldives.asp |accessdate= 6 March 2012 |archive-url= https://archive.is/20130116154608/http://www.aitkenspence.com/hotels/hotels_in_sri_lanka_and_maldives.asp |archive-date= 16 January 2013 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref> in the 3-5 [[Star (classification)#Hotel ratings|star category]].<ref name=tbl>{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence rejuvenates Neptune Resort |newspaper= The Bottom Line |date= 15 July 2009 |accessdate= 28 March 2012 |url= http://www.thebottomline.lk/2009/07/15/living30.html }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nBrands of Aitken Spence Hotels include \"Heritance Hotels and Resorts\", \"turyaa by Heritance\", \"Aitken Spence Hotels and Resorts\" and \"Adaaran Hotels and Resorts\".<ref name=\"Aitken Spence Hotel Brands\">{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Hotels Annual Report Brand Attributes 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence Hotels |accessdate=16 June 2018 |url= https://www.aitkenspencehotels.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/ASH1718.pdf}}</ref>\n\n=== Sri Lanka ===\nAitken Spence is currently one of the largest resort operators in Sri Lanka.<ref>{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence results boosted by strong tourism performance |author=  |newspaper= Daily FT |date= 4 February 2011 |accessdate= 28 March 2012 |url= http://www.ft.lk/2011/02/04/aitken-spence-results-boosted-by-strong-tourism-performance |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110209144658/http://www.ft.lk/2011/02/04/aitken-spence-results-boosted-by-strong-tourism-performance/ |archive-date= 9 February 2011 |url-status= dead }}</ref> Also, under the Adaaran brand, is the largest international resort operator in the Maldives.<ref>{{cite news|title= Aitken Spence expands presence in Maldives |author= |newspaper= Daily Mirror |date= 10 June 2015|accessdate=26 June 2017|url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/75755/aitken-spence-expands-presence-in-maldives}}</ref>\n\n==== Heritance Hotels and Resorts ====\n\n===== Heritance Ayurveda Maha Gedara =====\n\nAitken Spence Group first ventured into hospitality sector in 1974, with the opening of Neptune Hotel\u2014designed by [[Geoffrey Bawa|Deshamanya Geoffrey Bawa]]\u2014in [[Beruwala]], Sri Lanka.<ref name=tbl /> In July 2011, the Group rebranded the hotel as Heritance Ayurveda Maha Gedara after a major renovation wherein the hotel was converted to an [[Ayurveda#Sri Lanka|Ayurveda]] wellness resort.<ref>{{cite news |title=Heritance Ayurveda Maha Gedara- opens |newspaper=Daily News |date=17 December 2011 |accessdate=6 March 2012 |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2011/12/17/bus60.asp |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130312122224/http://www.dailynews.lk/2011/12/17/bus60.asp |archive-date=12 March 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2017, Heritance Ayurveda Maha Gedara, was accoladed with the internationally recommended Travelife for Hotels and Accommodations Gold Certification for the hotel's commitment to sustainability and ethical business practices.<ref>{{cite news |title=Heritance Ayurveda Maha Gedara achieves Travelife Gold Certification |newspaper=Daily Mirror |date=12 October 2017 |accessdate=6 March 2018 |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/article/Heritance-Ayurveda-Maha-Gedara-achieves-Travelife-Gold-Certification-138274.html}}</ref> In 2018, Heritance Ayurveda Maha Gedara was recognized by [[:pl:FIT Reisen|FIT Reisen]], a leading provider of health and wellness travel, with the Quality Certificate in the category of \u2018Ayurveda and yoga\u2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Heritance Ayurveda Maha Gedara recognised by Fit Reisen for quality |newspaper=Sri Lanka Travel News |date=27 March 2018 |accessdate=6 May 2018 |url= https://srilankatravelnews.wordpress.com/2018/03/27/heritance-ayurveda-maha-gedara-recognised-by-fit-reisen-for-quality/}}</ref>\n\n===== Heritance Ahungalla =====\nHeritance Ahungalla, formerly known as Triton, is Sri Lanka's first five-star beach resort\u2014launched in 1981 in Ahungalla, a town in southern coastal belt of Sri Lanka.  Originally designed by [[Geoffrey Bawa|Deshamanya Geoffrey Bawa]], the 152 roomed 5 star resort was relaunched under the Heritance brand in June 2006 subsequent to a US$13 million refurbishment.<ref name=hotelAR>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Hotels Annual Report 2010/2011 |author= Aitken Spence |accessdate= 6 March 2012 |url= http://www.aitkenspencehotels.com/images/homepage/141_aitken_spence_hotel_annual_report_2010_2011.pdf |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120417082838/http://www.aitkenspencehotels.com/images/homepage/141_aitken_spence_hotel_annual_report_2010_2011.pdf |archive-date= 17 April 2012 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The hotel is the first hotel in Sri Lanka to receive the ISO 50001 certification for energy management.<ref>{{cite news |title= Heritance Ahungalla, first Sri Lankan hotel to be ISO50001 certified |newspaper= sundaytimes.lk |date= 25 December 2011|accessdate=28 March 2012|url= http://sundaytimes.lk/111225/BusinessTimes/bt38.html }}</ref> The five-star Heritance Ahungalla won the prestigious TUI Top Quality 2018. This was awarded from [[TUI Group]], the largest leisure, travel and tourism company in the world.<ref name=ARKeyEvents/>\n\n===== Heritance Kandalama =====\n[[File:Heritance Kandalama Exterior View.JPG|thumb|x200px|Exterior view of Heritance Kandalama]].\nHeritance Kandalama, is the flagship hotel of Aitken Spence, is located in Kandalama, Dambulla in proximity to two [[World Heritage Site|UNESCO World Heritage Sites]]\u2014 [[Sigiriya]] and [[Dambulla Cave Temple]].<ref name=hotelAR /> The hotel is built into a natural rock outcrop within a jungle setting and overlooks the [[Kandalama Reservoir]].<ref name=hotelAR /> Designed by [[Geoffrey Bawa|Deshamanya Geoffrey Bawa]],<ref>{{cite news|title= Infinite relaxation in Sri Lanka\u2019s cultural triangle|author= |newspaper= Daily FT|date= 4 February 2012|accessdate= 28 March 2012|url= http://www.ft.lk/2012/02/04/infinite-relaxation-in-sri-lankas-cultural-triangle/|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120208190439/http://www.ft.lk/2012/02/04/infinite-relaxation-in-sri-lankas-cultural-triangle/|archive-date= 8 February 2012|url-status= dead}}</ref> it is the first hotel outside the United States to receive [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED certified]].<ref name=hk>{{cite news |title= Heritance crowned most energy efficient hotel chain by bagging Gold, Silver and Bronze Awards |author=  |newspaper= Daily FT |date= 15 August 2011 |accessdate= 28 March 2012 |url= http://www.ft.lk/2011/08/15/heritance-crowned-most-energy-efficient-hotel-chain-by-bagging-gold-silver-and-bronze-awards/ |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110820220444/http://www.ft.lk/2011/08/15/heritance-crowned-most-energy-efficient-hotel-chain-by-bagging-gold-silver-and-bronze-awards/ |archive-date= 20 August 2011 |url-status= dead }}</ref> The hotel was also the first in Asia to be Green Globe certified for its ecotourism best practices.<ref>{{cite news |title= Heritance Kandalama wins EarthCheck Silver certification |newspaper= Daily News |date= 4 February 2012 |accessdate= 28 March 2012 |url= http://www.dailynews.lk/2010/05/18/bus70.asp/ |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100523195438/http://www.dailynews.lk/2010/05/18/bus70.asp |archive-date= 23 May 2010 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===== Heritance Tea Factory =====\nHeritance Tea Factory is a concept hotel wherein a 61-year-old dilapidated tea factory has been remodelled and conserved as a hotel.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.heritancehotels.com/teafactory/our-history.html |title= The origins of Hethersett |author= Aitken Spence |accessdate= 28 March 2012 |archive-url= https://archive.is/20120905152413/http://www.heritancehotels.com/teafactory/our-history.html |archive-date= 5 September 2012 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref>  Located in Heathersett Estate (25 acre tea estate),<ref name=UNESCO>{{cite news|title= Heritance Tea Factory Hotel: An epitome of environmental conscience|author= |newspaper= The Island |date= 11 October 2011|accessdate=28 March 2012|url= http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=36604}}</ref> [[Kandapola]] in the [[Nuwara Eliya]] district, the 5 star resort is considered to be the highest elevated (6,800&nbsp;ft above sea level)<ref name=hotelAR /> luxury hotel in Sri Lanka. Conceptualized by Mr. G. C. Wickremasinghe, a former chairman and current board member of Aitken Spence PLC, and designed by Mr. Nihal Bodhinayake, the hotel came to operation in 1996.<ref name=PATA>{{cite news |title= Heritance Tea Factory only Lankan hotel to win PATA Grand Award in 2012 |author=  |newspaper= Daily FT |date= 27 February 2012 |accessdate= 28 March 2012 |url= http://www.ft.lk/2012/02/27/heritance-tea-factory-only-lankan-hotel-to-win-pata-grand-award-in-2012/ |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140202195844/http://www.ft.lk/2012/02/27/heritance-tea-factory-only-lankan-hotel-to-win-pata-grand-award-in-2012/ |archive-date= 2 February 2014 |url-status= dead }}</ref>  The hotel was awarded the Asia Pacific Heritage Merit Award in 2001 by [[UNESCO]] for preserving the tea factory and its colonial heritage.<ref name=UNESCO /> In February 2012, Heritance Tea Factory was also recognized by the [[Pacific Asia Travel Association]](PATA) with the Grand Award, first Sri Lankan hotel to be so recognized, in the Heritage and Culture category.<ref name=PATA/> In 2014, Heritance Tea Factory's cultivation and processing of tea was certified to Sri Lanka Standards Institute's organic tea certification standards, being the first tea producer to be so certified in Sri Lanka.<ref name=OrganicTeaHTF>{{cite news |title= Heritance Tea Factory first to secure Organic Tea Certification from SLSI |newspaper= Daily FT |date= 27 January 2014 |accessdate= 28 January 2014 |url= http://www.ft.lk/2014/01/27/heritance-tea-factory-first-to-secure-organic-tea-certification-from-slsi/ |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140128065337/http://www.ft.lk/2014/01/27/heritance-tea-factory-first-to-secure-organic-tea-certification-from-slsi/ |archive-date= 28 January 2014 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\n===== Heritance Negombo =====\n\nHeritance [[Negombo]] (formally known as Browns Beach Hotel) was rebranded as Heritance Negombo,.<ref name=HNfactsheet>{{cite web |title= Heritance Negombo Factsheet |author= Aitken Spence |accessdate= 31 January 2015 |url= http://www.heritancehotels.com/negombo/files/2014/12/Heritance-Negombo-Fact-Sheet.pdf }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=HeritanceNegombo1>{{cite news |title= Browns Beach to rebrand as \u2018Heritance Negombo\u2019|newspaper = Ceylon Today |accessdate=20 August 2013 |url= http://www.ceylontoday.lk/22-34678-news-detail-browns-beach-to-rebrand-as-heritance-negombo.html }}</ref> This hotel is the latest to the Heritance portfolio that came on board in 2016. The premium brand portfolio offers novel 'city hotel on the beach' concept, which combines proximity and convenience with a resort ambience.<ref name=HN>{{cite news|title= Heritance Negombo to open next month |newspaper= Daily Mirror |date= 24 March 2016|accessdate= 5 October 2017|url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/107335/Heritance-Negombo-to-open-next-month}}</ref> In March 2016, [[TUI Group]] CEO [[Friedrich Joussen]] visited the 139-room hotel. The historic visit was organized by TUI's joint venture partner in Sri Lanka Aitken Spence Travels.<ref name=CEOTUI>{{cite news|title= World\u2019s largest integrated tourism group CEO visits Heritance Negombo |newspaper= LBO |date= 3 March 2016|accessdate= 13 November 2017|url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/worlds-largest-integrated-tourism-group-ceo-visits-heritance-negombo/}}</ref>\n\n====Turyaa Kalutara====\n\nTuryaa Kalutara is a 200-room property in Waskaduwa, Kalutara, which was formerly known as \"The Sands by Aitken Spence Hotels\", \"Ramada Kalutara\" and \"Golden Sun\". The hotel which initially held 112 rooms was relaunched as Turyaa Kalutara after an addition of new wing to the hotel in November 2015.<ref name=TK>{{cite news|title= Aitken Spence unveils 'turyaa' brand at WTM |newspaper= Daily News |date= 3 November 2015|accessdate=4 November 2015|url= http://www.dailynews.lk/?q=business/aitken-spence-unveils-turyaa-brand-wtm}}</ref> Turyaa Kalutara is a beach-front resort with 200 rooms, equipped with private balconies.<ref name=TuryaaHeritance>{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence launches Turyaa by Heritance |newspaper= The Nation |date= 5 November 2015 |accessdate= 14 December 2016 |url= http://nation.lk/online/2015/11/05/aitken-spence-launches-turyaa-by-heritance.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180618130156/http://nation.lk/online/2015/11/05/aitken-spence-launches-turyaa-by-heritance.html |archive-date= 18 June 2018 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\n==== Aitken Spence Hotels and Resorts ====\n[[File:Earl's Regency Hotel-Kandy Sri Lanka I.jpg|thumb|x200px|Earl's Regency-Kandy]]\nAitken Spence Hotels and Resorts currently operates the following hotels in Sri Lanka: [[Bandarawela Hotel]], Earl's Regency and Earl's Regent- [[Kandy]].<ref name=ASHOTELS>{{cite web |title= Sri Lanka Hotels by Aitken Spence|author= Aitken Spence Hotels |accessdate=14 June 2018 |url= https://www.aitkenspencehotels.com/destinations/sri-lanka.html}}</ref> In 2012, total ownership of Hotel Hilltop Kandy was acquired; however, in 2017, the Group divested its ownership of Hotel Hilltop Kandy<ref name=ASsellsHTK>{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence sells Hill Top Kandy for Rs 740 mn|newspaper= Daily News |accessdate=3 October 2017 |url= http://www.dailynews.lk/2017/09/25/business/129174/aitken-spence-sells-hill-top-kandy-rs-740-mn}}</ref><ref name=HTK>{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence to sell Hotel Hilltop, Kandy for Rs.740mn |newspaper= Daily Mirror |accessdate=17 October 2017 |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/article/Aitken-Spence-to-sell-Hotel-Hilltop-Kandy-for-Rs-mn-137225.html}}</ref> and took on the management of The Regent Kandy, a newly refurbished property with a four-star rating located in the centre of the city.<ref name=ARHOTELS>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Hotels Annual Report 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence Hotels |accessdate=14 June 2018 |url= https://www.aitkenspencehotels.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/ASH1718.pdf}}</ref>\n\nAitken Spence has previously announced its interest to develop its properties in Ahungalla and [[Nilaveli]] as resort properties.<ref name=Nilaveli>{{cite news|title= Sri Lanka Aitken Spence plans eastern resort|newspaper= Lanka Business Online|accessdate= 20 August 2013|url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/sri-lanka-aitken-spence-plans-eastern-resort/1215925252|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131101145327/http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/sri-lanka-aitken-spence-plans-eastern-resort/1215925252|archive-date= 1 November 2013|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=Madhu>{{cite news|title= Six Senses arrives in Ahungalla with Aitken Spence Hotels|newspaper= Daily FT|accessdate= 20 August 2013|url= http://www.ft.lk/2010/10/01/six-senses-arrives-in-ahungalla-with-aitken-spence-hotels/2|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131103100353/http://www.ft.lk/2010/10/01/six-senses-arrives-in-ahungalla-with-aitken-spence-hotels/2/|archive-date= 3 November 2013|url-status= dead}}</ref><ref name=RIU>{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence negotiating deal with Spanish hotel chain for Ahungalla property|newspaper = Daily Mirror |accessdate=30 October 2013 |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/business/other/36142-aitken-spence-negotiating-deal-with-spanish-hotel-chain-for-ahungalla-property-.html}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2013, Aitken Spence announced its plans to enter into a joint venture with Spanish hotel chain [[RIU Hotels]] to build a 500-room, 5-star resort in Ahungalla to be opened in winter 2015.<ref name=RIUjv>{{cite news |title= Sri Lanka's Aitken Spence in resort with Spain's RIU |newspaper= Lanka Business Online |accessdate= 5 November 2013 |url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/sri-lankas-aitken-spence-in-resort-with-spains-riu/235464834 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131105103310/http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/sri-lankas-aitken-spence-in-resort-with-spains-riu/235464834 |archive-date= 5 November 2013 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The business model for the new hotel involves attracting long haul travelers to Sri Lanka through charter flight holiday packages facilitated by [[TUI AG|TUI]]. Model is set on [[Mattala Rajapaksa International Airport]] & [[E01 expressway (Sri Lanka)|Sri Lanka's Southern Expressway]] providing the connectivity for tourists\u2014disembarking from TUI's weekly 787 Dreamliner Charters\u2014to reach the hotel.<ref name=RIUmattala>{{cite news  |title= Mattala Airport and Southern Highway hailed internationally - Adjudged Sri Lanka\u2019s premier tourism products by WTM  |newspaper= The Nation  |accessdate= 24 November 2013  |url= http://www.nation.lk/edition/news-online/item/22635-mattala-airport-and-southern-highway-hailed-internationally-adjudged-sri-lanka%E2%80%99s-premier-tourism-products-by-wtm.html#sthash.IWcBccjE.dpuf  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131202232554/http://www.nation.lk/edition/news-online/item/22635-mattala-airport-and-southern-highway-hailed-internationally-adjudged-sri-lanka%E2%80%99s-premier-tourism-products-by-wtm.html#sthash.IWcBccjE.dpuf  |archive-date= 2 December 2013  |url-status= dead  }}</ref><ref name=TUIriu>{{cite news |title= Mattala TUI to explore new vistas in Sri Lanka tourism |newspaper = Ceylon Today |date= 17 January 2014 |accessdate= 1 February 2014 |url= http://www.ceylontoday.lk/22-53132-news-detail-tui-to-explore-new-vistas-in-sri-lanka-tourism.html}}</ref> In May 2015, Aitken Spence Travels partnered with [[:it: Alpitour|Alpitour Group]] and [[SriLankan Airlines]] to operate charters from Italy to attract 8000 tourists to this all-inclusive, 24-hour-service hotel on a Club Med model.<ref name=AlpitourRiu>{{cite news |title= SL, Spence ink $1.3 m deal with Italy tour firm at Expo 2015 |newspaper= Daily FT |date= 6 May 2015 |accessdate= 8 May 2015 |url= http://www.ft.lk/2015/05/06/sl-spence-ink-1-3-m-deal-with-italy-tour-firm-at-expo-2015/ |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150510033354/http://www.ft.lk/2015/05/06/sl-spence-ink-1-3-m-deal-with-italy-tour-firm-at-expo-2015/ |archive-date= 10 May 2015 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Hotel RIU Sri Lanka came on board with its 501-room partnership venture with Spanish hotel developer and operator [[RIU Hotels]]. Although the majority stake is owned by Aitken Spence Hotel Holdings PLC, day-to-day management is done by RIU Hotels & Resorts.<ref name=RIUResort>{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence Breaks Ground for RIU Resort, Ahungalla date |author= NEWS.LK |accessdate=10 June 2018 |url= https://www.news.lk/news/politics/item/2172-aitken-spence-breaks-ground-for-riu-resort-ahungalla}}</ref><ref name=ARHotelsRIU>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Hotels Annual Report 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence Hotels |accessdate=10 June 2018 |url= https://www.aitkenspencehotels.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/ASH1718.pdf}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Aitken Spence revealed plans to convert the [[Clan House, Galle|Clan House]], former headquarters of Clark Spence & Co. located within [[Galle Fort]], to a 15-room heritage boutique hotel.<ref name=ClanHotels>{{cite news |title= Spence to open new heritage hotel |newspaper= The Nation |accessdate= 6 June 2014 |url= http://www.nation.lk/edition/biz-news/item/30259-spence-to-open-new-heritage-hotel.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140618211717/http://www.nation.lk/edition/biz-news/item/30259-spence-to-open-new-heritage-hotel.html |archive-date= 18 June 2014 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, Aitken Spence acquired a strategic stake in Amethyst Resort, [[Pasikudah|Passikudah]] with the management rights.<ref name=\"ASHar2015\">{{cite web |url= https://www.cse.lk/cmt/upload_report_file/521_1433502972773.pdf |title= Aitken Spence Hotel Holdings PLC Annual Report 2014/2015 |accessdate= 7 June 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Aitken Spence Hotels partnered with [[SriLankan Airlines]]'s [[SriLankan Airlines#Frequent Flyer Programme|FlySmiLes]] loyalty program, which allows frequent flyers on [[Oneworld#Benefits and services|Oneworld]] carriers the opportunity to gain/redeem miles for their stay at any of Aitken Spence's Sri Lankan hotels.<ref name=AsSLpartner>{{cite web |title= More benefits for frequent flyers with FlySmiLes- Aitken Spence partnership  |date= 22 April 2014 |accessdate= 10 May 2014 |url= http://www.srilankan.com/corporate/en_uk/home/news-details/158}}</ref>\n\n==== Aitken Spence School of Hospitality ====\nAitken Spence opened its School of Hospitality in November 2007 at Ahungalla, Sri Lanka with the assistance of the Austrian Chamber of Commerce and Hilfswerk to bridge the skills gap in the tourism sector. The school was initially set up to recover from the Tsunami and assist locals in the Ahungalle region. However, since the ending of the war, the school serves to assist the development in the North and the East as well as other rural areas in the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Aitken Spence trains rural youth in Hospitality Sector |author= |url= http://sundaytimes.lk/100801/BusinessTimes/bt36.html|newspaper= Sunday Times |date= |accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> The school has so far provided training opportunities for marginalized youth from Uva, North Central, East and Northern provinces in food and beverage services.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://aitkenspenceplc.wordpress.com/2010/11/23/aitken-spence-school-of-hospitality-produces-third-batch-of-hospitality-trainees-from-the-east-and-uva/ |title= Aitken Spence School of Hospitality Produces Third Batch of Hospitality Trainees from the East and Uva |author= |date= 23 November 2010 |work= |publisher= |accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.undp.lk/SubPressReleases/Pages/detail.aspx?ItemID=39 |title= 30 youth complete the UNDP-Aitken Spence School of Hospitality supported training in the hospitality industry |author=  |date= 31 May 2012 |work=  |publisher= UNDP |accessdate= 15 October 2012 }}{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 2015, 27 trainees having completed a 3-month basic course in food and beverage, graduated from the Aitken Spence School of Hospitality in Ahungalla.<ref>{{cite news |title=Twenty seven youth graduate from Aitken Spence School of Hospitality |author= |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/65881/twenty-seven-youth-graduate-from-aitken-spence-school-of-hospitality|newspaper= Daily Mirror |date= |accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Maldives ===\nAitken Spence entered Maldivian hotel sector in 1993 with its investment in Bathala Island Resort.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/>  Aitken Spence is also the largest foreign resort operator in the Maldives<ref>{{cite news |title= Sri Lanka's Aitken Spence eye war-torn areas for tourism |url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?nid=206699017 |newspaper= Lanka Business Online |date= 7 August 2009 |accessdate= 22 March 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20121120175231/http://lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?nid=206699017 |archive-date= 20 November 2012 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref> and is among the five largest resort operators in the country.<ref name=bluechip />\n\n==== Adaaran Hotels and Resorts ====\n[[File:Adaaran Club Rannalhi.jpg|thumb|300px|Adaaran Club Rannalhi]]\nBranded as \"Adaaran\",<ref>{{cite news|title=Aitken Spence Hotels re-brands its Maldivian properties|url=http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?nid=839441046|newspaper=Lanka Business Online|date=26 July 2006|accessdate=22 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120429134856/http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?nid=839441046|archive-date=29 April 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the company currently operates 5 hotels in properties located on the islands of Vadoo, [[Meedhupparu]], Rannalhi and Hudhuranfushi.<ref name=hotelAR /><ref name=\"adaaranExpand\">{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence to build new hotel in Maldives |author= Shirajiv SIRIMANE |url= http://www.dailynews.lk/2012/10/11/bus01.asp |newspaper= Daily News |date= 11 October 2012 |accessdate= 11 October 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20121012232146/http://www.dailynews.lk/2012/10/11/bus01.asp |archive-date= 12 October 2012 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===== Adaaran Club Rannalhi =====\nAdaaran Club Rannalhi is a 4 star resort located in Rannalhi, a southern island in the [[Mal\u00e9 Atoll]], with 30 water villas (one of the first resorts to adopt over-water accommodation in Maldives) and 100 beach villas with a room capacity of 132 rooms.<ref name=hotelAR />\n\n===== Adaaran Prestige Vadoo =====\nAdaaran Prestige Vadoo resort, acquired by Aitken Spence in October 2007 is the latest addition to the Group's resorts in Maldives.  Located in close proximity to [[Mal\u00e9]], it houses 50 luxury water villas including six Japanese styled water bungalows.<ref name=\"ARMaritimeCinec\" />\n\n===== Adaaran Select Hudhuran Fushi =====\nAdaaran Select Hudhuran Fushi is a 4 star resort comprising 137 villas that includes 37 luxury villas.<ref name=hotelAR />\n\n===== Adaraan Select Meedhupparu =====\nSituated on Meedhupparu Island in [[Raa Atoll]], Adaaran Select Meedhupparu is a 4 star resort with 215 beach and garden villas.<ref name=hotelAR />\n\n===== Adaraan Prestige Water Villas =====\nAdaaran Prestige Water Villas, also located in the [[Meedhupparu| Meedhupparu Island]], consists of 20 luxury water villas.<ref name=hotelAR />\n\n===== Heritance Aarah =====\nIn March 2015, Aitken Spence acquired \"Aarah\", another island property in Maldives in [[Raa Atoll]], to develop a 163-room, USD $ 50mn resort, having received Maldivian Government's approval to expand buildable area in Maldivian archipelago.<ref name=\"Aarah\">{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence adds another island to Maldivian resort portfolio |author=  |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/65135/aitken-spence-adds-another-island-to-maldivian-resort-portfolio |newspaper= Daily Mirror|date=2 March 2015 |accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ASHrebrand\">{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence plans rebranding hotels |author= Duruthu Edirimuni Chandrasekera |url= http://www.sundaytimes.lk/150301/business-times/aitken-spence-plans-rebranding-hotels-137325.html |newspaper= Sunday Times|date=1 March 2015 |accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"HeritanceBrandAarah\">{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence to Introduce Heritance Brand to Maldives with Aarah Opening 2018 |author=  |url= http://maldives.net.mv/18779/aitken-spence-to-introduce-heritance-brand-to-maldives-with-aarah-opening-2018/ |newspaper= Maldives Insider|date=18 May 2018 |accessdate=18 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nHeritance Aarah from Aitken Spence Hotels will be the group's first \u2018Heritance\u2019 property overseas.<ref name=\"HeritanceAarah\">{{cite news |title= Maldives magic stays |author=  |url= http://www.ttnworldwide.com/Article/278851/_Maldives_magic_stays |newspaper= Travel & Tourism News Middle East|date=18 June 2018 |accessdate=18 June 2018}}</ref> Heritance Aarah is scheduled to open in time for the winter season of 2018.<ref name=\"HeritanceAarahOpening\">{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence to plant first overseas Heritance in the Maldives |author=  |url= https://maldivestimes.com/aitken-spence-to-plant-first-overseas-heritance-in-the-maldives/ |newspaper= Maldives Times|date=10 May 2018 |accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ARMaritimeCinec\" />\n\n===== Raafushi Island =====\nIn May 2015, Aitken Spence obtained the lease for the Raafushi Island in the [[Noonu Atoll]] to build a four star resort.<ref name=\"ASraafushi\">{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence acquires 2 new properties in the Maldives |author=  |url= http://www.ttgasia.com/article.php?article_id=25191 |newspaper= TTG Asia |date= 27 May 2015 |accessdate= 28 May 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150528224028/http://www.ttgasia.com/article.php?article_id=25191 |archive-date= 28 May 2015 |url-status= dead }}</ref><ref name=\"ASraafushiNoonu\">{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence to develop more resorts in Maldives |author= Fathimath Zahuva |url= http://www.haveeru.com.mv/news/60666 |newspaper= Haveeru Online |date= 26 May 2015 |accessdate= 28 May 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150528230835/http://www.haveeru.com.mv/news/60666 |archive-date= 28 May 2015 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== India ===\n\n==== Turyaa Chennai ====\n\nIn June 2014, Aitken Spence announced the purchase of a brand new five star hotel in Chennai.<ref name=ResedaChennai>{{cite news |title= Reseda-The Fern, Chennai five-star hotel sold for Rs 150 crore |newspaper = The Economic Times, India |accessdate= 15 June 2014 |url= http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-06-12/news/50536607_1_chennai-five-star-hotel-occupancy-branded-rooms}}</ref> The company plans to commence operations of this hotel in July 2015 under the brand Turyaa Chennai.<ref name=\"ASHar2015\">{{cite web |url= https://www.cse.lk/cmt/upload_report_file/521_1433502972773.pdf |title= Aitken Spence Hotel Holdings PLC Annual Report 2014/2015 |accessdate= 7 June 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe 140-room property, Turyaa Chennai opened its doors on 1 October 2015 and is located in the IT Corridor of Chennai and just a short drive away from the heart of the city. The property obtained the \u201c5-Star Deluxe\u201d classification in 2017, ranking it as one of five hotels in Chennai to have obtained this highly sought after accreditation. In 2018, the property was awarded the 'best five-star deluxe hotel\u2019 in Tamil Nadu at the Tamil Nadu Tourism Awards 2018.<ref name=TuryaaChennai>{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence Hotels Turyaa Chennai amongst Top Five-Star Hotels in the City |newspaper = LBO |accessdate= 15 June 2017 |url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/aitken-spence-hotels-turyaa-chennai-amongst-top-five-star-hotels-in-the-city/}}</ref><ref name=TuryaaChennaiAward>{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence\u2019s Turyaa Chennai awarded best five-star deluxe in Tamil Nadu |newspaper = Daily FT |accessdate= 8 May 2018 |url= http://www.ft.lk/travel-tourism/Aitken-Spence-s-Turyaa-Chennai-awarded-best-five-star-deluxe-in-Tamil-Nadu/27-654025}}</ref>\n\n=== Oman ===\nIn Oman, Aitken Spence currently owns one hotel and manages five hotels:<ref name=\"OmanHotels\">{{cite news | title = Sri Lanka Spence Hotel mulls more properties in Oman | newspaper = economynext| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 12 June 2015 | url = http://www.economynext.com/Sri_Lanka_Spence_Hotel_mulls_more_properties_in_Oman-3-2062.html |accessdate=11 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== Al Falaj Hotel Muscat ====\n\nAl Falaj Hotel is a 140 roomed 4 star resort located in the city of [[Muscat, Oman|Muscat]]. Aitken Spence bought the hotel from Oman Hotels and Tourism Company for whom the company had been managing the property since 2008.<ref name=hotelAR /><ref name=\"AlFalajPurchase\">{{cite news | title = Aitken Spence\u2019s RO14mn offer for Al Falaj approved | newspaper = Muscat Daily| location = Muscat, Oman | date = 25 January 2016 | url = http://www.muscatdaily.com/Archive/Business/Aitken-Spence-s-RO14mn-offer-for-Al-Falaj-approved-4kiq |accessdate=8 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Al Wadi Hotel, Sohar ====\n\nAl Wadi Hotel is a 79-room 3 star resort in [[Sohar]].<ref name=hotelAR />\n\n==== Desert Nights Camp, Al Wasil ====\n\nDesert Nights Camp is a 5 star tented resort property with 30 Bedouin style tents located in Al Wasil, a township close to Muscat.<ref name=hotelAR />\n\n==== Ruwi Hotel, Muscat ====\n\nLocated in close proximity to Seeb International Airport, Ruwi Hotel is a 3 star hotel with 100 rooms.<ref name=hotelAR />\n\n==== Sur Plaza Hotel, Sur ====\n\nSur Plaza Hotel is a 4 star 95 room resort located in [[Sur, Oman|Sur]] in proximity to Green Turtle Beach at Ras-al-Hadd.<ref name=hotelAR />\n\n==== Jabal Akhdar Hotel, Nizwa ====\n\nJabal Akhdar Hotel is a 26-room boutique hotel located in [[Nizwa]], 152&nbsp;km from the Muscat International Airport.<ref name=\"JabalAkhdar\">{{cite news | title = Aitken Spence in US $ 25mn Indian hotel acquisition | newspaper = Daily Mirror| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 12 June 2014 | url = http://www.dailymirror.lk/business/features/48316-aitken-spence-in-us--25mn-indian-hotel-acquisition.html |accessdate=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Transport ==\n[[File:Hapag Lloyd Container 01.jpg|thumb|x200px | Aitken Spence Logistics offers container shipping]]\nAitken Spence offers integrated transportation services in air-sea freight forwarding, warehousing, distribution, couriers, ground transport and marine. Its services cover the complete physical cargo flow process from shipper to recipient.  It also handles third and fourth party logistics management contracts.<ref name=logistics>{{cite web|title= Aitken Spence Logistic Solutions|author= Aitken Spence|accessdate= 10 August 2012|url= http://www.aitkenspence.com/logistic_solutions/logistic_solutions_provider_sri_lanka.asp|archive-url= https://archive.is/20130116083828/http://www.aitkenspence.com/logistic_solutions/logistic_solutions_provider_sri_lanka.asp|archive-date= 16 January 2013|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> The company also represents [[DB Schenker]] in Sri Lanka and Maldives.<ref name=DBSlogistics>{{cite web |title= DB Schenker announces new forwarding partner in Sri Lanka|author= Lloyds Loading List |accessdate=28 October 2015 |url= http://www.lloydsloadinglist.com/freight-directory/news/DB-Schenker-announces-new-forwarding-partner-in-Sri-Lanka/64608.htm#.VjEHfcUrJdi}}</ref> Also, represents [[DPD Group]] and [[DTDC]] Express in Sri Lanka and Maldives.<ref name=DPDpartner>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence partners DPD Group for courier services. |author= Daily News|accessdate=14 March 2017 |url= http://www.dailynews.lk/2017/03/14/business/110317/aitken-spence-partners-dpd-group-courier-services}}</ref><ref name=DTDCpartner>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence partners with Europe\u2019s second largest int\u2019l parcel delivery network. |author= Mirror Business |accessdate=16 March 2017 |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/article/Aitken-Spence-partners-with-Europe-s-second-largest-int-l-parcel-delivery-network--125591.html}}</ref> The segment represents the cargo GSA for Qatar airways in Sri Lanka and the cargo GSA for Sri Lankan Airlines in Maldives and Myanmar, and are the managing agents for cargo GSA for Sri Lankan Airlines in Bangladesh.<ref name=ASCargoIntConference>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence hosts WACO International Conference in Colombo. |author= Lanka Business Online |accessdate=4 December 2015 |url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/aitken-spence-hosts-waco-international-conference-in-colombo/}}</ref>\n\n=== Cargo consolidation and storage facilities ===\nIn terms of cargo consolidation, the company offers both local and multi country cargo consolidation. In Sri Lanka, it operates its own container freight station with in-house customs that complies with [[Customs-Trade Partnership Against Terrorism|C-TPAT]] standards. Aitken Spence Cargo and Courier services provide air freight, ocean freight, supply chain management, brokerage, project cargo management and international and domestic courier as primary services and also specialize in airline cargo GSA representation [http://aitkenspence.com/logistics-2/cargo-courier-services/ Aitken Spence Logistics]. Aitken Spence Logistics also services shipments of garments through its garments on hanger facilities and quality assurance centre facilities. The company also offers refrigerated storage services in terms of cold rooms and [[Refrigerated container|reefer]] containers to its clients.\n\nWith respect to warehousing facilities in Sri Lanka, Aitken Spence operates a central cargo storage complexses with a total floor area exceeding 300,000 sqft, located in Colombo, Wattala, Mabole and Katunayake Zone with a modern fleet of equipment and cargo handling machinery.<ref name=ARLogisticsHighlights>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Annual Report Logistics 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=10 July 2018 |url= http://aitkenspence.com/annualreport/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Aitken Spence Logistics enhanced by world class equipment |newspaper=Sunday Times |accessdate=4 March 2018 |url= http://www.sundaytimes.lk/180304/business-times/aitken-spence-logistics-enhanced-by-world-class-equipment-283896.html}}</ref>\n\n=== Container handling, repair and modification facilities ===\nThe container services arm of Aitken Spence Logistics that processes a container every two minutes is the first company in Sri Lanka to operate its own container depot (first at Mattakkuliya in 1979 and shifted to Mabole in 1989).<ref name=containerDepot>{{cite web |title= Reliably Consolidated|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=10 August 2012 |url= http://aitkenspenceplc.wordpress.com/tag/mattakuliya/}}</ref> In addition, Aitken Spence also runs a Lloyd's approved facility for container modification and repair services.<ref>{{cite news |title=Aitken Spence Logistics opens new Container Repair and Rigging Facility |newspaper=Sunday Times |date=1 June 2014 |accessdate=3 July 2018  |url= http://www.sundaytimes.lk/140601/business-times/aitken-spence-logistics-opens-new-container-repair-and-rigging-facility-100546.html}}</ref>\n\nThe company provides import and export container handling services, handling transshipment cargo, and the servicing of passenger cruise vessels, car carriers and casual callers.<ref name=ARShipping>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Annual Report 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=18 June 2018 |url= http://aitkenspence.com/annualreport/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Aitken Spence Logistics pursues continuous fleet enhancement |newspaper=Daily News |date=2 March 2018 |accessdate=30 May 2018 |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2018/03/02/business/144345/aitken-spence-logistics-pursues-continuous-fleet-enhancementy }}{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n=== Ground transport and project cargo handling ===\nAitken Spence also offers transportation through its transport fleet of prime movers with 20\u2019/40\u2019 trailers, lorries and tank trucks.<ref name=logistics /> The Group is also capable in handling Heavy Over-Dimensional Project cargo. It is also the agent for Flexi Tank Services in Sri Lanka for Trans Ocean Distribution.<ref name=logistics />\n\n=== Freight forwarding, courier services and air cargo ===\n[[File:Stern of the Colombo Express.jpg|thumb|x200px|Hapag Lloyd is represented in Sri Lanka through Aitken Spence Maritime]]\nIn addition to its own haulage, Aitken Spence also provides freight forwarding through its global partner network. Aitken Spence Cargo, specialized freight-forwarding arm of Aitken Spence, provides air freight, sea freight, brokerage, customs facilitation and supply chain [[solution]]s to clients in Sri Lanka, Bangladesh and Maldives.<ref name=logistics />\n\nAitken Spence handles cargo sales agencies for [[Singapore Airlines Cargo]], [[Air Jamaica]], [[Thomas Cook Airlines Scandinavia|My Travels]], [[Qatar Airways Cargo]] and [[EVA Air]] in Sri Lanka. It is also the General Sales Agents (Cargo) for My Travels in Maldives & Bangladesh; Livingston Air in Bangladesh, Singapore and Thailand; [[Continental Airlines Cargo]] in Bangladesh, while being the cargo sales agents for [[SriLankan Airlines#Cargo|SriLankan Airlines Cargo]] in the Maldives.\n\nAitken Spence Group represents [[TNT Express]] courier services in Sri Lanka and provides both domestic and international courier services. It also represents Spring Global Mail in Sri Lanka.<ref name=logistics />\n\n=== Maritime services ===\nAitken Spence offers services in the maritime sector through its maritime wing, Aitken Spence Maritime. Its services include liner agency representation (of G6 Alliance), cruise vessel representation, feeder and casual caller representation, break bulk facilities, and ship servicing and facilitation (crew services, bunkering, repairs, supply of provisions) for ports in Sri Lanka.  It also provides ship chartering services.<ref name=logistics />\n\nIn January 2005, in a joint venture with Ceyline Holdings, Aitken Spence re-entered the ship owning for time charter business in order to profit from the then shipping boom.<ref name=ShipOwning>{{cite web|title= Aitken Spence to invest $ 7.5 million on two vessels.|author= Daily News|accessdate= 16 May 2013|url= http://www.dailynews.lk/2004/12/09/bus02.html|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20050219074029/http://www.dailynews.lk/2004/12/09/bus02.html|archive-date= 19 February 2005|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=ShipOwning2>{{cite web |title= Spence to double fleet to 10 ships. |author= Sunday Times|accessdate=16 May 2013 |url= http://www.sundaytimes.lk/050626/ft/2.html}}</ref> In 2007, with the saturation of the ship chartering market, Aitken Spence exited the ship owning business and shifted its strategic focus to expanding its port management business. \n<ref name=ShipDivesting>{{cite web |title= Sri Lanka conglomerate sells off ships |author= Lanka Business Online |accessdate= 16 May 2013 |url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/Sri_Lanka_conglomerate_sells_off_ships/424491405 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131216211915/http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/Sri_Lanka_conglomerate_sells_off_ships/424491405 |archive-date= 16 December 2013 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=PortManagement>{{cite web|title= Sri Lanka's Aitken Spence hunts port management business|author= Lanka Business Online|accessdate= 16 May 2013|url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/Sri_Lankas_Aitken_Spence_hunts_port_management_business/1347781965|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130513065245/http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/Sri_Lankas_Aitken_Spence_hunts_port_management_business/1347781965|archive-date= 13 May 2013|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Aitken Spence in partnership with [[PSA International|Port of Singapore Authority]] submitted a joint bid to build and operate the South Container Terminal of the [[Colombo Harbor#Expansion project|Colombo Port Expansion Project]]. When the initial bidding process of [[Sri Lanka Port Authority]] (SLPA) stalled and was reactivated, Aitken Spence partnered with [[China Merchants Holdings (International)|China Merchant Holdings International]] and was the sole bidder in support of the project.<ref name=SouthPortBid1>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence port bid in our national interest |author= The Sunday Times|accessdate=16 May 2013 |url= http://www.sundaytimes.lk/080302/FinancialTimes/ft334.html}}</ref><ref name=SouthPortBid2>{{cite web |title= A wise call on Colombo South Port |author= The Sunday Times|accessdate=8 December 2013 |url= http://www.sundaytimes.lk/090830/FinancialTimes/ft39.html}}</ref> In 2010, the bid was approved by SLPA and construction began on the US$450 million project.<ref name=PortProject>{{cite web |title= Sri Lanka awards Rs. 50 bn Colombo South Port deal to China Holdings - Aitken Spence consortium  |author= Asian Tribune |accessdate=16 May 2013 |url= http://www.asiantribune.com/news/2010/09/17/sri-lanka-awards-rs-50-bn-colombo-south-port-deal-china-holdings-aitken-spence-conso}}</ref><ref name=PortProject2>{{cite web|title= Deal signed to build Colombo Port Expansion project\u2019s South Container Terminal|author= Daily FT|accessdate= 16 May 2013|url= http://www.ft.lk/2011/11/14/deal-signed-to-build-colombo-port-expansion-project%E2%80%99s-south-container-terminal/|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131212151153/http://www.ft.lk/2011/11/14/deal-signed-to-build-colombo-port-expansion-project%E2%80%99s-south-container-terminal/|archive-date= 12 December 2013|url-status= dead}}</ref>  However, in 2012, citing cost escalations and changes in financing requirements, Aitken Spence sold its stake to CMHI in 2012, realizing a LKR Rs. 630 million capital gain.<ref name=cmbPortExit>{{cite web |title= Sri Lanka conglomerate sells stake on Colombo Port project for Rs. 630 million|author= Lanka Newspapers|accessdate=16 May 2013 |url= http://www.lankanewspapers.com/news/2012/1/74081.html}}</ref><ref name=cmbPortExit2>{{cite news |title= Sri Lanka's Aitken Spence sells port stake to China Merchants |author= Reuters|accessdate=16 May 2013 |url= http://uk.reuters.com/article/2012/01/23/srilanka-port-spence-idUKL4E8CN4PO20120123 |date=23 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nAitken Spence is the first Sri Lankan company to venture into port efficiency improvement, training and container terminal management overseas with its operations in the African continent.<ref name=logistics /> As a result of the strategic partnership with the Port of Durban from 2006, Aitken Spence won a \"ship planning and mentoring\" project covering the Ports of Durban, Cape Town and Ngqura in South Africa in 2010. In 2011, Aitken Spence announced that it has won a deal to improve the efficiency of Port of Nacala in Mozambique.<ref name=PortEfficiency>{{cite web|title= Sri Lanka Aitken Spence to make Mozambique port efficient.|author= Lanka Business Online|accessdate= 10 August 2012|url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?nid=1702158326|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20121123224538/http://lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?nid=1702158326|archive-date= 23 November 2012|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> In 2013, Aitken Spence took over the management of two Fijian ports, [[Suva]] and [[Lautoka]], with its purchase of 51% of Fiji Ports Terminal Ltd, a 100% owned subsidiary of Fiji Ports Corporation Ltd.<ref name=\"fijiPortMgmt\"/><ref name=FijiPort/><ref name=fijiEfficiency>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence aims to get port efficiency, productivity. |author= Fiji Sun|accessdate=4 August 2013 |url= http://www.fijisun.com.fj/2013/08/01/aitken-spence-aims-to-get-port-efficiency-productivity/}}</ref> The company further consolidated its presence in the Fijian maritime sector in acquiring a 20% stake in Fiji Ports Corporation Ltd. in November 2015.<ref name=\"fijiPortCorp\">{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence buys 20% stake in Fiji Ports Corp for $ 16 m; expands footprint in South Pacific   |author= Daily FT|accessdate=6 November 2015 |url= http://www.ft.lk/article/493071/Aitken-Spence-buys-20--stake-in-Fiji-Ports-Corp-for---16-m--expands-footprint-in-South-Pacific}}</ref><ref name=ASFiji>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence expands Fiji operations   |author= Mirror Business|accessdate=6 November 2015 |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/94255/aitken-spence-expands-fiji-operations}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Aitken Spence renewed its alliance with Ceyline Group of Companies when it invested in [[CINEC|Colombo International Nautical and Engineering College (CINEC)]].<ref name=CINEC1>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence in strategic partnership with CINEC Maritime Campus. |author= The Nation|accessdate=16 May 2013 |url= http://www.nation.lk/2010/04/11/busi5.htm}}</ref><ref name=CINEC2>{{cite web|title= Sri Lanka Aitken Spence mulls overseas maritime campus.|author= Lanka Business Online|accessdate= 16 May 2013|url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/sri-lanka-aitken-spence-mulls-overseas-maritime-campus/1064979551|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131216211313/http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/sri-lanka-aitken-spence-mulls-overseas-maritime-campus/1064979551|archive-date= 16 December 2013|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> In 2012, Aitken Spence increased its stake in CINEC from 10% to 40% in a move to further strengthen its maritime portfolio.<ref name=CINEC3>{{cite web|title= Sri Lanka Aitken Spence December net up 41-pct|author= Lanka Business Online|accessdate= 16 May 2013|url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/Sri_Lanka_Aitken_Spence_December_net_up_41-pct/888547756|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130514123329/http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/Sri_Lanka_Aitken_Spence_December_net_up_41-pct/888547756|archive-date= 14 May 2013|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> Located in Malabe, the CINEC Campus is Sri Lanka's largest private higher education institution and also has branches in\nColombo, Trincomalee and Jaffna. CINEC also manages the maritime academies in Fiji and Seychelles.<ref name=ARMaritimeCinec>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Annual Report 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=18 June 2018 |url= http://aitkenspence.com/annualreport/}}</ref> In 2013, further to Aitken Spence's entry into port management in Fiji, Fijian Government announced plans to invite CINEC to manage [[Fiji National University|Fiji National University's]] maritime school.<ref name=AScinecFiji>{{cite web |title=Aitken Spence boosts Fiji Port efficiencies by 35 pc in two months |author=Daily News |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/business/aitken-spence-boosts-fiji-port-efficiencies-35-pc-two-months#sthash.ENSNHQBs.dpuf |accessdate=15 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216211854/http://www.dailynews.lk/business/aitken-spence-boosts-fiji-port-efficiencies-35-pc-two-months#sthash.ENSNHQBs.dpuf |archive-date=16 December 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=CINECfnu>{{cite web |title= 2014 Fiji National Budget Speech by PM Commodore Voreqe Bainimarama |author= Mai Life Magazine|accessdate=22 November 2013 |url= http://www.mailife.com.fj/2013/11/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Cinec unveils ship shaped training facility on campus|newspaper=Hiru News |date=15 July 2015 |accessdate=26 March 2017  |url= http://www.hirunews.lk/business/113212/cinec-unveils-ship-shaped-training-facility-on-campus}}</ref>\n\n== Services ==\nIn the services sector, Aitken Spence operates in a number of key domains: inbound tourism, outbound travel, airline agencies, conventions and exhibitions, elevator agency, financial services, insurance, business and knowledge process outsourcing and luxury lifestyle [[solution]]s.{{clarify|date=September 2018}}<ref name=services>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Services|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=10 May 2017 |url= http://aitkenspence.com/services/}}</ref>\n\n=== Destination management ===\n[[File:SIA Boeing 747-400, 9V-SPF, SIN 5.jpg|thumb|x200px |Aitken Spence has represented Singapore Airlines in Sri Lanka since 1972]]\nWith regards to inbound tourism sector, Aitken Spence Travels \u2013 a joint venture with [[TUI Travel|TUI]]\u2014is the largest [[destination management company]] in Sri Lanka representing over 200 international tour operators, and has been recognized with Sri Lanka's Presidential Award for the Best Destination Management Company and leading Destination Management Company at the World Travel Awards in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |title=Aitken Spence Travels, Lanka\u2019s leading DMC at World Travel Awards |newspaper=Daily News |date=8 August 2017 |accessdate=6 March 2018 |url= http://www.dailynews.lk/2017/08/08/business/124447/aitken-spence-travels-lanka%E2%80%99s-leading-dmc-world-travel-awards}}</ref><ref name=servicestravels>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Services Destination Management|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=10 October 2017 |url= http://aitkenspence.com/services/travels/}}</ref> The outbound travel arm of Aitken Spence Travels is an [[IATA]] approved outbound travel agency and has been in operation since 1975, making it one of the oldest IATA agencies in Sri Lanka. In addition to its core business of airline ticketing, it is also the general sales agent for [[Rail Europe, Inc.]] and Tradewinds. Aitken Spence Travels is also the representative in Sri Lanka for [[CWT (company)|CWT]], a global [[travel management company]].<ref name=services /> Aitken Spence is also the preferred partner of [[The Emirates Group#Travel|Emirates Holidays]] in Sri Lanka.<ref name=SpenEmirates>{{cite web |title= In-bound tourist traffic provokes Emirates and Aitken Spence to enhance visitor convenience |newspaper= The Island|accessdate=24 November 2013 |url= http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=92557}}</ref> In financial year 2017/2018, Aitken Spence Travels handled over 178,000 tourists to Sri Lanka.<ref name=178Kvisitors>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Travels records landmark 178,000 happy visitors to Sri Lanka|newspaper= Daily FT|accessdate=18 May 2018 |url= http://www.ft.lk/travel-tourism/Aitken-Spence-Travels-records-landmark-178-000-happy-visitors-to-Sri-Lanka/27-655376}}</ref>\n\n=== Event management and MICE ===\n\nAitken Spence Conventions & Exhibitions is the event management arm of the Aitken Spence PLC and is specialized in organizing Meetings, Incentives, Conferences & Exhibitions in Sri Lanka and the Maldives.[http://aitkenspenceconventions.com/ Aitken Spence Conventions & Exhibitions]<ref name=Conventions>{{cite web|title= Focus on regional markets for international parleys|newspaper= The Sunday Observer|accessdate= 24 November 2013|url= http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2008/02/17/fin14.asp|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131202222832/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2008/02/17/fin14.asp|archive-date= 2 December 2013|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=ASexhibitions>{{cite web |title= \nAitken Spence bags top Travel Awards |newspaper= Daily Mirror|accessdate=24 November 2013 |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/travel/business-travel/21617-aitken-spence-bags-top-travel-awards-.html}}</ref><ref name=ASexhibition>{{cite web |title= \nAitken Spence Conventions & Exhibitions to coordinate conference  |newspaper= The Island|accessdate=12 March 2014 |url= http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=99438}}</ref> The company also represents Pacific World MICE company in Sri Lanka and the Maldives.<ref name=PacificWorld>{{cite web |title= \nPacific World Expands Presence To Sri Lanka And Maldives With Aitken Spence  |newspaper= Daily Mirror|accessdate=21 November 2014 |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/56907/pacific-world-expands-presence-to-sri-lanka-and-maldives-with-aitken-spence}}</ref>\n\n=== Airline agency ===\nIn terms of airline agency services, Aitken Spence acts as the General Sales Agent for [[Singapore Airlines|Singapore International Airlines]] in Sri Lanka and the Maldives. Aitken Spence is also the General Sales Agent for [[SriLankan Airlines]] in Maldives.<ref name=services />\n\n=== Financial services ===\nIn the financial services sector, Aitken Spence in a joint venture with Mercantile Merchant Bank, Sri Lanka offers [[Western Union|Western Union Money Transfer services]] in Sri Lanka with a network of over 2000 sub-agent locations countrywide, which includes banks, financial institutions and retail outlets.<ref name=services /> As an authorized agent for Western Union in Sri Lanka, the Group's money transfer services business has a commanding 65% share of the Western Union business in Sri Lanka.<ref name=ARServicesWU>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Annual Report 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=11 July 2018 |url= http://aitkenspence.com/annualreport/}}</ref>\n\nAitken Spence serves as survey and claim settling agents for [[Lloyd's of London]] since 1876, covering the commercial ports in Sri Lanka and the Republic of Maldives. It also carries out quality surveys and hull and machinery surveys. In addition, Aitken Spence Insurance also acts as survey and claims settling agents for several other reputed insurance companies worldwide including [[Aviva|AVIVA]], [[People's Insurance Company of China]], Oriental Insurance Co. of India, [[New India Assurance]], [[IFFCO Tokio General Insurance Company Limited|Iffco-Tokio]] of India, [[RSA Insurance Group|Royal & Sun Alliance Group]], Northern Marine Underwriters, China Pacific Property Insurance Co. Ltd, [[Mitsui Sumitomo Insurance Group|Sumitomo Fire & Marine Insurance Co. Ltd.]], [[Tokio Marine Nichido|Tokyo Marine & Fire Insurance Co.]] of Japan, Cesam of France, QBE Insurance of Singapore and [[American Home Assurance Company]] since 1949.<ref name=services />\n\n=== Knowledge and information technology ===\nThe Group also provides human resources consulting in Sri Lanka and overseas under brand \"Genuity\".<ref name=services />\n\nAitken Spence Technologies offers IT in, [[Enterprise Content Management]] (ECM), [[Enterprise Resource Planning]] (ERP), both based on core-[[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]] Applications and Technologies, and Application Development based on Open Source/Java technologies.<ref name=IT>{{cite web|title= Calspence Technologies consolidates and re-brands|author= FT Sri Lanka|accessdate= 10 August 2012|url= http://www.ft.lk/2012/02/23/calspence-technologies-consolidates-and-re-brands/|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131019161750/http://www.ft.lk/2012/02/23/calspence-technologies-consolidates-and-re-brands/|archive-date= 19 October 2013|url-status= dead}}</ref><ref name=KiaEBS>{{cite web|title= Kia with Aitken Spence to deploy Oracle Solution to automate processes.|author= Lanka Business Today|accessdate= 19 May 2015|url= http://www.lankabusinesstoday.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=9106:kia-with-aitken-spence-to-deploy-oracle-solution-to-automate-processes&catid=54:business&Itemid=76}}{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 2012, Aitken Spence was appointed as [[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]] University Education Re-seller Partner and Approved Training Centre.<ref name=OracleUni>{{cite web|title= Aitken Spence Technologies appointed Oracle Uni approved re-seller partner, training centre.|author= FT Sri Lanka|accessdate= 4 June 2013|url= http://www.ft.lk/2012/03/03/aitken-spence-technologies-appointed-oracle-uni-approved-re-seller-partner-training-centre/|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130604100005/http://www.ft.lk/2012/03/03/aitken-spence-technologies-appointed-oracle-uni-approved-re-seller-partner-training-centre/|archive-date= 4 June 2013|url-status= dead}}</ref> Aitken Spence Technologies is also a member of [[IBM|IBM PartnerWorld]] program.<ref name=IBM>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Technologies |accessdate=15 October 2013 |url= http://www.aitkenspencetech.com/}}</ref> In October 2013, '''PlantERM''', the Enterprise Resource Management application developed for the first time in Sri Lanka for the plantation sector by Aitken Spence Technologies, received the NBQSA Gold Award in the General Applications category.<ref name=NBQSA2013>{{cite web |title= NBQSA 2013 Winners |accessdate=18 October 2013 |url= http://www.nbqsasrilanka.org/node/75/}}</ref>\n\nAitken Spence offers financcial accounting outsourcing services through its subsidiary Aitken Spence Business Solutions in Sri Lanka, Maldives and Bangladesh. The business solutions partners include; Citi Bank, HSBC, Deutsche Bank and Standard Chartered Bank on the electronic banking and Oracle in the ERP solutions.<ref name=BPO>{{cite web|title= Aitken Spence to ride on BPO boom.|author= FT Sri Lanka|accessdate= 10 August 2012|url= http://www.ft.lk/2011/03/22/aitken-spence-to-ride-on-bpo-boom/|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110426121733/http://www.ft.lk/2011/03/22/aitken-spence-to-ride-on-bpo-boom/|archive-date= 26 April 2011|url-status= dead}}</ref><ref name=Spencebpo>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Business Solutions |accessdate=15 October 2013 |url= http://www.spencebpo.com/3-services.html}}</ref>[https://aitkenspence.com/services/financial-accounting-outsourcing/ Aitken Spence Business Solutions]\n\n=== Elevator agency ===\n\nAitken Spence also provides elevator services acting as the agent for [[Otis Elevator Company|OTIS]] Elevators (part of [[United Technologies Corporation]]) in Sri Lanka and Maldives since 1989.<ref name=services />\n\n==Strategic investments==\n\n===Power generation===\n\nAitken Spence first entered the power sector in 1996 in a joint venture with a Japanese investor to build two thermal power plants in Sri Lanka<ref name=\"jvjp\"/> with the Government of Sri Lanka inviting private sector to invest in resolving the then power crisis. However, due to the longevity of the process in obtaining clearances, the Japanese partner backed out and in 1999, Aitken Spence (51%) partnered with [[Commonwealth Development Corporation]] Globeleq (29%), Baneras House of India (10%) and [[Wartsila|Wartsila Finland Oy]] (10%) to construct the [[Ace Matara Power Station]] (24.4MW) and [[Ace Horana Power Station]] (24.4MW).<ref name=\"hnb\">{{cite news | title = HNB leads landmark financing deal of US$ 88 million | newspaper = The Sunday Leader| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 10 August 2003 | url = http://www.thesundayleader.lk/archive/20030810/business-3.htm| accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref> Subsequently, following a Request for Proposal by [[Ceylon Electricity Board]] (CEB) in February 2002, Aitken Spence together with [[Caterpillar Inc.|Caterpillar Power Ventures Corporation]] began the construction of the [[Embilipitiya Power Station]] (100MW), which came online in April 2005.<ref name=\"hnb\" /><ref name=\"cat\">{{cite web |url= http://www.cat.com/cda/files/698809/7/CPGS_SriLanka.pdf |title= Ace Power Embilipitiya |accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nAce Power Embilipitiya thermal power plant opeartes on a 100MW while the Branford Hydro power plant operates at 2.5MW, Ace Wind power plant at 3MW  and Western Power at 10MW capacity.<ref name=ARACEPOWER>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Annual Report 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=10 July 2018 |url= http://aitkenspence.com/annualreport/}}</ref> The Power Purchase Agreement (PPA) between the [[Ceylon Electricity Board]] and Ace Power Embilipitiya lapsed in 2015; however, renewed the agreement for a one more year in April, 2016, when the country ran into power crisis after two back-to-back blackouts in late 2015 and early 2016. During the first quarter of 2018, the government decided to extend the purchasing of the thermal power for three more years as the country had four seasons of back-to-back dry spells, which exhausted reservoirs and the crucial catchment areas.<ref name=\"acepower\">{{cite web |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/article/Government-extends-agreement-with-Ace-Power-for-three-more-years-to-avert-power-crisis-148133.html |title= Government extends agreement with Ace Power for three more years to avert power crisis |newspaper = Mirror Business |accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:AitkenSpenceWindPower-Ambewela-September2012-1.jpg|thumb|x200px|Ace Wind Power, Ambewela]]\n\n====Hydro, Wind, Solar, Waste-to-Energy and Dendro Power====\n\nAitken Spence has also sought to diversify its power portfolio with increased presence in the clean and renewable energy domain in Sri Lanka.\n\nAitken Spence Power has already completed construction of the 2.5 MW '''Branford Hydro Power''' Plant in Matale, and of [[Ambewela Aitken Spence Wind Farm|Ace Wind Power]] power plant in [[Ambewela]]<ref name=\"renew\">{{cite news|title=Blue chips eye more hydro, wind power plants |newspaper=Daily News |location=Colombo, Sri Lanka |date=8 June 2011 |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2011/06/08/bus05.asp |accessdate=9 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110823125438/http://www.dailynews.lk/2011/06/08/bus05.asp |archivedate=23 August 2011 }}</ref> that has an installed capacity of 3 MW. Both power plants were connected to the national grid during 2012/13 financial year.<ref name=\"ASar2012\">{{cite web|title= Aitken Spence PLC Annual Report 2011/2012|author= Aitken Spence|accessdate= 9 October 2012|url= http://www.aitkenspence.com/pdf/ar2012/aitken_spence_plc_ar_2011_12_changed_1.pdf|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130512213943/http://www.aitkenspence.com/pdf/ar2012/aitken_spence_plc_ar_2011_12_changed_1.pdf|archive-date= 12 May 2013|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> Aitken Spence Power is also currently building the [[Aitken Spence Power Station]], Waste-To-Energy Coprocessing Plant at Muthurajawela.<ref name=\"coprocessing\">{{cite news| title = Garbage Power At Rs. 22 A Unit| newspaper = The Sunday Leader| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka| date = 13 November 2011| url = http://www.thesundayleader.lk/2011/11/13/garbage-power-at-rs-22-a-unit/| accessdate = 9 October 2012| archive-url = https://archive.is/20130218220708/http://www.thesundayleader.lk/2011/11/13/garbage-power-at-rs-22-a-unit/| archive-date = 18 February 2013| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAce Power embarked on a landmark project in the country's waste to energy sphere. Seen as a vital and much needed solution for the waste disposal crisis within Colombo city limits, the proposed project involves the construction of a 10MW waste-toenergy plant at Muthurajawela. The plant will be fuelled by waste collected from the Colombo Municipal Area, which was previously dumped in Meethotamulla. The plant is equipped to convert between 600 \u2013 800 metric tonnes of municipal solid waste daily to electricity. Estimated to cost Rs. 13 billion on completion, the project is funded through a combination of equity and term loan funding. The construction work on the project commenced following the ground-breaking ceremony held in August 2017 with the participation of the president. This new waste to energy project is due to commence commercial operations in 2019.<ref name=\"wastetoenergy\">{{cite news | title = Sri Lanka starts work on two 10MW waste-to-energy plants | newspaper = Economy Next | date = 10 August 2017 | url = http://www.economynext.com/Sri_Lanka_starts_work_on_two_10MW_waste_to_energy_plants-3-8486-.html}}</ref><ref name=\"wastetoenergyplant\">{{cite news | title = HNB concludes Syndicated Term Loan for Sri Lanka\u2019s first waste to energy plant | newspaper = Lanka Business Online | date = 31 May 2018 | url = http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/hnb-concludes-syndicated-term-loan-for-sri-lankas-first-waste-to-energy-plant/}}</ref>\n\nAitken Spence Hotels (through biomass plants and solar generation)<ref name=\"hotelrenew\">{{cite news | title = Sri Lanka's Aitken Spence in renewable energy drive | newspaper = Lanka Business Online | location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 5 October 2012 | url = http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?nid=2104555452 | accessdate = 9 October 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121102014945/http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?nid=2104555452 | archive-date = 2 November 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> and Plantations (through mini hydro projects)<ref name=\"plantationHydro\">{{cite news | title = Elpitiya Plantations recognised for hydro power generation | newspaper = ft.lk | location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 13 August 2012 | url = http://www.ft.lk/2012/08/13/elpitiya-plantations-recognised-for-hydro-power-generation/ | accessdate = 9 October 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120815024257/http://www.ft.lk/2012/08/13/elpitiya-plantations-recognised-for-hydro-power-generation/ | archive-date = 15 August 2012 | url-status = dead }}</ref> have also undertaken mini power projects of their own. Heritance Ayurveda Maha Gedara is the first hotel in Sri Lanka to enter into a net metering agreement with CEB.<ref name=\"hotelrenew\"/>\n\n===Plantation services===\n[[File:Dunsinane Estate, Elpitiya Plantation.jpg|thumb|left| Dunsinane Estate, Nuwara Eliya]]\nAitken Spence has been in the plantations industry from the early 1900s.<ref name=\"superbrand\">{{cite web |url= http://www.superbrands.com/lkb1/pdf/aitkenspence.pdf |title= Aitken Spence |accessdate= 9 October 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131216212024/http://www.superbrands.com/lkb1/pdf/aitkenspence.pdf |archive-date= 16 December 2013 |url-status= dead }}</ref> In 1975, the estates originally owned by Aitken Spence were acquired under the plantation nationalization program. In 1992, with the re-privatization of plantations industry, Aitken Spence reentered the sector in taking over the management of Udapussellawa Plantation PLC. It also invested in a minority stake in Talawakelle Plantations. Aitken Spence later divested its stake in Udapussellawa and Talawakelle Plantations<ref name=\"talawakelle\">{{cite news | title = Talawakelle posts record profit and turnover| newspaper = The Island| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka| date = 2 April 2011 | url = http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=22230| accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe management of Elpitiya Plantations PLC was taken over by Aitken Spence in 1997 from Carsons through Aitken Spence Plantations Managements Ltd. The Group currently manages 13 estates (with over 8800 hectares of cultivated land) in Sri Lanka, producing high, mid and low grown teas.<ref name=ARplantationssummary>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Annual Report 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=5 June 2018 |url= http://aitkenspence.com/annualreport/}}</ref> From the 13 estates, six estates are located on the up cluster in [[Kandy]] and [[Nuwara Eliya]] districts (estates: Dunsinane, Sheen, Fernlands, Meddecombra, New Peacock and Nayapane) and seven estates in the low cluster (Deviturai, Talgaswella, Gulugahakanda, Lelwala, Ketandola, Bentota and Elpitiya). These estates conform with multiple standards on sustainability\nincluding ISO 22000 for food safety management system, [[Rainforest Alliance|Rainforest Alliance certification]], [[Ethical Tea Partnership]] and [[Forest Stewardship Council]] certification.<ref name=\"EthicalTea\">{{cite news | title = Sri Lanka's New Peacock Estate claim highest yield among large tea farms| newspaper = economynext | location = Colombo, Sri Lanka| date = 22 April 2015 | url = http://www.economynext.com/Sri_Lanka_s_New_Peacock_Estate_claim_highest_yield_among_large_tea_farms-3-1586-9.html| accessdate=22 April 2015}}</ref> In addition to tea, Elpitiya Plantations also produces rubber, coconut, cinnamon and palm oil.<ref name=\"ARplantations\">{{cite web |url= http://aitkenspence.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Aitken-Spence-PLC-AR-2017-18.pdf |title= Annual Report Strategic Investments Plantations |accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nGroup has diversified its plantation operations into other areas such as palm oil processing, hydro power development, speciality tea manufacturing and eco tourism.\n\nThe Group also has its own tea brand for black tea and green tea in Sri Lanka under the name \"Harrow Ceylon Choice\".\n\nIn January 2013, Elpitiya Plantations PLC entered a joint venture with Dianhong International Limited, Hong Kong, a subsidiary of Yunnan Dianhong Group Company Limited of China, to grow and process tea in Sri Lanka for Chinese Speciality Tea market.<ref name=\"TeaBoI\">{{cite news | title = New BoI project signed to produce tea for Chinese market| newspaper = Ceylon Today | location = Colombo, Sri Lanka| date = 25 January 2013 | url = http://www.ceylontoday.lk/22-22854-news-detail-new-boi-project-signed-to-produce-tea-for-chinese-market.html| accessdate=9 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"TeaDYGCL\">{{cite news| title = Lankan Tea taps Chinese investment| newspaper = The Nation| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka| date = 27 January 2013| url = http://www.nation.lk/edition/biz-news/item/15069-lankan-tea-taps-chinese-investment.html| accessdate = 9 October 2013| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131014173926/http://www.nation.lk/edition/biz-news/item/15069-lankan-tea-taps-chinese-investment.html| archive-date = 14 October 2013| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, shares of Aitken Spence Plantation Managements Ltd was introduced to the Colombo Stock Exchange.<ref name=\"aspmCSE\">{{cite news| title = Aitken Spence Sri Lanka plantation unit to be listed| newspaper = Lanka Business Online| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka| date = 4 April 2013| url = http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/Aitken_Spence_Sri_Lanka_plantation_unit_to_be_listed/1644914590| accessdate = 9 October 2013| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131216201050/http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/Aitken_Spence_Sri_Lanka_plantation_unit_to_be_listed/1644914590| archive-date = 16 December 2013| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Garment manufacturing===\n\nAitken Spence entered the garments manufacturing sector in 1979<ref name=\"garmentsweb\" /> with its factory at Mattakkuliya.<ref name=\"mattakkuliyagarments\">{{cite news | title = Maldivian link saves the day for Aitken Spence| newspaper = Sunday Times| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 18 February 2001 | url = http://sundaytimes.lk/010218/busm.html| accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref> Currently, Aitken Spence operates two factories in Sri Lanka\u2014in [[Matugama]] (opened in 1993 in support of the 200 garment factories initiative of the then Government of Sri Lanka)<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/> and at Koggala Export Processing Zone (since 2008)<ref name=\"koggalaopen\">{{cite news | title = Aitken Spence Q3profit up by 16% to Rs 1.9b| newspaper = The Island| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 14 February 2008 | url = http://www.island.lk/2008/02/14/business7.html | accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref>\u2014that manufactures and exports clothing for clients such as [[The Gap, Inc.]], [[Columbia Sportswear]], [[Kohl's]] and [[Sears]] in the US, and [[Marks & Spencer]] Work Wear, [[Sainsbury's]], [[Tesco]], [[Waitrose]], Boots and Marriot in Europe.<ref name=\"garmentsweb\"/>\n\n===Printing===\n\nIn 1955, Clark Spence & Co. opened its own press to service its internal printing needs in Galle. Printing services were gradually opened for external parties and with the higher demand, the service offering was expanded with a full-fledged printing plant. Subsequently, in 1962, printing plant was moved from Galle to Colombo (Vauxhall St. Colombo 02 premises, where current Aitken Spence Group Headquarters is located) and ownership transferred to Aitken Spence & Co.<ref name=\"printbegin\">{{cite web |url= http://aitkenspenceplc.wordpress.com/2009/11/16/our-printing-heritage-2/|title= Our Printing Heritage |accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Galle2Colombo\">{{cite news | title = Amherst, El Alamein and Aitken Spence | newspaper = Sunday Times| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | url = http://www.sundaytimes.lk/030406/plus/6.html| accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref>\n[[File:Aitken Spence Green Printing Facility.JPG|thumb|x225px|Aitken Spence Green Printing Facility]]\nIn 1977, whole printing department was burnt from a fire and its operations were halted. In 1982, a new printing plant was built at Bloemendhal Road, Colombo 13 to resume printing services.<ref name=\"printbegin\"/> In 2010, due to capacity constraints, the company made a decision to relocate this printing plant yet again.<ref name=\"printlocate\">{{cite news | title = Aitken Spence Printing makes technology enhancements | newspaper = Sunday Times| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 24 October 2010 | url = http://www.sundaytimes.lk/101024/BusinessTimes/bt31.html| accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe production of printed packaging materials represents about 80 percent of business for the printing segment. In regards to packaging materials, it currently caters to major brands in garment industry, FMCG, cosmetics and pharmaceuticals in Sri Lanka. The company also caters to international clients such as [[Marks & Spencer]], British Home Stores, [[Tesco]] and DBA Europe.<ref name=\"printbegin\"/>\n\n===Next Generation Technology Products===\n\nIn October 2014, Aitken Spence invested in Eco Corp Asia, a company holding the exclusive rights in Sri Lanka to market nanotechnology based liquid glass coating product of Nanopool GmbH.<ref name=\"NanoPool\">{{cite news| title = Aitken Spence and Eco Corp Asia to take nanotechnology to next level| newspaper = Daily FT| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka| date = 3 November 2014| url = http://www.ft.lk/2014/11/03/aitken-spence-and-eco-corp-asia-to-take-nanotechnology-to-next-level/| access-date = 7 November 2014| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141107111542/http://www.ft.lk/2014/11/03/aitken-spence-and-eco-corp-asia-to-take-nanotechnology-to-next-level/| archive-date = 7 November 2014| url-status = dead}}</ref> The operation formulates specialized surface protection systems and applications on different materials utilizing nanotechnology; while introducing diverse innovative solutions for industries.<ref name=ARecocorpasia>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Annual Report Ecocorp Asia 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=5 July 2018 |url= http://aitkenspence.com/annualreport/}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.aitkenspence.com Official Website]\n* [http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/Stock/SPENN?CountryCode=LK The Wall Street Journal MarketWatch Overview]\n\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Publicly traded companies of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies]]\n[[Category:Hospitality companies of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Logistics companies]]\n[[Category:Business process outsourcing companies]]\n[[Category:Hotel chains]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name   = Aitken Spence\n|logo   = Aitken Spence logo.png\n|type   = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{Colombo Stock Exchange|SPEN.N0000}}\n|foundation = 1868\n| founder   = Patrick Gordon Spence<br>Thomas Clark<br>Edward Aitken<br>S.R. Aitken\n|location    = [[Colombo]], [[Sri Lanka]]\n|key_people        = [[Harry Jayawardena]]<br> (Chairman),<br> Rajan Brito <br>(Deputy Chairman and<br> Managing Director),<br> Rohan Fernando (Director),<br> Stasshani Jayawardena(Director)\n| area_served      = [[Sri Lanka]], [[Maldives]], [[Bangladesh]],<br>[[India]], [[South Africa]], [[Oman]], [[Fiji]], [[Mozambique]]\n|industry       = [[Leisure industry|Leisure]]<br>[[Transportation]] & [[Logistics]]<br>[[Power Generation]]<br>[[Information Technology]]<br>[[Financial Services]]<br>[[Business Process Outsourcing|BPO]]<br>[[Knowledge Process Outsourcing|KPO]]<br>[[Printing]]<br>[[Apparel]]<br>[[Plantations|Plantation Services]]<br>[[Real Estate Development|Property Development]]\n|products = \n|revenue = {{increase}} US$ 338.9 million <small>(2017/18)</small>\n|operating_income = {{profit}} US$ 3.5 million <small>(2017/18)</small>\n|net_income = {{profit}} US$ 33.1 million <small>(2017/18)</small>\n|assets = {{profit}} US$ 693.1 million <small>(2017/18)</small>\n|equity = {{profit}} US$ 361.7 million <small>(2017/18)</small>\n|num_employees = 13,533 (2018)\n|homepage = [http://www.aitkenspence.com Official Website] |\n}}\n'''Aitken Spence PLC''' ({{lang-si|[[:si:\u0d91\u0dba\u0dd2\u0da7\u0dca\u0d9a\u0dd2\u0db1\u0dca \u0dc3\u0dca\u0db4\u0dd9\u0db1\u0dca\u0dc3\u0dca|\u0d91\u0dba\u0dd2\u0da7\u0dca\u0d9a\u0dd2\u0db1\u0dca \u0dc3\u0dca\u0db4\u0dd9\u0db1\u0dca\u0dc3\u0dca]]}}; {{lang-ta|[[:ta:\u0b8e\u0baf\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0bb8\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc6\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0bb8\u0bcd|\u0b8e\u0baf\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0bb8\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc6\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0bb8\u0bcd]]}}) is a Sri Lankan [[Blue chip (stock market)|blue chip]] [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]]<ref name=bluechip>{{cite news | title = Aitken Spence\u2019s 9 month profits up 24% to Rs. 3 b | newspaper = Daily FT | location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 16 February 2012 | url = http://www.ft.lk/2012/02/14/aitken-spences-9-month-profits-up-24-to-rs-3-b/ | accessdate = 14 February 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131216213315/http://www.ft.lk/2012/02/14/aitken-spences-9-month-profits-up-24-to-rs-3-b/ | archive-date = 16 December 2013 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> with operations in South Asia, the Middle East, Africa and the Pacific.<ref name=\"dnprofile\">{{cite news | title = Aitken Spence posts Rs 1.7b profit in 1H | newspaper = Daily News | location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 5 November 2011 | url = http://www.dailynews.lk/2011/11/05/bus05.asp | accessdate = 10 January 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130218224018/http://www.dailynews.lk/2011/11/05/bus05.asp | archive-date = 18 February 2013 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"fijiPortMgmt\">{{cite news | title = Aitken Spence takes control of Fijian ports | publisher = Port Technology International | location = | date = 31 July 2013 | url = http://www.porttechnology.org/news/aitken_spence_takes_control_of_fijian_ports/ | accessdate=1 August 2013 }}</ref>  Listed in the [[Colombo Stock Exchange]] since 1983, it has major interests in hotels, travel, maritime services and logistics.<ref name=\"dnprofile\"/> The group also has a significant presence in printing, plantations, power generation, financial services, IT, BPO/KPO sector,  elevator agency services, garments, and property development.<ref name=\"dnprofile\"/>\n\nAitken Spence has been recognised by [[Forbes]] as one of the most successful publicly traded companies with annual sales under US$1 billion outside of the United States, for three consecutive years.<ref name=\"ASabout\">{{cite web| last = Aitken Spence| title = About Us| publisher = Aitken Spence| url = http://www.aitkenspence.com/about_us/hotels_logistics_power_sri_lanka.asp| accessdate = 17 January 2012| archive-url = https://archive.is/20120720111535/http://www.aitkenspence.com/about_us/hotels_logistics_power_sri_lanka.asp| archive-date = 20 July 2012| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref> In 2012, Aitken Spence was adjudged the top winner of the Best Corporate Citizen Award in 2017 and 2012 presented by the [[Ceylon Chamber of Commerce]] and has retained the title for 11 consecutive years.<ref name=\"BCCA2012\">{{cite news | title = Aitken Spence bags Best Corporate Citizen Award 2012 | newspaper = Daily Mirror | location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 13 November 2012 | url = http://www.dailymirror.lk/business/other/23439-aitken-spence-wins-best-corporate-citizen-award-2012-.html| accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"BCCA2017\">{{cite news | title = Aitken Spence wins Best Corporate Citizen Award 2017 | newspaper = Daily FT | location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 30 November 2017 | url = http://www.ft.lk/front-page/Aitken-Spence-wins--Best-Corporate-Citizen-Sustainability-Award-2017-/44-644258| accessdate= 17 January 2018}}</ref> The company is one of the first signatories to the UN's [[United Nations Global Compact|Global Compact]] in Sri Lanka.<ref name=\"UNGC\">{{cite web |title= UNGC Participants and Stakeholders |url= http://www.unglobalcompact.org/participants/search?commit=t&country%5B%5D=111&page=1&per_page=250|accessdate=11 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Patrick G. Spence.jpg|thumb|Patrick G. Spence]]\nWhilst the roots of Aitken Spence can be dated back to Wilson & Archer Partnership of the 1830s in the early [[British Ceylon|British Colonial Ceylon]], the company began to take its current form after the signing of a formal partnership agreement between Thomas Clark and Patrick Gordon Spence\u2014Scottish merchants and shipping agents<ref name=\"Trading\">{{cite book | last = Wright | first = Arnold |title= Twentieth Century Impressions of Ceylon: Its History, People, Commerce.. |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=eUF_rS8FEoIC&pg=PA437 |accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref> in [[Galle]]\u2014on 1 September 1868, wherein Clark Spence & Co. was established.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\">{{cite web| last = Aitken Spence| year = 2011| title = Aitken Spence Company Annual Report 2010-2011: Time Line| pages = 182\u2013183| url = http://www.aitkenspence.com/pdf/ar2011/aitken_spence_company_annual_report_2010_2011.pdf| accessdate = 17 January 2012| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131216214018/http://www.aitkenspence.com/pdf/ar2011/aitken_spence_company_annual_report_2010_2011.pdf| archive-date = 16 December 2013| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"FoundingHistory\">{{cite news | title = The Rootage of Insurance in Sri Lanka | author = M.Z.M. Nazim | newspaper = The Island | location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 17 November 2009 | url = http://www.island.lk/2009/11/17/business8.html | accessdate=17 November 2011}}</ref> Clark Spence & Co.'s trading segment at this stage included exports of [[graphite|natural vein graphite]] (plumbago), gems, hides, [[Caesalpinia sappan|Sappan wood]], [[ebony]], coffee, coconut oil, [[coir|coir yarn, bristle fibre]], arrack,  and [[citronella oil]] to [[United Kingdom]], [[Continental Europe]], [[United States of America]] and [[Australia]]; and imports of [[Burma|Burmese]] rice and coal for [[Steamboat|steamer ship]] [[Fuel oil#Bunker fuel|bunkers]].<ref name=\"earlytrade\">{{cite web| last = Aitken Spence| year = 2005| title = Aitken Spence Company Annual Report 2004-2005: A Brief Historical Outlook| pages = 126/128| url = http://www.aitkenspence.com/pdf/aitken_spence_2004_05_annual%20_report.pdf| accessdate = 17 January 2012| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090205175707/http://aitkenspence.com/pdf/aitken_spence_2004_05_annual%20_report.pdf| archive-date = 5 February 2009| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April 1871, Patrick Gordon Spence, secured Clark Spence & Co. as the sole agent of Lloyd's of London in [[Ceylon]].<ref name=\"FoundingHistory\"/> In order to service the Agency for the [[Lloyd's|Lloyd's of London]] for the [[Port of Colombo]], Clark Spence & Co. partnered with Britton, Aitken & Co. to open a branch office in [[Colombo]]. On New Year's Day, 1873, E.C. Britton opted out of the Britton, Aitken & Co. partnership, resulting in Patrick Gordon Spence, Edward Aitken and S.R. Aitken coming together to form Aitken Spence & Co. to manage the operations in Colombo, whilst Clark Spence & Co. continued in partnership to operate in Galle.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/><ref name=\"FoundingHistory\"/> In 1876, Aitken Spence & Co. obtained the Lloyds agency from Clark Spence & Co.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/> Aitken Spence had also obtained the local agency of [[Morgan Crucible| Morgan Crucible Company]] for trading in plumbago.<ref name=\"Trading\" /> As Colombo became the commercial capital of Sri Lanka, Aitken Spence & Co became more prominent and subsequently its partner company, Clark Spence & Co. originally based in Galle, became a subsidiary of Aitken Spence & Co.<ref name=\"LMDcorporateHistory\">{{cite web| last = Lanka Monthly Digest (LMD)| year = 2013| title = Corporate Heritage: Aitken Spence| url = http://lmd.lk/2013/12/26/corporate-heritage-profiles-9/| accessdate = 15 April 2014| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140415080257/http://lmd.lk/2013/12/26/corporate-heritage-profiles-9/| archive-date = 15 April 2014| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:Edward Aitken.jpg|thumb|Edward Aitken]]\nBy the 1880s, Aitken Spence had also secured the shipping agencies [[:nl:Koninklijke Rotterdamsche Lloyd|Koninklijke Rotterdamsche Lloyd]] and [[Netherland Line|Stoomvaart Maatschappij Nederland]] for Ceylon.<ref name=\"dutchshipping\">{{cite web | last = Lorck| year = 1912| title= Isles of the East: An Illustrated Guide. | url = https://archive.org/stream/cu31924010584682/cu31924010584682_djvu.txt| accessdate=23 December 2012}}</ref> The company moved into plantations sector as an agency house in the early 1900s and with the onset of the Great Depression, began to withdraw from its trading business. In 1918, Aitken Spence purchased the [[Lloyd's Building, Colombo|Freudenberg Building]] in Colombo, and made it its company headquarters having renamed the building as Lloyds Building. As a pioneer in port operations, Aitken Spence was entrusted in coordinating the Operations of Colombo Port during the Second World War.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/><ref name=\"FoundingHistory\"/>\n\nAitken Spence became a Private Company in 1952.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/> In its centenary year, 1968, it appointed its first Sri Lankan Chairman,<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/> E.L. Van Langenberg.<ref name=\"Heritage\">{{cite web |last= Aitken Spence |title= Our Heritage |url= http://www.aitkenspence.com/about_us/shipping_tourism_insurance_industry_sri_lanka.asp |accessdate= 17 January 2012 |archive-url= https://archive.is/20130117151217/http://www.aitkenspence.com/about_us/shipping_tourism_insurance_industry_sri_lanka.asp |archive-date= 17 January 2013 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref> By 1971, as Sri Lanka was preparing to end British dominion and declare as [[Sri Lanka#Independence|republic]], the company became a wholly Sri Lankan owned entity.<ref name=\"CompanyOwner\">{{cite book | last = Shalini Perera | year = 2011| title= Corporate Ownership and Control | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=VXT36YV6RBIC&pg=PA124 | accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> In 1972, it began to offer shares to its executives, thereby broad basing its ownership. The company eventually moved on from this model and in 1983 offered its shares to the general public on the [[Colombo Stock Exchange]] with an issued share capital of Rs. 51 million.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/><ref name=\"LMDcover\">{{cite news | title = Aitken Spence Historic Milestones | newspaper = LMD | location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = September 2005 | url = http://lmd.lk/archives/2005/September/cov7.htm | accessdate = 12 October 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130406154554/http://lmd.lk/archives/2005/September/cov7.htm | archive-date = 6 April 2013 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nDuring the early 1960s and early 1970s, Insurance and Plantations sectors\u2014which were core business segments of Aitken Spence, where the company had been well established at the time\u2014were nationalized.<ref name=\"Nationalized\">{{cite news |title= Changing of the guard at Aitken Spence|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/011230/bus3.html|newspaper= The Sunday Times |date= 30 December 2001|accessdate= 5 April 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Nationalization\">{{cite news|title= R. Sivaratnam retires after 40 years at Aitken Spence|url= http://www.priu.gov.lk/news_update/features/20020103sivaratnam_retires.htm|newspaper= Daily News|date= 1 January 2002|accessdate= 12 November 2015|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160304081255/http://www.priu.gov.lk/news_update/features/20020103sivaratnam_retires.htm|archive-date= 4 March 2016|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> However, the Group's [[marine insurance]] segment (including its Lloyd Agency) continued to operate as it did not fall within the purview of nationalization.\n\nDespite the setbacks from nationalization, in realizing the then government's thrust to boost tourism, Aitken Spence launched its tourism segment in 1972 with investments in its first hotel (Neptune Hotel in Beruwala, Sri Lanka opened in 1974).<ref name=\"Nationalized\"/> The company then entered into Aviation in 1974 (as general sales agent for [[Singapore Airlines]] in Sri Lanka).<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/> In consolidating its travel agency business that had begun with the launch of Aitken Spence Hotels in 1974, Aitken Spence set up Aitken Spence Travels in 1977 as inbound and outbound tour operators in Sri Lanka and as agents for [[Eurail]] and Britrail.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/><ref name=\"TravelsFormation\">{{cite news|title= Prema Cooray : A long and colourful journey|url= http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2002/12/15/bus17.html|newspaper= The Sunday Observer|date= 15 December 2002|accessdate= 15 May 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150924111825/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2002/12/15/bus17.html|archive-date= 24 September 2015|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> Tourism is now a core business segment of Aitken Spence.\n\nWith Sri Lanka adopting open market economic policies focused on export led growth in 1977, Aitken Spence forayed further into new business segments : Container and allied services in 1979; Garments and apparels in 1979;<ref name=\"garmentsweb\">{{cite web|url= http://www.aitkenspence.com/strategic_investments/garment_manufacture_in_sri_lanka.asp|title= Garment Manufacture|accessdate= October 9, 2012|archive-url= https://archive.is/20130116093005/http://www.aitkenspence.com/strategic_investments/garment_manufacture_in_sri_lanka.asp|archive-date= 16 January 2013|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> International courier service agency with [[Thomas Nationwide Transport|TNT]] in 1981;<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/> and Elevators in 1989 as agent of [[Otis Elevator Company|OTIS]].<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/> With insurance sector being deregulated in the 1980s, the Group played a pivotal role in the resurgence of private sector insuarance as a proponent of the National Insurance Corporation and Union Assuarance Ltd, stakes in which Aitken Spence subsequently divested. Aitken Spence reentered Plantations sector, when the sector was reprivatized in 1992,  through its stake in Udapussellawa Plantation PLC that was later divested.\n\nIn response to the Power Crisis in Sri Lanka in 1996, Aitken Spence began to explore investment opportunities in power generation sector, with first two power plants coming online in 2002.<ref name=\"jvjp\">{{cite news |title= CEB grid to get 20 mega watt boost |url= http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2002/03/10/bus01.html |newspaper= The Sunday Observer |date= 10 March 2002 |accessdate= 9 October 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150924111719/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2002/03/10/bus01.html |archive-date= 24 September 2015 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The Group also maintained container vessel operations, with acquisition of five ships in a joint venture with Ceyline Group in 2003, which it later divested in 2008. In 2010, in continuing its partnership with Ceyline Group, Aitken Spence invested in [[Colombo International Nautical and Engineering College|CINEC]], Sri Lanka's largest private higher education institution. In 2004, Aitken Spence Travels partnered with [[TUI Group]] of Germany to form a joint venture that is the largest leisure, travel and tourism company in the world.\n\nAitken Spence was the first Sri Lankan resort operator to embark on overseas resort operations having acquired Bathala Island Resort of [[Maldives]] in 1993.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/><ref name=\"TourismInnovation\">{{cite news |title= Kandalama, Club Rannhali my indelible moments|url= http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=62856|newspaper= The Island |date= 2 October 2012|accessdate= 15 May 2014}}</ref> In 1996, Aitken Spence entered [[Bangladesh]] through Aitken Spence Cargo with its shipping services.<ref>{{cite web| last = Aitken Spence Cargo| title = About Ace Cargo| url = http://www.acecargo.lk/about-acecargo.html| accessdate = 17 January 2012| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20111229145231/http://www.acecargo.lk/about-acecargo.html| archive-date = 29 December 2011| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref> A decade later, in 2006, Aitken Spence entered the Indian hospitality sector, having secured management contracts for five hotel properties in [[India]].<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/> On the same year, the company broke new ground by becoming the first Sri Lankan company to venture into port efficiency management outside of Sri Lanka, when it undertook to improve efficiency of ports in the African continent.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/><ref>{{cite news |title= Sri Lanka Aitken Spence to make Mozambique port efficient |url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?nid=1702158326 |newspaper= Lanka Business Online |date= 12 June 2011 |accessdate= 21 March 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20121123224538/http://lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?nid=1702158326 |archive-date= 23 November 2012 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The company increased its global presence even further by obtaining the management of four hotel properties in [[Oman]] in 2007.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/> In 2013, Aitken Spence announced its proposed venture into [[Fiji]] to manage the Ports of [[Suva]] and [[Lautoka]] in a public private partnership with the Government of Fiji.<ref name=\"fijiPortMgmt\"/><ref name=FijiPort>{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence PLC takes over the management of two major ports in Fiji |url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/130505/business-times/aitken-spence-plc-takes-over-the-management-of-two-major-ports-in-fiji-42782.html |newspaper= The Sunday Times |date= 5 May 2013 |accessdate=6 May 2013}}</ref> The Group has expressed interest to further diversify its investments in Fiji, venturing into hospitality, power and printing sectors.<ref name=FijiDiversity>{{cite news |title= Company plans for more investment in Fiji |url= http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=293963 |newspaper= The Fiji Times Online |date= 4 February 2015 |accessdate= 7 February 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150207204809/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=293963 |archive-date= 7 February 2015 |url-status= dead }}</ref> Currently, the company has operations in eight countries (Sri Lanka, Maldives, Bangladesh, India, South Africa, Oman, Fiji and Myanmar), spanning several continents<ref>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Company Annual Report 2017-2018:Our Network |pages = 8, 28\u201333 | url = http://aitkenspence.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Aitken-Spence-PLC-AR-2017-18.pdf | accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref> with 13,000 employees.<ref>{{cite video|year=2018|title=Corporate Video|url=http://www.aitkenspence.com/about_us/hotels_logistics_power_sri_lanka.asp|publisher=Aitken Spence|accessdate=21 March 2012|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120720111535/http://www.aitkenspence.com/about_us/hotels_logistics_power_sri_lanka.asp|archive-date=20 July 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=ARKeyEvents>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Annual Report Key Events 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=18 June 2018 |url= http://aitkenspence.com/annualreport/#KeyEvents}}</ref>\n\n== Governance structure ==\nAitken Spence is governed by the chairman and the board of directors and is managed by the Group Management Committee.<ref name=\"Management\">{{cite web | last = Aitken Spence| year = 2018| title= Aitken Spence Company Annual Report 2017-2018: Board of Directors and Board of Management  | url = http://aitkenspence.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Aitken-Spence-PLC-AR-2017-18.pdf | accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Chairman and Board of Directors ===\nThe current chairman of Aitken Spence is [[Harry Jayawardena|Mr. Harry Jayawardena]]. He is the founder director and current chairman/managing director of the Stassen Group of Companies \u2013 a diversified group in exports and import trade, the chairman of Lanka Milk Foods (CWE) PLC, Browns Beach Hotels PLC, Balangoda Plantations PLC, Madulsima Plantations PLC, Melstacorp PLC, Ambewela Livestock Company Ltd, Lanka Bell Ltd and also the current chairman of the [[Distilleries Company of Sri Lanka|Distilleries Company of Sri Lanka (DCSL) PLC]].<ref name=\"Management\"/>\n\nThe current panel of board directors includes Dr. Parakrama Dissanayake, deputy chairman/managing director; and executive directors Dr. Rohan Fernando, and Ms. Stasshani Jayawardena; and the non-executive directors Mr. Rajan Brito, Mr. G.C. Wickremasinghe, Mr. Charles Gomez, Mr. Niranjan Deva Aditya and Mr. Rajan Asirwatham.<ref name=\"Management\"/><ref>{{cite web |title= Stasshani Jayawardena Appointed to the Aitken Spence PLC Board |url= http://aitkenspenceplc.wordpress.com// |date= 29 November 2013 |accessdate= 30 November 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131210041408/http://aitkenspenceplc.wordpress.com/ |archive-date= 10 December 2013 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n[[File:Aitken Spence Towers.JPG|thumb|x200px|Aitken Spence Towers, Corporate Headquarters of Aitken Spence Group, in Colombo. 02.]]\n\n=== Group Management Committee ===\nGroup Management Committee is headed by Dr. Parakrama Dissanayke. The other members of the Group Management Committee are Dr. Rohan Fernando,  Ms. Stasshani Jayawardena, Ms. Nilanthi Sivapragasam, Mr. Rohan Pandithakorralage, Ms. Nimmi Guneratne, Mr. Susith Jayawickrama,  Mr. Dinesh Mendis, Mr. Prasanna Karunathilake, Mr. Leel Wickremarachchi, Mr. Nalin Jayasundera, Mr. Iqram Cuttilan, Mr. Janaka Gunawardena, Mr. Jerome Brohier, Mr.Vasantha Kudaliyanage, Mr. Calude Jayantha Fernando and Mr. Chaminda Hidurangala<ref name=\"AR2017\">{{cite web | last = Aitken Spence| year = 2014| title= Aitken Spence Company Annual Report 2017-2018 | url = http://aitkenspence.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Aitken-Spence-PLC-AR-2017-18.pdf | accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Corporate sustainability==\n\nAitken Spence PLC was adjudged the winner of the Best Corporate Citizen Sustainability Award 2018, 2017 and 2012 conducted by the [[Ceylon Chamber of Commerce]]. The company has been ranked among the Top 10 Corporate Citizens for an unprecedented 13 consecutive years.<ref name=\"Best Corporate Citizen\">{{cite news |url= http://www.ft.lk/front-page/Aitken-Spence-wins--Best-Corporate-Citizen-Sustainability-Award-2017-/44-644258|title= Best Corporate Citizen Sustainability Award |date= 29 November 2017|accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref> Aitken Spence PLC won multiple category awards such as for Employee Relations and Community Relations, Triple Bottom Line Award for its work on Environmental Sustainability and was awarded the sector based sustainability champions for Diversified Holdings.<ref>{{cite news |title=Best Corporate Citizen Award |newspaper=The Island |date=29 November 2017 |accessdate=7 February 2018 |url= http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=175776}}</ref>\n\nAitken Spence's sustainability framework has been rated Platinum by STING Corporate Accountability Index 2018 for the 6th consecutive year and has been ranked among the top three companies in the index since 2011.<ref>{{cite news |title=Aitken Spence Rated Platinum |newspaper=Daily News |date=21 March 2018 |accessdate=26 March 2018  |url= http://www.dailynews.lk/2018/03/21/business/146074/aitken-spence-rated-platinum-consecutively-corporate-accountability}}</ref> Published by LMD bi-annually, the index rated the top 50 companies from the LMD 100 (excluding investment companies) as well as key state-owned enterprises on a holistic and integrated model covering corporate responsibility, sustainability and governance.\n\nAs a result of the company's long-standing engagement with the local network of the [[United Nations Global Compact|UN Global Compact]], Aitken Spence has been admitted to the board and the steering committee of the Sri Lanka Network.<ref name=\"GCNCrole\">{{cite web |url= https://aitkenspenceplc.wordpress.com/2011/11/ |title= Aitken Spence Recognized as a Best Corporate Citizen for the Sixth Year Running |accessdate=13 October 2012}}</ref> The company reports 'Advanced\u2019 in the UNGC Communication on Progress (COP) which indicates that the company qualifies as GC Active and, in addition, cover the company's implementation of advanced criteria and best practices.<ref name=\"UNGC COP\">{{cite web |url= https://www.unglobalcompact.org/participation/report/cop/ |title= The Communication on Progress (COP) in Brief |accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"UNGC Advanced COP\">{{cite web |url= https://www.unglobalcompact.org/participation/report/cop/create-and-submit/advanced?page=1&per_page=250/ |title= Total number of GC Advanced COPs received |accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> Dr. Rohan Fernando, head of plantations and business development at Aitken Spence, was the former chairman of the Global Compact Sri Lanka Network.<ref name=\"GCNCchair\">{{cite news|url= http://www.dailynews.lk/2011/05/16/bus18.asp|title= Environmental trusteeship essential for sustainability|date= 16 May 2011|accessdate= 13 October 2012|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110821060434/http://www.dailynews.lk/2011/05/16/bus18.asp|archive-date= 21 August 2011|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAitken Spence is amongst the first 38 companies in the world to endorse the Women's Empowerment Principles, a joint initiative of [[UN Women]] and UN Global Compact to promote gender equality in business, and the first company to do so in Sri Lanka.<ref name=\"wep\">{{cite web|url= http://www.dailynews.lk/2010/06/22/bus04.asp|title= Aitken Spence signs UN's Women's Empowerment Principles|date= 22 June 2010|accessdate= 13 October 2012|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100625132344/http://www.dailynews.lk/2010/06/22/bus04.asp|archive-date= 25 June 2010|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"wepsite\">{{cite web |url= http://weprinciples.org/Site/CeosSpeak/ |title= CEOs Speak |accessdate=13 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nAitken Spence is also one of the first companies in Sri Lanka to pledge its support to the Caring for Climate initiative, which is a joint effort by [[UNEP]], [[United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change|UNFCCC]] and [[United Nations Global Compact|UNGC]] to promote positive climate action in business.<ref name=\"careclimate\">{{cite web |url= http://www.unglobalcompact.org/docs/news_events/8.1/caring_for_climate.pdf |title= Caring for Climate: The Business Leadership Platform| date = June 2010 |accessdate=13 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"climate\">{{cite web | url=http://www.caringforclimate.org/about-list.php | title=Caring for Climate: List of Signatories }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, Aitken Spence launched '''Empowering Sri Lanka First''', an English and IT teaching program for children from its neighbouring communities as its flagship corporate community engagement initiative. The program enrols eight-year-old students for weekend English classes (180 children currently enrolled in pilot phase from Dambulla, Ahungalla, and Mawaramandiya) for a period of three years. The curriculum of the English program has been custom designed by [[British Council]] to complement Sri Lanka's local school syllabus and teachers from local communities trained on interactive [[pedagogy]]. Aitken Spence has announced its plans to commence the IT component of the program in September 2013.<ref name=\"ESLF\">{{cite news|title= Aitken Spence launches \u2018Empowering Sri Lanka First\u2019|url= http://www.ft.lk/2013/07/27/aitken-spence-launches-empowering-sri-lanka-first/|date= 27 July 2013|accessdate= 4 August 2013|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131216211018/http://www.ft.lk/2013/07/27/aitken-spence-launches-empowering-sri-lanka-first/|archive-date= 16 December 2013|url-status= dead}}</ref> The project was recognized with a merit award at the Best Sustainability Projects Awards 2014.<ref name=\"BCCSA2014\">{{cite news|url= http://www.ft.lk/2014/11/26/mas-intimate-wins-coveted-best-corporate-citizen-sustainability-award-2014/|title= MAS Intimate wins coveted Best Corporate Citizen Sustainability Award 2014|date= 26 November 2014|accessdate= 26 November 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141128220722/http://www.ft.lk/2014/11/26/mas-intimate-wins-coveted-best-corporate-citizen-sustainability-award-2014/|archive-date= 28 November 2014|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n\nAs part of a broadbased diversification strategy, the sector embarked on a landmark project in the country's waste to energy sphere. Seen as a vital and much needed solution for the waste disposal crisis within Colombo city limits, the proposed project involves the construction of a 10MW waste-toenergy plant at Muthurajawela. The plant will be fuelled by waste collected from the Colombo Municipal Area, which was previously dumped in Meethotamulla. The plant is equipped to convert between 600 \u2013 800 metric tonnes of municipal solid waste daily to electricity.<ref name=\"waste to energy\">{{cite news |title= The first waste-to-energy initiative in Sri Lanka |url= http://www.ft.lk/article/634380/Two-waste-to-energy-plants-to-get-off-the-ground-today/ | date= 10 August 2017 |accessdate= 9 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Sri Lanka's first waste to energy plant\">{{cite news |title= HNB partners up as lead banker to Sri Lanka's first waste-to-energy plant |url= http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=170297/ | date= 20 August 2017 |accessdate=30 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Hotels ==\n\nAitken Spence operates a chain of 21 hotels and resorts in four countries: Sri Lanka, Maldives, India and Oman and currently is the largest hotel room inventory owned by a Sri Lankan resort company with a room inventory of over 2600 rooms of capacity.<ref name=ASHR>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Hotels Annual Report Strategy and Prospects 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence Hotels |accessdate=16 June 2018 |url= https://www.aitkenspencehotels.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/ASH1718.pdf}}</ref> Its portfolio includes beach resorts and water villas, [[Ayurveda]] holiday resorts, and eco and culture resorts<ref name=hotelweb>{{cite web |title= Hotels |last= Aitken Spence |url= http://www.aitkenspence.com/hotels/hotels_in_sri_lanka_and_maldives.asp |accessdate= 6 March 2012 |archive-url= https://archive.is/20130116154608/http://www.aitkenspence.com/hotels/hotels_in_sri_lanka_and_maldives.asp |archive-date= 16 January 2013 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref> in the 3-5 [[Star (classification)#Hotel ratings|star category]].<ref name=tbl>{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence rejuvenates Neptune Resort |newspaper= The Bottom Line |date= 15 July 2009 |accessdate= 28 March 2012 |url= http://www.thebottomline.lk/2009/07/15/living30.html }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nBrands of Aitken Spence Hotels include \"Heritance Hotels and Resorts\", \"turyaa by Heritance\", \"Aitken Spence Hotels and Resorts\" and \"Adaaran Hotels and Resorts\".<ref name=\"Aitken Spence Hotel Brands\">{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Hotels Annual Report Brand Attributes 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence Hotels |accessdate=16 June 2018 |url= https://www.aitkenspencehotels.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/ASH1718.pdf}}</ref>\n\n=== Sri Lanka ===\nAitken Spence is currently one of the largest resort operators in Sri Lanka.<ref>{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence results boosted by strong tourism performance |author=  |newspaper= Daily FT |date= 4 February 2011 |accessdate= 28 March 2012 |url= http://www.ft.lk/2011/02/04/aitken-spence-results-boosted-by-strong-tourism-performance |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110209144658/http://www.ft.lk/2011/02/04/aitken-spence-results-boosted-by-strong-tourism-performance/ |archive-date= 9 February 2011 |url-status= dead }}</ref> Also, under the Adaaran brand, is the largest international resort operator in the Maldives.<ref>{{cite news|title= Aitken Spence expands presence in Maldives |author= |newspaper= Daily Mirror |date= 10 June 2015|accessdate=26 June 2017|url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/75755/aitken-spence-expands-presence-in-maldives}}</ref>\n\n==== Heritance Hotels and Resorts ====\n\n===== Heritance Ayurveda Maha Gedara =====\n\nAitken Spence Group first ventured into hospitality sector in 1974, with the opening of Neptune Hotel\u2014designed by [[Geoffrey Bawa|Deshamanya Geoffrey Bawa]]\u2014in [[Beruwala]], Sri Lanka.<ref name=tbl /> In July 2011, the Group rebranded the hotel as Heritance Ayurveda Maha Gedara after a major renovation wherein the hotel was converted to an [[Ayurveda#Sri Lanka|Ayurveda]] wellness resort.<ref>{{cite news |title=Heritance Ayurveda Maha Gedara- opens |newspaper=Daily News |date=17 December 2011 |accessdate=6 March 2012 |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2011/12/17/bus60.asp |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130312122224/http://www.dailynews.lk/2011/12/17/bus60.asp |archive-date=12 March 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2017, Heritance Ayurveda Maha Gedara, was accoladed with the internationally recommended Travelife for Hotels and Accommodations Gold Certification for the hotel's commitment to sustainability and ethical business practices.<ref>{{cite news |title=Heritance Ayurveda Maha Gedara achieves Travelife Gold Certification |newspaper=Daily Mirror |date=12 October 2017 |accessdate=6 March 2018 |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/article/Heritance-Ayurveda-Maha-Gedara-achieves-Travelife-Gold-Certification-138274.html}}</ref> In 2018, Heritance Ayurveda Maha Gedara was recognized by [[:pl:FIT Reisen|FIT Reisen]], a leading provider of health and wellness travel, with the Quality Certificate in the category of \u2018Ayurveda and yoga\u2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Heritance Ayurveda Maha Gedara recognised by Fit Reisen for quality |newspaper=Sri Lanka Travel News |date=27 March 2018 |accessdate=6 May 2018 |url= https://srilankatravelnews.wordpress.com/2018/03/27/heritance-ayurveda-maha-gedara-recognised-by-fit-reisen-for-quality/}}</ref>\n\n===== Heritance Ahungalla =====\nHeritance Ahungalla, formerly known as Triton, is Sri Lanka's first five-star beach resort\u2014launched in 1981 in Ahungalla, a town in southern coastal belt of Sri Lanka.  Originally designed by [[Geoffrey Bawa|Deshamanya Geoffrey Bawa]], the 152 roomed 5 star resort was relaunched under the Heritance brand in June 2006 subsequent to a US$13 million refurbishment.<ref name=hotelAR>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Hotels Annual Report 2010/2011 |author= Aitken Spence |accessdate= 6 March 2012 |url= http://www.aitkenspencehotels.com/images/homepage/141_aitken_spence_hotel_annual_report_2010_2011.pdf |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120417082838/http://www.aitkenspencehotels.com/images/homepage/141_aitken_spence_hotel_annual_report_2010_2011.pdf |archive-date= 17 April 2012 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The hotel is the first hotel in Sri Lanka to receive the ISO 50001 certification for energy management.<ref>{{cite news |title= Heritance Ahungalla, first Sri Lankan hotel to be ISO50001 certified |newspaper= sundaytimes.lk |date= 25 December 2011|accessdate=28 March 2012|url= http://sundaytimes.lk/111225/BusinessTimes/bt38.html }}</ref> The five-star Heritance Ahungalla won the prestigious TUI Top Quality 2018. This was awarded from [[TUI Group]], the largest leisure, travel and tourism company in the world.<ref name=ARKeyEvents/>\n\n===== Heritance Kandalama =====\n[[File:Heritance Kandalama Exterior View.JPG|thumb|x200px|Exterior view of Heritance Kandalama]].\nHeritance Kandalama, is the flagship hotel of Aitken Spence, is located in Kandalama, Dambulla in proximity to two [[World Heritage Site|UNESCO World Heritage Sites]]\u2014 [[Sigiriya]] and [[Dambulla Cave Temple]].<ref name=hotelAR /> The hotel is built into a natural rock outcrop within a jungle setting and overlooks the [[Kandalama Reservoir]].<ref name=hotelAR /> Designed by [[Geoffrey Bawa|Deshamanya Geoffrey Bawa]],<ref>{{cite news|title= Infinite relaxation in Sri Lanka\u2019s cultural triangle|author= |newspaper= Daily FT|date= 4 February 2012|accessdate= 28 March 2012|url= http://www.ft.lk/2012/02/04/infinite-relaxation-in-sri-lankas-cultural-triangle/|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120208190439/http://www.ft.lk/2012/02/04/infinite-relaxation-in-sri-lankas-cultural-triangle/|archive-date= 8 February 2012|url-status= dead}}</ref> it is the first hotel outside the United States to receive [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED certified]].<ref name=hk>{{cite news |title= Heritance crowned most energy efficient hotel chain by bagging Gold, Silver and Bronze Awards |author=  |newspaper= Daily FT |date= 15 August 2011 |accessdate= 28 March 2012 |url= http://www.ft.lk/2011/08/15/heritance-crowned-most-energy-efficient-hotel-chain-by-bagging-gold-silver-and-bronze-awards/ |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110820220444/http://www.ft.lk/2011/08/15/heritance-crowned-most-energy-efficient-hotel-chain-by-bagging-gold-silver-and-bronze-awards/ |archive-date= 20 August 2011 |url-status= dead }}</ref> The hotel was also the first in Asia to be Green Globe certified for its ecotourism best practices.<ref>{{cite news |title= Heritance Kandalama wins EarthCheck Silver certification |newspaper= Daily News |date= 4 February 2012 |accessdate= 28 March 2012 |url= http://www.dailynews.lk/2010/05/18/bus70.asp/ |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100523195438/http://www.dailynews.lk/2010/05/18/bus70.asp |archive-date= 23 May 2010 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===== Heritance Tea Factory =====\nHeritance Tea Factory is a concept hotel wherein a 61-year-old dilapidated tea factory has been remodelled and conserved as a hotel.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.heritancehotels.com/teafactory/our-history.html |title= The origins of Hethersett |author= Aitken Spence |accessdate= 28 March 2012 |archive-url= https://archive.is/20120905152413/http://www.heritancehotels.com/teafactory/our-history.html |archive-date= 5 September 2012 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref>  Located in Heathersett Estate (25 acre tea estate),<ref name=UNESCO>{{cite news|title= Heritance Tea Factory Hotel: An epitome of environmental conscience|author= |newspaper= The Island |date= 11 October 2011|accessdate=28 March 2012|url= http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=36604}}</ref> [[Kandapola]] in the [[Nuwara Eliya]] district, the 5 star resort is considered to be the highest elevated (6,800&nbsp;ft above sea level)<ref name=hotelAR /> luxury hotel in Sri Lanka. Conceptualized by Mr. G. C. Wickremasinghe, a former chairman and current board member of Aitken Spence PLC, and designed by Mr. Nihal Bodhinayake, the hotel came to operation in 1996.<ref name=PATA>{{cite news |title= Heritance Tea Factory only Lankan hotel to win PATA Grand Award in 2012 |author=  |newspaper= Daily FT |date= 27 February 2012 |accessdate= 28 March 2012 |url= http://www.ft.lk/2012/02/27/heritance-tea-factory-only-lankan-hotel-to-win-pata-grand-award-in-2012/ |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140202195844/http://www.ft.lk/2012/02/27/heritance-tea-factory-only-lankan-hotel-to-win-pata-grand-award-in-2012/ |archive-date= 2 February 2014 |url-status= dead }}</ref>  The hotel was awarded the Asia Pacific Heritage Merit Award in 2001 by [[UNESCO]] for preserving the tea factory and its colonial heritage.<ref name=UNESCO /> In February 2012, Heritance Tea Factory was also recognized by the [[Pacific Asia Travel Association]](PATA) with the Grand Award, first Sri Lankan hotel to be so recognized, in the Heritage and Culture category.<ref name=PATA/> In 2014, Heritance Tea Factory's cultivation and processing of tea was certified to Sri Lanka Standards Institute's organic tea certification standards, being the first tea producer to be so certified in Sri Lanka.<ref name=OrganicTeaHTF>{{cite news |title= Heritance Tea Factory first to secure Organic Tea Certification from SLSI |newspaper= Daily FT |date= 27 January 2014 |accessdate= 28 January 2014 |url= http://www.ft.lk/2014/01/27/heritance-tea-factory-first-to-secure-organic-tea-certification-from-slsi/ |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140128065337/http://www.ft.lk/2014/01/27/heritance-tea-factory-first-to-secure-organic-tea-certification-from-slsi/ |archive-date= 28 January 2014 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\n===== Heritance Negombo =====\n\nHeritance [[Negombo]] (formally known as Browns Beach Hotel) was rebranded as Heritance Negombo,.<ref name=HNfactsheet>{{cite web |title= Heritance Negombo Factsheet |author= Aitken Spence |accessdate= 31 January 2015 |url= http://www.heritancehotels.com/negombo/files/2014/12/Heritance-Negombo-Fact-Sheet.pdf }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=HeritanceNegombo1>{{cite news |title= Browns Beach to rebrand as \u2018Heritance Negombo\u2019|newspaper = Ceylon Today |accessdate=20 August 2013 |url= http://www.ceylontoday.lk/22-34678-news-detail-browns-beach-to-rebrand-as-heritance-negombo.html }}</ref> This hotel is the latest to the Heritance portfolio that came on board in 2016. The premium brand portfolio offers novel 'city hotel on the beach' concept, which combines proximity and convenience with a resort ambience.<ref name=HN>{{cite news|title= Heritance Negombo to open next month |newspaper= Daily Mirror |date= 24 March 2016|accessdate= 5 October 2017|url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/107335/Heritance-Negombo-to-open-next-month}}</ref> In March 2016, [[TUI Group]] CEO [[Friedrich Joussen]] visited the 139-room hotel. The historic visit was organized by TUI's joint venture partner in Sri Lanka Aitken Spence Travels.<ref name=CEOTUI>{{cite news|title= World\u2019s largest integrated tourism group CEO visits Heritance Negombo |newspaper= LBO |date= 3 March 2016|accessdate= 13 November 2017|url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/worlds-largest-integrated-tourism-group-ceo-visits-heritance-negombo/}}</ref>\n\n====Turyaa Kalutara====\n\nTuryaa Kalutara is a 200-room property in Waskaduwa, Kalutara, which was formerly known as \"The Sands by Aitken Spence Hotels\", \"Ramada Kalutara\" and \"Golden Sun\". The hotel which initially held 112 rooms was relaunched as Turyaa Kalutara after an addition of new wing to the hotel in November 2015.<ref name=TK>{{cite news|title= Aitken Spence unveils 'turyaa' brand at WTM |newspaper= Daily News |date= 3 November 2015|accessdate=4 November 2015|url= http://www.dailynews.lk/?q=business/aitken-spence-unveils-turyaa-brand-wtm}}</ref> Turyaa Kalutara is a beach-front resort with 200 rooms, equipped with private balconies.<ref name=TuryaaHeritance>{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence launches Turyaa by Heritance |newspaper= The Nation |date= 5 November 2015 |accessdate= 14 December 2016 |url= http://nation.lk/online/2015/11/05/aitken-spence-launches-turyaa-by-heritance.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180618130156/http://nation.lk/online/2015/11/05/aitken-spence-launches-turyaa-by-heritance.html |archive-date= 18 June 2018 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\n==== Aitken Spence Hotels and Resorts ====\n[[File:Earl's Regency Hotel-Kandy Sri Lanka I.jpg|thumb|x200px|Earl's Regency-Kandy]]\nAitken Spence Hotels and Resorts currently operates the following hotels in Sri Lanka: [[Bandarawela Hotel]], Earl's Regency and Earl's Regent- [[Kandy]].<ref name=ASHOTELS>{{cite web |title= Sri Lanka Hotels by Aitken Spence|author= Aitken Spence Hotels |accessdate=14 June 2018 |url= https://www.aitkenspencehotels.com/destinations/sri-lanka.html}}</ref> In 2012, total ownership of Hotel Hilltop Kandy was acquired; however, in 2017, the Group divested its ownership of Hotel Hilltop Kandy<ref name=ASsellsHTK>{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence sells Hill Top Kandy for Rs 740 mn|newspaper= Daily News |accessdate=3 October 2017 |url= http://www.dailynews.lk/2017/09/25/business/129174/aitken-spence-sells-hill-top-kandy-rs-740-mn}}</ref><ref name=HTK>{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence to sell Hotel Hilltop, Kandy for Rs.740mn |newspaper= Daily Mirror |accessdate=17 October 2017 |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/article/Aitken-Spence-to-sell-Hotel-Hilltop-Kandy-for-Rs-mn-137225.html}}</ref> and took on the management of The Regent Kandy, a newly refurbished property with a four-star rating located in the centre of the city.<ref name=ARHOTELS>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Hotels Annual Report 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence Hotels |accessdate=14 June 2018 |url= https://www.aitkenspencehotels.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/ASH1718.pdf}}</ref>\n\nAitken Spence has previously announced its interest to develop its properties in Ahungalla and [[Nilaveli]] as resort properties.<ref name=Nilaveli>{{cite news|title= Sri Lanka Aitken Spence plans eastern resort|newspaper= Lanka Business Online|accessdate= 20 August 2013|url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/sri-lanka-aitken-spence-plans-eastern-resort/1215925252|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131101145327/http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/sri-lanka-aitken-spence-plans-eastern-resort/1215925252|archive-date= 1 November 2013|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=Madhu>{{cite news|title= Six Senses arrives in Ahungalla with Aitken Spence Hotels|newspaper= Daily FT|accessdate= 20 August 2013|url= http://www.ft.lk/2010/10/01/six-senses-arrives-in-ahungalla-with-aitken-spence-hotels/2|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131103100353/http://www.ft.lk/2010/10/01/six-senses-arrives-in-ahungalla-with-aitken-spence-hotels/2/|archive-date= 3 November 2013|url-status= dead}}</ref><ref name=RIU>{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence negotiating deal with Spanish hotel chain for Ahungalla property|newspaper = Daily Mirror |accessdate=30 October 2013 |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/business/other/36142-aitken-spence-negotiating-deal-with-spanish-hotel-chain-for-ahungalla-property-.html}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2013, Aitken Spence announced its plans to enter into a joint venture with Spanish hotel chain [[RIU Hotels]] to build a 500-room, 5-star resort in Ahungalla to be opened in winter 2015.<ref name=RIUjv>{{cite news |title= Sri Lanka's Aitken Spence in resort with Spain's RIU |newspaper= Lanka Business Online |accessdate= 5 November 2013 |url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/sri-lankas-aitken-spence-in-resort-with-spains-riu/235464834 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131105103310/http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/sri-lankas-aitken-spence-in-resort-with-spains-riu/235464834 |archive-date= 5 November 2013 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The business model for the new hotel involves attracting long haul travelers to Sri Lanka through charter flight holiday packages facilitated by [[TUI AG|TUI]]. Model is set on [[Mattala Rajapaksa International Airport]] & [[E01 expressway (Sri Lanka)|Sri Lanka's Southern Expressway]] providing the connectivity for tourists\u2014disembarking from TUI's weekly 787 Dreamliner Charters\u2014to reach the hotel.<ref name=RIUmattala>{{cite news  |title= Mattala Airport and Southern Highway hailed internationally - Adjudged Sri Lanka\u2019s premier tourism products by WTM  |newspaper= The Nation  |accessdate= 24 November 2013  |url= http://www.nation.lk/edition/news-online/item/22635-mattala-airport-and-southern-highway-hailed-internationally-adjudged-sri-lanka%E2%80%99s-premier-tourism-products-by-wtm.html#sthash.IWcBccjE.dpuf  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131202232554/http://www.nation.lk/edition/news-online/item/22635-mattala-airport-and-southern-highway-hailed-internationally-adjudged-sri-lanka%E2%80%99s-premier-tourism-products-by-wtm.html#sthash.IWcBccjE.dpuf  |archive-date= 2 December 2013  |url-status= dead  }}</ref><ref name=TUIriu>{{cite news |title= Mattala TUI to explore new vistas in Sri Lanka tourism |newspaper = Ceylon Today |date= 17 January 2014 |accessdate= 1 February 2014 |url= http://www.ceylontoday.lk/22-53132-news-detail-tui-to-explore-new-vistas-in-sri-lanka-tourism.html}}</ref> In May 2015, Aitken Spence Travels partnered with [[:it: Alpitour|Alpitour Group]] and [[SriLankan Airlines]] to operate charters from Italy to attract 8000 tourists to this all-inclusive, 24-hour-service hotel on a Club Med model.<ref name=AlpitourRiu>{{cite news |title= SL, Spence ink $1.3 m deal with Italy tour firm at Expo 2015 |newspaper= Daily FT |date= 6 May 2015 |accessdate= 8 May 2015 |url= http://www.ft.lk/2015/05/06/sl-spence-ink-1-3-m-deal-with-italy-tour-firm-at-expo-2015/ |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150510033354/http://www.ft.lk/2015/05/06/sl-spence-ink-1-3-m-deal-with-italy-tour-firm-at-expo-2015/ |archive-date= 10 May 2015 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Hotel RIU Sri Lanka came on board with its 501-room partnership venture with Spanish hotel developer and operator [[RIU Hotels]]. Although the majority stake is owned by Aitken Spence Hotel Holdings PLC, day-to-day management is done by RIU Hotels & Resorts.<ref name=RIUResort>{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence Breaks Ground for RIU Resort, Ahungalla date |author= NEWS.LK |accessdate=10 June 2018 |url= https://www.news.lk/news/politics/item/2172-aitken-spence-breaks-ground-for-riu-resort-ahungalla}}</ref><ref name=ARHotelsRIU>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Hotels Annual Report 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence Hotels |accessdate=10 June 2018 |url= https://www.aitkenspencehotels.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/ASH1718.pdf}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Aitken Spence revealed plans to convert the [[Clan House, Galle|Clan House]], former headquarters of Clark Spence & Co. located within [[Galle Fort]], to a 15-room heritage boutique hotel.<ref name=ClanHotels>{{cite news |title= Spence to open new heritage hotel |newspaper= The Nation |accessdate= 6 June 2014 |url= http://www.nation.lk/edition/biz-news/item/30259-spence-to-open-new-heritage-hotel.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140618211717/http://www.nation.lk/edition/biz-news/item/30259-spence-to-open-new-heritage-hotel.html |archive-date= 18 June 2014 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, Aitken Spence acquired a strategic stake in Amethyst Resort, [[Pasikudah|Passikudah]] with the management rights.<ref name=\"ASHar2015\">{{cite web |url= https://www.cse.lk/cmt/upload_report_file/521_1433502972773.pdf |title= Aitken Spence Hotel Holdings PLC Annual Report 2014/2015 |accessdate= 7 June 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Aitken Spence Hotels partnered with [[SriLankan Airlines]]'s [[SriLankan Airlines#Frequent Flyer Programme|FlySmiLes]] loyalty program, which allows frequent flyers on [[Oneworld#Benefits and services|Oneworld]] carriers the opportunity to gain/redeem miles for their stay at any of Aitken Spence's Sri Lankan hotels.<ref name=AsSLpartner>{{cite web |title= More benefits for frequent flyers with FlySmiLes- Aitken Spence partnership  |date= 22 April 2014 |accessdate= 10 May 2014 |url= http://www.srilankan.com/corporate/en_uk/home/news-details/158}}</ref>\n\n==== Aitken Spence School of Hospitality ====\nAitken Spence opened its School of Hospitality in November 2007 at Ahungalla, Sri Lanka with the assistance of the Austrian Chamber of Commerce and Hilfswerk to bridge the skills gap in the tourism sector. The school was initially set up to recover from the Tsunami and assist locals in the Ahungalle region. However, since the ending of the war, the school serves to assist the development in the North and the East as well as other rural areas in the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Aitken Spence trains rural youth in Hospitality Sector |author= |url= http://sundaytimes.lk/100801/BusinessTimes/bt36.html|newspaper= Sunday Times |date= |accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> The school has so far provided training opportunities for marginalized youth from Uva, North Central, East and Northern provinces in food and beverage services.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://aitkenspenceplc.wordpress.com/2010/11/23/aitken-spence-school-of-hospitality-produces-third-batch-of-hospitality-trainees-from-the-east-and-uva/ |title= Aitken Spence School of Hospitality Produces Third Batch of Hospitality Trainees from the East and Uva |author= |date= 23 November 2010 |work= |publisher= |accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.undp.lk/SubPressReleases/Pages/detail.aspx?ItemID=39 |title= 30 youth complete the UNDP-Aitken Spence School of Hospitality supported training in the hospitality industry |author=  |date= 31 May 2012 |work=  |publisher= UNDP |accessdate= 15 October 2012 }}{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 2015, 27 trainees having completed a 3-month basic course in food and beverage, graduated from the Aitken Spence School of Hospitality in Ahungalla.<ref>{{cite news |title=Twenty seven youth graduate from Aitken Spence School of Hospitality |author= |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/65881/twenty-seven-youth-graduate-from-aitken-spence-school-of-hospitality|newspaper= Daily Mirror |date= |accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Maldives ===\nAitken Spence entered Maldivian hotel sector in 1993 with its investment in Bathala Island Resort.<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/>  Aitken Spence is also the largest foreign resort operator in the Maldives<ref>{{cite news |title= Sri Lanka's Aitken Spence eye war-torn areas for tourism |url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?nid=206699017 |newspaper= Lanka Business Online |date= 7 August 2009 |accessdate= 22 March 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20121120175231/http://lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?nid=206699017 |archive-date= 20 November 2012 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref> and is among the five largest resort operators in the country.<ref name=bluechip />\n\n==== Adaaran Hotels and Resorts ====\n[[File:Adaaran Club Rannalhi.jpg|thumb|300px|Adaaran Club Rannalhi]]\nBranded as \"Adaaran\",<ref>{{cite news|title=Aitken Spence Hotels re-brands its Maldivian properties|url=http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?nid=839441046|newspaper=Lanka Business Online|date=26 July 2006|accessdate=22 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120429134856/http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?nid=839441046|archive-date=29 April 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the company currently operates 5 hotels in properties located on the islands of Vadoo, [[Meedhupparu]], Rannalhi and Hudhuranfushi.<ref name=hotelAR /><ref name=\"adaaranExpand\">{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence to build new hotel in Maldives |author= Shirajiv SIRIMANE |url= http://www.dailynews.lk/2012/10/11/bus01.asp |newspaper= Daily News |date= 11 October 2012 |accessdate= 11 October 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20121012232146/http://www.dailynews.lk/2012/10/11/bus01.asp |archive-date= 12 October 2012 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===== Adaaran Club Rannalhi =====\nAdaaran Club Rannalhi is a 4 star resort located in Rannalhi, a southern island in the [[Mal\u00e9 Atoll]], with 30 water villas (one of the first resorts to adopt over-water accommodation in Maldives) and 100 beach villas with a room capacity of 132 rooms.<ref name=hotelAR />\n\n===== Adaaran Prestige Vadoo =====\nAdaaran Prestige Vadoo resort, acquired by Aitken Spence in October 2007 is the latest addition to the Group's resorts in Maldives.  Located in close proximity to [[Mal\u00e9]], it houses 50 luxury water villas including six Japanese styled water bungalows.<ref name=\"ARMaritimeCinec\" />\n\n===== Adaaran Select Hudhuran Fushi =====\nAdaaran Select Hudhuran Fushi is a 4 star resort comprising 137 villas that includes 37 luxury villas.<ref name=hotelAR />\n\n===== Adaraan Select Meedhupparu =====\nSituated on Meedhupparu Island in [[Raa Atoll]], Adaaran Select Meedhupparu is a 4 star resort with 215 beach and garden villas.<ref name=hotelAR />\n\n===== Adaraan Prestige Water Villas =====\nAdaaran Prestige Water Villas, also located in the [[Meedhupparu| Meedhupparu Island]], consists of 20 luxury water villas.<ref name=hotelAR />\n\n===== Heritance Aarah =====\nIn March 2015, Aitken Spence acquired \"Aarah\", another island property in Maldives in [[Raa Atoll]], to develop a 163-room, USD $ 50mn resort, having received Maldivian Government's approval to expand buildable area in Maldivian archipelago.<ref name=\"Aarah\">{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence adds another island to Maldivian resort portfolio |author=  |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/65135/aitken-spence-adds-another-island-to-maldivian-resort-portfolio |newspaper= Daily Mirror|date=2 March 2015 |accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ASHrebrand\">{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence plans rebranding hotels |author= Duruthu Edirimuni Chandrasekera |url= http://www.sundaytimes.lk/150301/business-times/aitken-spence-plans-rebranding-hotels-137325.html |newspaper= Sunday Times|date=1 March 2015 |accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"HeritanceBrandAarah\">{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence to Introduce Heritance Brand to Maldives with Aarah Opening 2018 |author=  |url= http://maldives.net.mv/18779/aitken-spence-to-introduce-heritance-brand-to-maldives-with-aarah-opening-2018/ |newspaper= Maldives Insider|date=18 May 2018 |accessdate=18 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nHeritance Aarah from Aitken Spence Hotels will be the group's first \u2018Heritance\u2019 property overseas.<ref name=\"HeritanceAarah\">{{cite news |title= Maldives magic stays |author=  |url= http://www.ttnworldwide.com/Article/278851/_Maldives_magic_stays |newspaper= Travel & Tourism News Middle East|date=18 June 2018 |accessdate=18 June 2018}}</ref> Heritance Aarah is scheduled to open in time for the winter season of 2018.<ref name=\"HeritanceAarahOpening\">{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence to plant first overseas Heritance in the Maldives |author=  |url= https://maldivestimes.com/aitken-spence-to-plant-first-overseas-heritance-in-the-maldives/ |newspaper= Maldives Times|date=10 May 2018 |accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ARMaritimeCinec\" />\n\n===== Raafushi Island =====\nIn May 2015, Aitken Spence obtained the lease for the Raafushi Island in the [[Noonu Atoll]] to build a four star resort.<ref name=\"ASraafushi\">{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence acquires 2 new properties in the Maldives |author=  |url= http://www.ttgasia.com/article.php?article_id=25191 |newspaper= TTG Asia |date= 27 May 2015 |accessdate= 28 May 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150528224028/http://www.ttgasia.com/article.php?article_id=25191 |archive-date= 28 May 2015 |url-status= dead }}</ref><ref name=\"ASraafushiNoonu\">{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence to develop more resorts in Maldives |author= Fathimath Zahuva |url= http://www.haveeru.com.mv/news/60666 |newspaper= Haveeru Online |date= 26 May 2015 |accessdate= 28 May 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150528230835/http://www.haveeru.com.mv/news/60666 |archive-date= 28 May 2015 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== India ===\n\n==== Turyaa Chennai ====\n\nIn June 2014, Aitken Spence announced the purchase of a brand new five star hotel in Chennai.<ref name=ResedaChennai>{{cite news |title= Reseda-The Fern, Chennai five-star hotel sold for Rs 150 crore |newspaper = The Economic Times, India |accessdate= 15 June 2014 |url= http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-06-12/news/50536607_1_chennai-five-star-hotel-occupancy-branded-rooms}}</ref> The company plans to commence operations of this hotel in July 2015 under the brand Turyaa Chennai.<ref name=\"ASHar2015\">{{cite web |url= https://www.cse.lk/cmt/upload_report_file/521_1433502972773.pdf |title= Aitken Spence Hotel Holdings PLC Annual Report 2014/2015 |accessdate= 7 June 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe 140-room property, Turyaa Chennai opened its doors on 1 October 2015 and is located in the IT Corridor of Chennai and just a short drive away from the heart of the city. The property obtained the \u201c5-Star Deluxe\u201d classification in 2017, ranking it as one of five hotels in Chennai to have obtained this highly sought after accreditation. In 2018, the property was awarded the 'best five-star deluxe hotel\u2019 in Tamil Nadu at the Tamil Nadu Tourism Awards 2018.<ref name=TuryaaChennai>{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence Hotels Turyaa Chennai amongst Top Five-Star Hotels in the City |newspaper = LBO |accessdate= 15 June 2017 |url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/aitken-spence-hotels-turyaa-chennai-amongst-top-five-star-hotels-in-the-city/}}</ref><ref name=TuryaaChennaiAward>{{cite news |title= Aitken Spence\u2019s Turyaa Chennai awarded best five-star deluxe in Tamil Nadu |newspaper = Daily FT |accessdate= 8 May 2018 |url= http://www.ft.lk/travel-tourism/Aitken-Spence-s-Turyaa-Chennai-awarded-best-five-star-deluxe-in-Tamil-Nadu/27-654025}}</ref>\n\n=== Oman ===\nIn Oman, Aitken Spence currently owns one hotel and manages five hotels:<ref name=\"OmanHotels\">{{cite news | title = Sri Lanka Spence Hotel mulls more properties in Oman | newspaper = economynext| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 12 June 2015 | url = http://www.economynext.com/Sri_Lanka_Spence_Hotel_mulls_more_properties_in_Oman-3-2062.html |accessdate=11 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== Al Falaj Hotel Muscat ====\n\nAl Falaj Hotel is a 140 roomed 4 star resort located in the city of [[Muscat, Oman|Muscat]]. Aitken Spence bought the hotel from Oman Hotels and Tourism Company for whom the company had been managing the property since 2008.<ref name=hotelAR /><ref name=\"AlFalajPurchase\">{{cite news | title = Aitken Spence\u2019s RO14mn offer for Al Falaj approved | newspaper = Muscat Daily| location = Muscat, Oman | date = 25 January 2016 | url = http://www.muscatdaily.com/Archive/Business/Aitken-Spence-s-RO14mn-offer-for-Al-Falaj-approved-4kiq |accessdate=8 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Al Wadi Hotel, Sohar ====\n\nAl Wadi Hotel is a 79-room 3 star resort in [[Sohar]].<ref name=hotelAR />\n\n==== Desert Nights Camp, Al Wasil ====\n\nDesert Nights Camp is a 5 star tented resort property with 30 Bedouin style tents located in Al Wasil, a township close to Muscat.<ref name=hotelAR />\n\n==== Ruwi Hotel, Muscat ====\n\nLocated in close proximity to Seeb International Airport, Ruwi Hotel is a 3 star hotel with 100 rooms.<ref name=hotelAR />\n\n==== Sur Plaza Hotel, Sur ====\n\nSur Plaza Hotel is a 4 star 95 room resort located in [[Sur, Oman|Sur]] in proximity to Green Turtle Beach at Ras-al-Hadd.<ref name=hotelAR />\n\n==== Jabal Akhdar Hotel, Nizwa ====\n\nJabal Akhdar Hotel is a 26-room boutique hotel located in [[Nizwa]], 152&nbsp;km from the Muscat International Airport.<ref name=\"JabalAkhdar\">{{cite news | title = Aitken Spence in US $ 25mn Indian hotel acquisition | newspaper = Daily Mirror| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 12 June 2014 | url = http://www.dailymirror.lk/business/features/48316-aitken-spence-in-us--25mn-indian-hotel-acquisition.html |accessdate=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Transport ==\n[[File:Hapag Lloyd Container 01.jpg|thumb|x200px | Aitken Spence Logistics offers container shipping]]\nAitken Spence offers integrated transportation services in air-sea freight forwarding, warehousing, distribution, couriers, ground transport and marine. Its services cover the complete physical cargo flow process from shipper to recipient.  It also handles third and fourth party logistics management contracts.<ref name=logistics>{{cite web|title= Aitken Spence Logistic Solutions|author= Aitken Spence|accessdate= 10 August 2012|url= http://www.aitkenspence.com/logistic_solutions/logistic_solutions_provider_sri_lanka.asp|archive-url= https://archive.is/20130116083828/http://www.aitkenspence.com/logistic_solutions/logistic_solutions_provider_sri_lanka.asp|archive-date= 16 January 2013|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> The company also represents [[DB Schenker]] in Sri Lanka and Maldives.<ref name=DBSlogistics>{{cite web |title= DB Schenker announces new forwarding partner in Sri Lanka|author= Lloyds Loading List |accessdate=28 October 2015 |url= http://www.lloydsloadinglist.com/freight-directory/news/DB-Schenker-announces-new-forwarding-partner-in-Sri-Lanka/64608.htm#.VjEHfcUrJdi}}</ref> Also, represents [[DPD Group]] and [[DTDC]] Express in Sri Lanka and Maldives.<ref name=DPDpartner>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence partners DPD Group for courier services. |author= Daily News|accessdate=14 March 2017 |url= http://www.dailynews.lk/2017/03/14/business/110317/aitken-spence-partners-dpd-group-courier-services}}</ref><ref name=DTDCpartner>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence partners with Europe\u2019s second largest int\u2019l parcel delivery network. |author= Mirror Business |accessdate=16 March 2017 |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/article/Aitken-Spence-partners-with-Europe-s-second-largest-int-l-parcel-delivery-network--125591.html}}</ref> The segment represents the cargo GSA for Qatar airways in Sri Lanka and the cargo GSA for Sri Lankan Airlines in Maldives and Myanmar, and are the managing agents for cargo GSA for Sri Lankan Airlines in Bangladesh.<ref name=ASCargoIntConference>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence hosts WACO International Conference in Colombo. |author= Lanka Business Online |accessdate=4 December 2015 |url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/aitken-spence-hosts-waco-international-conference-in-colombo/}}</ref>\n\n=== Cargo consolidation and storage facilities ===\nIn terms of cargo consolidation, the company offers both local and multi country cargo consolidation. In Sri Lanka, it operates its own container freight station with in-house customs that complies with [[Customs-Trade Partnership Against Terrorism|C-TPAT]] standards. Aitken Spence Cargo and Courier services provide air freight, ocean freight, supply chain management, brokerage, project cargo management and international and domestic courier as primary services and also specialize in airline cargo GSA representation [http://aitkenspence.com/logistics-2/cargo-courier-services/ Aitken Spence Logistics]. Aitken Spence Logistics also services shipments of garments through its garments on hanger facilities and quality assurance centre facilities. The company also offers refrigerated storage services in terms of cold rooms and [[Refrigerated container|reefer]] containers to its clients.\n\nWith respect to warehousing facilities in Sri Lanka, Aitken Spence operates a central cargo storage complexses with a total floor area exceeding 300,000 sqft, located in Colombo, Wattala, Mabole and Katunayake Zone with a modern fleet of equipment and cargo handling machinery.<ref name=ARLogisticsHighlights>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Annual Report Logistics 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=10 July 2018 |url= http://aitkenspence.com/annualreport/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Aitken Spence Logistics enhanced by world class equipment |newspaper=Sunday Times |accessdate=4 March 2018 |url= http://www.sundaytimes.lk/180304/business-times/aitken-spence-logistics-enhanced-by-world-class-equipment-283896.html}}</ref>\n\n=== Container handling, repair and modification facilities ===\nThe container services arm of Aitken Spence Logistics that processes a container every two minutes is the first company in Sri Lanka to operate its own container depot (first at Mattakkuliya in 1979 and shifted to Mabole in 1989).<ref name=containerDepot>{{cite web |title= Reliably Consolidated|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=10 August 2012 |url= http://aitkenspenceplc.wordpress.com/tag/mattakuliya/}}</ref> In addition, Aitken Spence also runs a Lloyd's approved facility for container modification and repair services.<ref>{{cite news |title=Aitken Spence Logistics opens new Container Repair and Rigging Facility |newspaper=Sunday Times |date=1 June 2014 |accessdate=3 July 2018  |url= http://www.sundaytimes.lk/140601/business-times/aitken-spence-logistics-opens-new-container-repair-and-rigging-facility-100546.html}}</ref>\n\nThe company provides import and export container handling services, handling transshipment cargo, and the servicing of passenger cruise vessels, car carriers and casual callers.<ref name=ARShipping>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Annual Report 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=18 June 2018 |url= http://aitkenspence.com/annualreport/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Aitken Spence Logistics pursues continuous fleet enhancement |newspaper=Daily News |date=2 March 2018 |accessdate=30 May 2018 |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2018/03/02/business/144345/aitken-spence-logistics-pursues-continuous-fleet-enhancementy }}{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n=== Ground transport and project cargo handling ===\nAitken Spence also offers transportation through its transport fleet of prime movers with 20\u2019/40\u2019 trailers, lorries and tank trucks.<ref name=logistics /> The Group is also capable in handling Heavy Over-Dimensional Project cargo. It is also the agent for Flexi Tank Services in Sri Lanka for Trans Ocean Distribution.<ref name=logistics />\n\n=== Freight forwarding, courier services and air cargo ===\n[[File:Stern of the Colombo Express.jpg|thumb|x200px|Hapag Lloyd is represented in Sri Lanka through Aitken Spence Maritime]]\nIn addition to its own haulage, Aitken Spence also provides freight forwarding through its global partner network. Aitken Spence Cargo, specialized freight-forwarding arm of Aitken Spence, provides air freight, sea freight, brokerage, customs facilitation and supply chain [[solution]]s to clients in Sri Lanka, Bangladesh and Maldives.<ref name=logistics />\n\nAitken Spence handles cargo sales agencies for [[Singapore Airlines Cargo]], [[Livingston Energy Flight|Livingston Air]], [[Air Jamaica]], [[Air Italy]], [[Thomas Cook Airlines Scandinavia|My Travels]], [[Qatar Airways Cargo]] and [[EVA Air]] in Sri Lanka. It is also the General Sales Agents (Cargo) for My Travels in Maldives & Bangladesh; Livingston Air in Bangladesh, Singapore and Thailand; [[Continental Airlines Cargo]] in Bangladesh, while being the cargo sales agents for Livingston Air and [[SriLankan Airlines#Cargo|SriLankan Airlines Cargo]] in the Maldives.\n\nAitken Spence Group represents [[TNT Express]] courier services in Sri Lanka and provides both domestic and international courier services. It also represents Spring Global Mail in Sri Lanka.<ref name=logistics />\n\n=== Maritime services ===\nAitken Spence offers services in the maritime sector through its maritime wing, Aitken Spence Maritime. Its services include liner agency representation(of G6 Alliance), cruise vessel representation, feeder and casual caller representation, break bulk facilities, and ship servicing and facilitation (crew services, bunkering, repairs, supply of provisions) for ports in Sri Lanka.  It also provides ship chartering services.<ref name=logistics />\n\nIn January 2005, in a joint venture with Ceyline Holdings, Aitken Spence re-entered the ship owning for time charter business in order to profit from the then shipping boom.<ref name=ShipOwning>{{cite web|title= Aitken Spence to invest $ 7.5 million on two vessels.|author= Daily News|accessdate= 16 May 2013|url= http://www.dailynews.lk/2004/12/09/bus02.html|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20050219074029/http://www.dailynews.lk/2004/12/09/bus02.html|archive-date= 19 February 2005|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=ShipOwning2>{{cite web |title= Spence to double fleet to 10 ships. |author= Sunday Times|accessdate=16 May 2013 |url= http://www.sundaytimes.lk/050626/ft/2.html}}</ref> In 2007, with the saturation of the ship chartering market, Aitken Spence exited the ship owning business and shifted its strategic focus to expanding its port management business. \n<ref name=ShipDivesting>{{cite web |title= Sri Lanka conglomerate sells off ships |author= Lanka Business Online |accessdate= 16 May 2013 |url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/Sri_Lanka_conglomerate_sells_off_ships/424491405 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131216211915/http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/Sri_Lanka_conglomerate_sells_off_ships/424491405 |archive-date= 16 December 2013 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=PortManagement>{{cite web|title= Sri Lanka's Aitken Spence hunts port management business|author= Lanka Business Online|accessdate= 16 May 2013|url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/Sri_Lankas_Aitken_Spence_hunts_port_management_business/1347781965|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130513065245/http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/Sri_Lankas_Aitken_Spence_hunts_port_management_business/1347781965|archive-date= 13 May 2013|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Aitken Spence in partnership with [[PSA International|Port of Singapore Authority]] submitted a joint bid to build and operate the South Container Terminal of the [[Colombo Harbor#Expansion project|Colombo Port Expansion Project]]. When the initial bidding process of [[Sri Lanka Port Authority]] (SLPA) stalled and was reactivated, Aitken Spence partnered with [[China Merchants Holdings (International)|China Merchant Holdings International]] and was the sole bidder in support of the project.<ref name=SouthPortBid1>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence port bid in our national interest |author= The Sunday Times|accessdate=16 May 2013 |url= http://www.sundaytimes.lk/080302/FinancialTimes/ft334.html}}</ref><ref name=SouthPortBid2>{{cite web |title= A wise call on Colombo South Port |author= The Sunday Times|accessdate=8 December 2013 |url= http://www.sundaytimes.lk/090830/FinancialTimes/ft39.html}}</ref> In 2010, the bid was approved by SLPA and construction began on the US$450 million project.<ref name=PortProject>{{cite web |title= Sri Lanka awards Rs. 50 bn Colombo South Port deal to China Holdings - Aitken Spence consortium  |author= Asian Tribune |accessdate=16 May 2013 |url= http://www.asiantribune.com/news/2010/09/17/sri-lanka-awards-rs-50-bn-colombo-south-port-deal-china-holdings-aitken-spence-conso}}</ref><ref name=PortProject2>{{cite web|title= Deal signed to build Colombo Port Expansion project\u2019s South Container Terminal|author= Daily FT|accessdate= 16 May 2013|url= http://www.ft.lk/2011/11/14/deal-signed-to-build-colombo-port-expansion-project%E2%80%99s-south-container-terminal/|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131212151153/http://www.ft.lk/2011/11/14/deal-signed-to-build-colombo-port-expansion-project%E2%80%99s-south-container-terminal/|archive-date= 12 December 2013|url-status= dead}}</ref>  However, in 2012, citing cost escalations and changes in financing requirements, Aitken Spence sold its stake to CMHI in 2012, realizing a LKR Rs. 630 million capital gain.<ref name=cmbPortExit>{{cite web |title= Sri Lanka conglomerate sells stake on Colombo Port project for Rs. 630 million|author= Lanka Newspapers|accessdate=16 May 2013 |url= http://www.lankanewspapers.com/news/2012/1/74081.html}}</ref><ref name=cmbPortExit2>{{cite news |title= Sri Lanka's Aitken Spence sells port stake to China Merchants |author= Reuters|accessdate=16 May 2013 |url= http://uk.reuters.com/article/2012/01/23/srilanka-port-spence-idUKL4E8CN4PO20120123 |date=23 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nAitken Spence is the first Sri Lankan company to venture into port efficiency improvement, training and container terminal management overseas with its operations in the African continent.<ref name=logistics /> As a result of the strategic partnership with the Port of Durban from 2006, Aitken Spence won a \"ship planning and mentoring\" project covering the Ports of Durban, Cape Town and Ngqura in South Africa in 2010. In 2011, Aitken Spence announced that it has won a deal to improve the efficiency of Port of Nacala in Mozambique.<ref name=PortEfficiency>{{cite web|title= Sri Lanka Aitken Spence to make Mozambique port efficient.|author= Lanka Business Online|accessdate= 10 August 2012|url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?nid=1702158326|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20121123224538/http://lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?nid=1702158326|archive-date= 23 November 2012|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> In 2013, Aitken Spence took over the management of two Fijian ports, [[Suva]] and [[Lautoka]], with its purchase of 51% of Fiji Ports Terminal Ltd, a 100% owned subsidiary of Fiji Ports Corporation Ltd.<ref name=\"fijiPortMgmt\"/><ref name=FijiPort/><ref name=fijiEfficiency>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence aims to get port efficiency, productivity. |author= Fiji Sun|accessdate=4 August 2013 |url= http://www.fijisun.com.fj/2013/08/01/aitken-spence-aims-to-get-port-efficiency-productivity/}}</ref> The company further consolidated its presence in the Fijian maritime sector in acquiring a 20% stake in Fiji Ports Corporation Ltd. in November 2015.<ref name=\"fijiPortCorp\">{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence buys 20% stake in Fiji Ports Corp for $ 16 m; expands footprint in South Pacific   |author= Daily FT|accessdate=6 November 2015 |url= http://www.ft.lk/article/493071/Aitken-Spence-buys-20--stake-in-Fiji-Ports-Corp-for---16-m--expands-footprint-in-South-Pacific}}</ref><ref name=ASFiji>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence expands Fiji operations   |author= Mirror Business|accessdate=6 November 2015 |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/94255/aitken-spence-expands-fiji-operations}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Aitken Spence renewed its alliance with Ceyline Group of Companies when it invested in [[CINEC|Colombo International Nautical and Engineering College (CINEC)]].<ref name=CINEC1>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence in strategic partnership with CINEC Maritime Campus. |author= The Nation|accessdate=16 May 2013 |url= http://www.nation.lk/2010/04/11/busi5.htm}}</ref><ref name=CINEC2>{{cite web|title= Sri Lanka Aitken Spence mulls overseas maritime campus.|author= Lanka Business Online|accessdate= 16 May 2013|url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/sri-lanka-aitken-spence-mulls-overseas-maritime-campus/1064979551|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131216211313/http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/sri-lanka-aitken-spence-mulls-overseas-maritime-campus/1064979551|archive-date= 16 December 2013|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> In 2012, Aitken Spence increased its stake in CINEC from 10% to 40% in a move to further strengthen its maritime portfolio.<ref name=CINEC3>{{cite web|title= Sri Lanka Aitken Spence December net up 41-pct|author= Lanka Business Online|accessdate= 16 May 2013|url= http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/Sri_Lanka_Aitken_Spence_December_net_up_41-pct/888547756|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130514123329/http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/Sri_Lanka_Aitken_Spence_December_net_up_41-pct/888547756|archive-date= 14 May 2013|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> Located in Malabe, the CINEC Campus is Sri Lanka's largest private higher education institution and also has branches in\nColombo, Trincomalee and Jaffna. CINEC also manages the maritime academies in Fiji and Seychelles.<ref name=ARMaritimeCinec>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Annual Report 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=18 June 2018 |url= http://aitkenspence.com/annualreport/}}</ref> In 2013, further to Aitken Spence's entry into port management in Fiji, Fijian Government announced plans to invite CINEC to manage [[Fiji National University|Fiji National University's]] maritime school.<ref name=AScinecFiji>{{cite web |title=Aitken Spence boosts Fiji Port efficiencies by 35 pc in two months |author=Daily News |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/business/aitken-spence-boosts-fiji-port-efficiencies-35-pc-two-months#sthash.ENSNHQBs.dpuf |accessdate=15 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216211854/http://www.dailynews.lk/business/aitken-spence-boosts-fiji-port-efficiencies-35-pc-two-months#sthash.ENSNHQBs.dpuf |archive-date=16 December 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=CINECfnu>{{cite web |title= 2014 Fiji National Budget Speech by PM Commodore Voreqe Bainimarama |author= Mai Life Magazine|accessdate=22 November 2013 |url= http://www.mailife.com.fj/2013/11/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Cinec unveils ship shaped training facility on campus|newspaper=Hiru News |date=15 July 2015 |accessdate=26 March 2017  |url= http://www.hirunews.lk/business/113212/cinec-unveils-ship-shaped-training-facility-on-campus}}</ref>\n\n== Services ==\nIn the services sector, Aitken Spence operates in a number of key domains: inbound tourism, outbound travel, airline agencies, conventions and exhibitions, elevator agency, financial services, insurance, business and knowledge process outsourcing and luxury lifestyle [[solution]]s.{{clarify|date=September 2018}}<ref name=services>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Services|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=10 May 2017 |url= http://aitkenspence.com/services/}}</ref>\n\n=== Destination management ===\n[[File:SIA Boeing 747-400, 9V-SPF, SIN 5.jpg|thumb|x200px |Aitken Spence has represented Singapore Airlines in Sri Lanka since 1972]]\nWith regards to inbound tourism sector, Aitken Spence Travels \u2013 a joint venture with [[TUI Travel|TUI]]\u2014is the largest [[destination management company]] in Sri Lanka representing over 200 international tour operators, and has been recognized with Sri Lanka's Presidential Award for the Best Destination Management Company and leading Destination Management Company at the World Travel Awards in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |title=Aitken Spence Travels, Lanka\u2019s leading DMC at World Travel Awards |newspaper=Daily News |date=8 August 2017 |accessdate=6 March 2018 |url= http://www.dailynews.lk/2017/08/08/business/124447/aitken-spence-travels-lanka%E2%80%99s-leading-dmc-world-travel-awards}}</ref><ref name=servicestravels>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Services Destination Management|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=10 October 2017 |url= http://aitkenspence.com/services/travels/}}</ref> The outbound travel arm of Aitken Spence Travels is an [[IATA]] approved outbound travel agency and has been in operation since 1975, making it one of the oldest IATA agencies in Sri Lanka. In addition to its core business of airline ticketing, it is also the general sales agent for [[Rail Europe, Inc.]] and Tradewinds. Aitken Spence Travels is also the representative in Sri Lanka for [[CWT (company)|CWT]], a global [[travel management company]].<ref name=services /> Aitken Spence is also the preferred partner of [[The Emirates Group#Travel|Emirates Holidays]] in Sri Lanka.<ref name=SpenEmirates>{{cite web |title= In-bound tourist traffic provokes Emirates and Aitken Spence to enhance visitor convenience |newspaper= The Island|accessdate=24 November 2013 |url= http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=92557}}</ref> In financial year 2017/2018, Aitken Spence Travels handled over 178,000 tourists to Sri Lanka.<ref name=178Kvisitors>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Travels records landmark 178,000 happy visitors to Sri Lanka|newspaper= Daily FT|accessdate=18 May 2018 |url= http://www.ft.lk/travel-tourism/Aitken-Spence-Travels-records-landmark-178-000-happy-visitors-to-Sri-Lanka/27-655376}}</ref>\n\n=== Event management and MICE ===\n\nAitken Spence Conventions & Exhibitions is the event management arm of the Aitken Spence PLC and is specialized in organizing Meetings, Incentives, Conferences & Exhibitions in Sri Lanka and the Maldives.[http://aitkenspenceconventions.com/ Aitken Spence Conventions & Exhibitions]<ref name=Conventions>{{cite web|title= Focus on regional markets for international parleys|newspaper= The Sunday Observer|accessdate= 24 November 2013|url= http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2008/02/17/fin14.asp|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131202222832/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2008/02/17/fin14.asp|archive-date= 2 December 2013|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=ASexhibitions>{{cite web |title= \nAitken Spence bags top Travel Awards |newspaper= Daily Mirror|accessdate=24 November 2013 |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/travel/business-travel/21617-aitken-spence-bags-top-travel-awards-.html}}</ref><ref name=ASexhibition>{{cite web |title= \nAitken Spence Conventions & Exhibitions to coordinate conference  |newspaper= The Island|accessdate=12 March 2014 |url= http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=99438}}</ref> The company also represents Pacific World MICE company in Sri Lanka and the Maldives.<ref name=PacificWorld>{{cite web |title= \nPacific World Expands Presence To Sri Lanka And Maldives With Aitken Spence  |newspaper= Daily Mirror|accessdate=21 November 2014 |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/56907/pacific-world-expands-presence-to-sri-lanka-and-maldives-with-aitken-spence}}</ref>\n\n=== Airline agency ===\nIn terms of airline agency services, Aitken Spence acts as the General Sales Agent for [[Singapore Airlines|Singapore International Airlines]] in Sri Lanka and the Maldives. Aitken Spence is also the General Sales Agent for [[SriLankan Airlines]] in Maldives.<ref name=services />\n\n=== Financial services ===\nIn the financial services sector, Aitken Spence in a joint venture with Mercantile Merchant Bank, Sri Lanka offers [[Western Union|Western Union Money Transfer services]] in Sri Lanka with a network of over 2000 sub-agent locations countrywide, which includes banks, financial institutions and retail outlets.<ref name=services /> As an authorized agent for Western Union in Sri Lanka, the Group's money transfer services business has a commanding 65% share of the Western Union business in Sri Lanka.<ref name=ARServicesWU>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Annual Report 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=11 July 2018 |url= http://aitkenspence.com/annualreport/}}</ref>\n\nAitken Spence serves as survey and claim settling agents for [[Lloyd's of London]] since 1876, covering the commercial ports in Sri Lanka and the Republic of Maldives. It also carries out quality surveys and hull and machinery surveys. In addition, Aitken Spence Insurance also acts as survey and claims settling agents for several other reputed insurance companies worldwide including [[Aviva|AVIVA]], [[People's Insurance Company of China]], Oriental Insurance Co. of India, [[New India Assurance]], [[IFFCO Tokio General Insurance Company Limited|Iffco-Tokio]] of India, [[RSA Insurance Group|Royal & Sun Alliance Group]], Northern Marine Underwriters, China Pacific Property Insurance Co. Ltd, [[Mitsui Sumitomo Insurance Group|Sumitomo Fire & Marine Insurance Co. Ltd.]], [[Tokio Marine Nichido|Tokyo Marine & Fire Insurance Co.]] of Japan, Cesam of France, QBE Insurance of Singapore and [[American Home Assurance Company]] since 1949.<ref name=services />\n\n=== Knowledge and information technology ===\nThe Group also provides human resources consulting in Sri Lanka and overseas under brand \"Genuity\".<ref name=services />\n\nAitken Spence Technologies offers IT in, [[Enterprise Content Management]] (ECM), [[Enterprise Resource Planning]] (ERP), both based on core-[[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]] Applications and Technologies, and Application Development based on Open Source/Java technologies.<ref name=IT>{{cite web|title= Calspence Technologies consolidates and re-brands|author= FT Sri Lanka|accessdate= 10 August 2012|url= http://www.ft.lk/2012/02/23/calspence-technologies-consolidates-and-re-brands/|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131019161750/http://www.ft.lk/2012/02/23/calspence-technologies-consolidates-and-re-brands/|archive-date= 19 October 2013|url-status= dead}}</ref><ref name=KiaEBS>{{cite web|title= Kia with Aitken Spence to deploy Oracle Solution to automate processes.|author= Lanka Business Today|accessdate= 19 May 2015|url= http://www.lankabusinesstoday.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=9106:kia-with-aitken-spence-to-deploy-oracle-solution-to-automate-processes&catid=54:business&Itemid=76}}{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 2012, Aitken Spence was appointed as [[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]] University Education Re-seller Partner and Approved Training Centre.<ref name=OracleUni>{{cite web|title= Aitken Spence Technologies appointed Oracle Uni approved re-seller partner, training centre.|author= FT Sri Lanka|accessdate= 4 June 2013|url= http://www.ft.lk/2012/03/03/aitken-spence-technologies-appointed-oracle-uni-approved-re-seller-partner-training-centre/|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130604100005/http://www.ft.lk/2012/03/03/aitken-spence-technologies-appointed-oracle-uni-approved-re-seller-partner-training-centre/|archive-date= 4 June 2013|url-status= dead}}</ref> Aitken Spence Technologies is also a member of [[IBM|IBM PartnerWorld]] program.<ref name=IBM>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Technologies |accessdate=15 October 2013 |url= http://www.aitkenspencetech.com/}}</ref> In October 2013, '''PlantERM''', the Enterprise Resource Management application developed for the first time in Sri Lanka for the plantation sector by Aitken Spence Technologies, received the NBQSA Gold Award in the General Applications category.<ref name=NBQSA2013>{{cite web |title= NBQSA 2013 Winners |accessdate=18 October 2013 |url= http://www.nbqsasrilanka.org/node/75/}}</ref>\n\nAitken Spence offers financcial accounting outsourcing services through its subsidiary Aitken Spence Business Solutions in Sri Lanka, Maldives and Bangladesh. The business solutions partners include; Citi Bank, HSBC, Deutsche Bank and Standard Chartered Bank on the electronic banking and Oracle in the ERP solutions.<ref name=BPO>{{cite web|title= Aitken Spence to ride on BPO boom.|author= FT Sri Lanka|accessdate= 10 August 2012|url= http://www.ft.lk/2011/03/22/aitken-spence-to-ride-on-bpo-boom/|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110426121733/http://www.ft.lk/2011/03/22/aitken-spence-to-ride-on-bpo-boom/|archive-date= 26 April 2011|url-status= dead}}</ref><ref name=Spencebpo>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Business Solutions |accessdate=15 October 2013 |url= http://www.spencebpo.com/3-services.html}}</ref>[https://aitkenspence.com/services/financial-accounting-outsourcing/ Aitken Spence Business Solutions]\n\n=== Elevator agency ===\n\nAitken Spence also provides elevator services acting as the agent for [[Otis Elevator Company|OTIS]] Elevators (part of [[United Technologies Corporation]]) in Sri Lanka and Maldives since 1989.<ref name=services />\n\n==Strategic investments==\n\n===Power generation===\n\nAitken Spence first entered the power sector in 1996 in a joint venture with a Japanese investor to build two thermal power plants in Sri Lanka<ref name=\"jvjp\"/> with the Government of Sri Lanka inviting private sector to invest in resolving the then power crisis. However, due to the longevity of the process in obtaining clearances, the Japanese partner backed out and in 1999, Aitken Spence (51%) partnered with [[Commonwealth Development Corporation]] Globeleq (29%), Baneras House of India (10%) and [[Wartsila|Wartsila Finland Oy]] (10%) to construct the [[Ace Matara Power Station]] (24.4MW) and [[Ace Horana Power Station]] (24.4MW).<ref name=\"hnb\">{{cite news | title = HNB leads landmark financing deal of US$ 88 million | newspaper = The Sunday Leader| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 10 August 2003 | url = http://www.thesundayleader.lk/archive/20030810/business-3.htm| accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref> Subsequently, following a Request for Proposal by [[Ceylon Electricity Board]] (CEB) in February 2002, Aitken Spence together with [[Caterpillar Inc.|Caterpillar Power Ventures Corporation]] began the construction of the [[Embilipitiya Power Station]] (100MW), which came online in April 2005.<ref name=\"hnb\" /><ref name=\"cat\">{{cite web |url= http://www.cat.com/cda/files/698809/7/CPGS_SriLanka.pdf |title= Ace Power Embilipitiya |accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nAce Power Embilipitiya thermal power plant opeartes on a 100MW while the Branford Hydro power plant operates at 2.5MW, Ace Wind power plant at 3MW  and Western Power at 10MW capacity.<ref name=ARACEPOWER>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Annual Report 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=10 July 2018 |url= http://aitkenspence.com/annualreport/}}</ref> The Power Purchase Agreement (PPA) between the [[Ceylon Electricity Board]] and Ace Power Embilipitiya lapsed in 2015; however, renewed the agreement for a one more year in April, 2016, when the country ran into power crisis after two back-to-back blackouts in late 2015 and early 2016. During the first quarter of 2018, the government decided to extend the purchasing of the thermal power for three more years as the country had four seasons of back-to-back dry spells, which exhausted reservoirs and the crucial catchment areas.<ref name=\"acepower\">{{cite web |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/article/Government-extends-agreement-with-Ace-Power-for-three-more-years-to-avert-power-crisis-148133.html |title= Government extends agreement with Ace Power for three more years to avert power crisis |newspaper = Mirror Business |accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:AitkenSpenceWindPower-Ambewela-September2012-1.jpg|thumb|x200px|Ace Wind Power, Ambewela]]\n\n====Hydro, Wind, Solar, Waste-to-Energy and Dendro Power====\n\nAitken Spence has also sought to diversify its power portfolio with increased presence in the clean and renewable energy domain in Sri Lanka.\n\nAitken Spence Power has already completed construction of the 2.5 MW '''Branford Hydro Power''' Plant in Matale, and of [[Ambewela Aitken Spence Wind Farm|Ace Wind Power]] power plant in [[Ambewela]]<ref name=\"renew\">{{cite news|title=Blue chips eye more hydro, wind power plants |newspaper=Daily News |location=Colombo, Sri Lanka |date=8 June 2011 |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2011/06/08/bus05.asp |accessdate=9 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110823125438/http://www.dailynews.lk/2011/06/08/bus05.asp |archivedate=23 August 2011 }}</ref> that has an installed capacity of 3 MW. Both power plants were connected to the national grid during 2012/13 financial year.<ref name=\"ASar2012\">{{cite web|title= Aitken Spence PLC Annual Report 2011/2012|author= Aitken Spence|accessdate= 9 October 2012|url= http://www.aitkenspence.com/pdf/ar2012/aitken_spence_plc_ar_2011_12_changed_1.pdf|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130512213943/http://www.aitkenspence.com/pdf/ar2012/aitken_spence_plc_ar_2011_12_changed_1.pdf|archive-date= 12 May 2013|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> Aitken Spence Power is also currently building the [[Aitken Spence Power Station]], Waste-To-Energy Coprocessing Plant at Muthurajawela.<ref name=\"coprocessing\">{{cite news| title = Garbage Power At Rs. 22 A Unit| newspaper = The Sunday Leader| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka| date = 13 November 2011| url = http://www.thesundayleader.lk/2011/11/13/garbage-power-at-rs-22-a-unit/| accessdate = 9 October 2012| archive-url = https://archive.is/20130218220708/http://www.thesundayleader.lk/2011/11/13/garbage-power-at-rs-22-a-unit/| archive-date = 18 February 2013| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAce Power embarked on a landmark project in the country's waste to energy sphere. Seen as a vital and much needed solution for the waste disposal crisis within Colombo city limits, the proposed project involves the construction of a 10MW waste-toenergy plant at Muthurajawela. The plant will be fuelled by waste collected from the Colombo Municipal Area, which was previously dumped in Meethotamulla. The plant is equipped to convert between 600 \u2013 800 metric tonnes of municipal solid waste daily to electricity. Estimated to cost Rs. 13 billion on completion, the project is funded through a combination of equity and term loan funding. The construction work on the project commenced following the ground-breaking ceremony held in August 2017 with the participation of the president. This new waste to energy project is due to commence commercial operations in 2019.<ref name=\"wastetoenergy\">{{cite news | title = Sri Lanka starts work on two 10MW waste-to-energy plants | newspaper = Economy Next | date = 10 August 2017 | url = http://www.economynext.com/Sri_Lanka_starts_work_on_two_10MW_waste_to_energy_plants-3-8486-.html}}</ref><ref name=\"wastetoenergyplant\">{{cite news | title = HNB concludes Syndicated Term Loan for Sri Lanka\u2019s first waste to energy plant | newspaper = Lanka Business Online | date = 31 May 2018 | url = http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/hnb-concludes-syndicated-term-loan-for-sri-lankas-first-waste-to-energy-plant/}}</ref>\n\nAitken Spence Hotels (through biomass plants and solar generation)<ref name=\"hotelrenew\">{{cite news | title = Sri Lanka's Aitken Spence in renewable energy drive | newspaper = Lanka Business Online | location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 5 October 2012 | url = http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?nid=2104555452 | accessdate = 9 October 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121102014945/http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?nid=2104555452 | archive-date = 2 November 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> and Plantations (through mini hydro projects)<ref name=\"plantationHydro\">{{cite news | title = Elpitiya Plantations recognised for hydro power generation | newspaper = ft.lk | location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 13 August 2012 | url = http://www.ft.lk/2012/08/13/elpitiya-plantations-recognised-for-hydro-power-generation/ | accessdate = 9 October 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120815024257/http://www.ft.lk/2012/08/13/elpitiya-plantations-recognised-for-hydro-power-generation/ | archive-date = 15 August 2012 | url-status = dead }}</ref> have also undertaken mini power projects of their own. Heritance Ayurveda Maha Gedara is the first hotel in Sri Lanka to enter into a net metering agreement with CEB.<ref name=\"hotelrenew\"/>\n\n===Plantation services===\n[[File:Dunsinane Estate, Elpitiya Plantation.jpg|thumb|left| Dunsinane Estate, Nuwara Eliya]]\nAitken Spence has been in the plantations industry from the early 1900s.<ref name=\"superbrand\">{{cite web |url= http://www.superbrands.com/lkb1/pdf/aitkenspence.pdf |title= Aitken Spence |accessdate= 9 October 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131216212024/http://www.superbrands.com/lkb1/pdf/aitkenspence.pdf |archive-date= 16 December 2013 |url-status= dead }}</ref> In 1975, the estates originally owned by Aitken Spence were acquired under the plantation nationalization program. In 1992, with the re-privatization of plantations industry, Aitken Spence reentered the sector in taking over the management of Udapussellawa Plantation PLC. It also invested in a minority stake in Talawakelle Plantations. Aitken Spence later divested its stake in Udapussellawa and Talawakelle Plantations<ref name=\"talawakelle\">{{cite news | title = Talawakelle posts record profit and turnover| newspaper = The Island| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka| date = 2 April 2011 | url = http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=22230| accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe management of Elpitiya Plantations PLC was taken over by Aitken Spence in 1997 from Carsons through Aitken Spence Plantations Managements Ltd. The Group currently manages 13 estates (with over 8800 hectares of cultivated land) in Sri Lanka, producing high, mid and low grown teas.<ref name=ARplantationssummary>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Annual Report 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=5 June 2018 |url= http://aitkenspence.com/annualreport/}}</ref> From the 13 estates, six estates are located on the up cluster in [[Kandy]] and [[Nuwara Eliya]] districts (estates: Dunsinane, Sheen, Fernlands, Meddecombra, New Peacock and Nayapane) and seven estates in the low cluster (Deviturai, Talgaswella, Gulugahakanda, Lelwala, Ketandola, Bentota and Elpitiya). These estates conform with multiple standards on sustainability\nincluding ISO 22000 for food safety management system, [[Rainforest Alliance|Rainforest Alliance certification]], [[Ethical Tea Partnership]] and [[Forest Stewardship Council]] certification.<ref name=\"EthicalTea\">{{cite news | title = Sri Lanka's New Peacock Estate claim highest yield among large tea farms| newspaper = economynext | location = Colombo, Sri Lanka| date = 22 April 2015 | url = http://www.economynext.com/Sri_Lanka_s_New_Peacock_Estate_claim_highest_yield_among_large_tea_farms-3-1586-9.html| accessdate=22 April 2015}}</ref> In addition to tea, Elpitiya Plantations also produces rubber, coconut, cinnamon and palm oil.<ref name=\"ARplantations\">{{cite web |url= http://aitkenspence.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Aitken-Spence-PLC-AR-2017-18.pdf |title= Annual Report Strategic Investments Plantations |accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nGroup has diversified its plantation operations into other areas such as palm oil processing, hydro power development, speciality tea manufacturing and eco tourism.\n\nThe Group also has its own tea brand for black tea and green tea in Sri Lanka under the name \"Harrow Ceylon Choice\".\n\nIn January 2013, Elpitiya Plantations PLC entered a joint venture with Dianhong International Limited, Hong Kong, a subsidiary of Yunnan Dianhong Group Company Limited of China, to grow and process tea in Sri Lanka for Chinese Speciality Tea market.<ref name=\"TeaBoI\">{{cite news | title = New BoI project signed to produce tea for Chinese market| newspaper = Ceylon Today | location = Colombo, Sri Lanka| date = 25 January 2013 | url = http://www.ceylontoday.lk/22-22854-news-detail-new-boi-project-signed-to-produce-tea-for-chinese-market.html| accessdate=9 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"TeaDYGCL\">{{cite news| title = Lankan Tea taps Chinese investment| newspaper = The Nation| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka| date = 27 January 2013| url = http://www.nation.lk/edition/biz-news/item/15069-lankan-tea-taps-chinese-investment.html| accessdate = 9 October 2013| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131014173926/http://www.nation.lk/edition/biz-news/item/15069-lankan-tea-taps-chinese-investment.html| archive-date = 14 October 2013| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, shares of Aitken Spence Plantation Managements Ltd was introduced to the Colombo Stock Exchange.<ref name=\"aspmCSE\">{{cite news| title = Aitken Spence Sri Lanka plantation unit to be listed| newspaper = Lanka Business Online| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka| date = 4 April 2013| url = http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/Aitken_Spence_Sri_Lanka_plantation_unit_to_be_listed/1644914590| accessdate = 9 October 2013| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131216201050/http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/news/Aitken_Spence_Sri_Lanka_plantation_unit_to_be_listed/1644914590| archive-date = 16 December 2013| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Garment manufacturing===\n\nAitken Spence entered the garments manufacturing sector in 1979<ref name=\"garmentsweb\" /> with its factory at Mattakkuliya.<ref name=\"mattakkuliyagarments\">{{cite news | title = Maldivian link saves the day for Aitken Spence| newspaper = Sunday Times| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 18 February 2001 | url = http://sundaytimes.lk/010218/busm.html| accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref> Currently, Aitken Spence operates two factories in Sri Lanka\u2014in [[Matugama]] (opened in 1993 in support of the 200 garment factories initiative of the then Government of Sri Lanka)<ref name=\"ARtimeline\"/> and at Koggala Export Processing Zone (since 2008)<ref name=\"koggalaopen\">{{cite news | title = Aitken Spence Q3profit up by 16% to Rs 1.9b| newspaper = The Island| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 14 February 2008 | url = http://www.island.lk/2008/02/14/business7.html | accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref>\u2014that manufactures and exports clothing for clients such as [[The Gap, Inc.]], [[Columbia Sportswear]], [[Kohl's]] and [[Sears]] in the US, and [[Marks & Spencer]] Work Wear, [[Sainsbury's]], [[Tesco]], [[Waitrose]], Boots and Marriot in Europe.<ref name=\"garmentsweb\"/>\n\n===Printing===\n\nIn 1955, Clark Spence & Co. opened its own press to service its internal printing needs in Galle. Printing services were gradually opened for external parties and with the higher demand, the service offering was expanded with a full-fledged printing plant. Subsequently, in 1962, printing plant was moved from Galle to Colombo (Vauxhall St. Colombo 02 premises, where current Aitken Spence Group Headquarters is located) and ownership transferred to Aitken Spence & Co.<ref name=\"printbegin\">{{cite web |url= http://aitkenspenceplc.wordpress.com/2009/11/16/our-printing-heritage-2/|title= Our Printing Heritage |accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Galle2Colombo\">{{cite news | title = Amherst, El Alamein and Aitken Spence | newspaper = Sunday Times| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | url = http://www.sundaytimes.lk/030406/plus/6.html| accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref>\n[[File:Aitken Spence Green Printing Facility.JPG|thumb|x225px|Aitken Spence Green Printing Facility]]\nIn 1977, whole printing department was burnt from a fire and its operations were halted. In 1982, a new printing plant was built at Bloemendhal Road, Colombo 13 to resume printing services.<ref name=\"printbegin\"/> In 2010, due to capacity constraints, the company made a decision to relocate this printing plant yet again.<ref name=\"printlocate\">{{cite news | title = Aitken Spence Printing makes technology enhancements | newspaper = Sunday Times| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka | date = 24 October 2010 | url = http://www.sundaytimes.lk/101024/BusinessTimes/bt31.html| accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe production of printed packaging materials represents about 80 percent of business for the printing segment. In regards to packaging materials, it currently caters to major brands in garment industry, FMCG, cosmetics and pharmaceuticals in Sri Lanka. The company also caters to international clients such as [[Marks & Spencer]], British Home Stores, [[Tesco]] and DBA Europe.<ref name=\"printbegin\"/>\n\n===Next Generation Technology Products===\n\nIn October 2014, Aitken Spence invested in Eco Corp Asia, a company holding the exclusive rights in Sri Lanka to market nanotechnology based liquid glass coating product of Nanopool GmbH.<ref name=\"NanoPool\">{{cite news| title = Aitken Spence and Eco Corp Asia to take nanotechnology to next level| newspaper = Daily FT| location = Colombo, Sri Lanka| date = 3 November 2014| url = http://www.ft.lk/2014/11/03/aitken-spence-and-eco-corp-asia-to-take-nanotechnology-to-next-level/| access-date = 7 November 2014| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141107111542/http://www.ft.lk/2014/11/03/aitken-spence-and-eco-corp-asia-to-take-nanotechnology-to-next-level/| archive-date = 7 November 2014| url-status = dead}}</ref> The operation formulates specialized surface protection systems and applications on different materials utilizing nanotechnology; while introducing diverse innovative solutions for industries.<ref name=ARecocorpasia>{{cite web |title= Aitken Spence Annual Report Ecocorp Asia 2017/2018|author= Aitken Spence |accessdate=5 July 2018 |url= http://aitkenspence.com/annualreport/}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.aitkenspence.com Official Website]\n* [http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/Stock/SPENN?CountryCode=LK The Wall Street Journal MarketWatch Overview]\n\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Publicly traded companies of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies]]\n[[Category:Hospitality companies of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Logistics companies]]\n[[Category:Business process outsourcing companies]]\n[[Category:Hotel chains]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "defunct", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aitken_Spence"}
{"title_page": "Brooklyn Nine-Nine", "text_new": "{{short description|American police procedural comedy television series}}\n{{Use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Brooklyn Nine-Nine\n| image                    = Brooklyn Nine-Nine Logo.png\n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Television comedy|Comedy]]\n* [[Police procedural]]\n* [[Sitcom]]\n}}\n| creator                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Dan Goor]]\n* [[Michael Schur]]\n}}\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Andy Samberg]]\n* [[Stephanie Beatriz]]\n* [[Terry Crews]]\n* [[Melissa Fumero]]\n* [[Joe Lo Truglio]]\n* [[Chelsea Peretti]]\n* [[Andre Braugher]]\n* [[Dirk Blocker]]\n* [[Joel McKinnon Miller]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer     = {{ubl|Dan Marocco|{{small|featuring}}|Jacques Slade|Lamar Van Sciver|Frank Greenfield}}\n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = Dan Marocco\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 7<!-- Please do not change this number until the season has started airing. -->\n| num_episodes             = 142\n| list_episodes            = List of Brooklyn Nine-Nine episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Dan Goor]]\n* [[Michael Schur]]\n* [[David Miner (television producer)|David Miner]]\n* [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller|Phil Lord<br />Christopher Miller]]\n* Luke Del Tredici\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Marshall Boone\n* [[Norm Hiscock]]\n* Matt Nodella\n* Andy Samberg\n* [[Neil Campbell (producer)|Neil Campbell]]\n* Matt Lawton\n* Cortney Carrillo \n* [[Carol Kolb]]\n* Phil Augusta Jackson\n* [[Sierra Teller Ornelas|Sierra Ornelas Miller]]\n* Richard H. Prince\n}}\n| camera                   = [[Single-camera setup|Single-camera]]\n| runtime                  = 21\u201323 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Fremulon]]\n* [[Dan Goor|Dr. Goor Productions]]\n* [[3 Arts Entertainment]]\n* [[Universal Television]]\n}}\n| distributor              = [[NBCUniversal Television Distribution]]\n| network                  = [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] (2013\u20132018)<br />[[NBC]] (2019\u2013present) <!-- Do not add NBC until episodes have actually been produced (and they can be cited!) -->\n| picture_format           = [[High-definition television|HDTV]] [[1080i]]\n| audio_format             = [[Dolby Digital|Dolby Digital 5.1]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2013|9|17}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|present}}\n| website                  = https://www.nbc.com/brooklyn-nine-nine\n}}\n'''''Brooklyn Nine-Nine''''' is an American [[police procedural]] [[comedy]] television series created by [[Dan Goor]] and [[Michael Schur]]. The series revolves around Jake Peralta ([[Andy Samberg]]), an immature but talented [[New York Police Department|NYPD]] detective in [[Brooklyn]]'s fictional 99th Precinct, who often comes into conflict with his new commanding officer, the serious and stern Captain Raymond Holt ([[Andre Braugher]]). The rest of the cast features [[Stephanie Beatriz]] as Rosa Diaz, [[Terry Crews]] as Terry Jeffords, [[Melissa Fumero]] as Amy Santiago, [[Joe Lo Truglio]] as Charles Boyle, [[Chelsea Peretti]] as Gina Linetti, [[Dirk Blocker]] as Michael Hitchcock, and [[Joel McKinnon Miller]] as Norm Scully.\n\nProduced as a [[single-camera]] comedy, [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] originally ordered 13 episodes for its first season, eventually expanding it to 22 episodes. ''Brooklyn Nine-Nine'' premiered on September 17, 2013. On May 10, 2018, Fox canceled the series after five seasons. The following day, [[NBC]] picked up the series for a sixth season; it premiered on NBC on January 10, 2019. On February 27, NBC renewed the series for a seventh season, which premiered on February 6, 2020. The series was renewed for an eighth season in November 2019, ahead of the premiere of its seventh season.\n\nThe series has been acclaimed by critics for its cast, especially Samberg, Beatriz, Fumero, and Braugher. It has won two [[Creative Arts Emmy Awards]] and a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Television Series \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Golden Globe Award for Best Television Series&nbsp;\u2013 Musical or Comedy]]. Samberg has won a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy|Golden Globe Award for Best Actor&nbsp;\u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy]], while Braugher has been nominated for three consecutive [[Primetime Emmy Awards]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series]] and has won two [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series|Critics' Choice Television Awards for Best Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series]]. The series has also received particular praise for its portrayal of serious issues whilst retaining a sense of humor. For its portrayal of [[LGBTQ+]] people, the series won a [[GLAAD Media Award]] for Outstanding Comedy Series. <!--Per WP:CITELEAD, references are not needed in the lead if it is sourced in the body of the article!-->{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Premise==\nSet in the fictional 99th Precinct of the [[New York City Police Department]] in [[Brooklyn]], ''Brooklyn Nine-Nine'' follows a team of detectives headed by the overly serious, newly appointed Captain Raymond Holt ([[Andre Braugher]]). The detectives include Jake Peralta ([[Andy Samberg]]), who has a high rate of successful arrests and solved cases, in spite of his relaxed, carefree and (at times) childish attitude. He eventually falls for his stern, nerdy, by-the-book but loveable partner, Amy Santiago ([[Melissa Fumero]]). The hard-working but timid Charles Boyle ([[Joe Lo Truglio]]) is partnered with the apathetic, aggressive and stern, Rosa Diaz ([[Stephanie Beatriz]]). The pair of older Detectives, Michael Hitchcock ([[Dirk Blocker]]) and Norm Scully ([[Joel McKinnon Miller]]) often seem incompetent, stupid and lazy, but have solved more cases over the years simply because they have been on the job much longer. \n\nThe detectives report to Lieutenant Terry Jeffords ([[Terry Crews]]), a gentle giant and devoted family man who initially has a phobia of going back to active field police work for fear of being killed in the line of duty and leaving his children fatherless. The precinct also includes sarcastic and dominating civilian administrator Gina Linetti ([[Chelsea Peretti]]), who dislikes her job, prioritizes her social media, and believes that dancing is her life goal.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{{See also|List of Brooklyn Nine-Nine characters}}\n<!-- Do not replace this with a table. Per WP:TVCAST and consensus, the cast listing should be presented in prose or list format. -->\n* [[Andy Samberg]] as [[List of Brooklyn Nine-Nine characters#Jake Peralta|Jake Peralta]]\n* [[Stephanie Beatriz]] as [[List of Brooklyn Nine-Nine characters#Rosa Diaz|Rosa Diaz]]\n* [[Terry Crews]] as [[List of Brooklyn Nine-Nine characters#Terry Jeffords|Terry Jeffords]]\n* [[Melissa Fumero]] as [[List of Brooklyn Nine-Nine characters#Amy Santiago|Amy Santiago]]\n* [[Joe Lo Truglio]] as [[List of Brooklyn Nine-Nine characters#Charles Boyle|Charles Boyle]]\n* [[Chelsea Peretti]] as [[List of Brooklyn Nine-Nine characters#Gina Linetti|Gina Linetti]] (main season 1\u20136){{efn|Chelsea Peretti is credited as a series regular from 1x01 through 6x04. She is credited as a special guest star in 6x15.}}\n* [[Andre Braugher]] as [[List of Brooklyn Nine-Nine characters#Raymond Holt|Raymond Holt]]\n* [[Dirk Blocker]] as [[List of Brooklyn Nine-Nine characters#Michael Hitchcock|Michael Hitchcock]] (main season 2\u2013present, recurring season 1)\n* [[Joel McKinnon Miller]] as [[List of Brooklyn Nine-Nine characters#Norm Scully|Norm Scully]] (main season 2\u2013present, recurring season 1)\n\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Development and production==\n[[File:NYPD 78th precinct.jpg|thumb|The [[:en:Organization of the New York City Police Department#Police precincts|NYPD 78th precinct]] building in Brooklyn. An exterior image is used as an [[establishing shot]] during the show.]]\n[[Michael Schur]] and [[Dan Goor]], who had known each other since their time as students at [[Harvard University|Harvard]] and had collaborated on ''[[Parks and Recreation]]'', liked the idea of setting a comedy in a police station, a setting which they felt was insufficiently used for television comedies since ''[[Barney Miller]]''. They pitched the idea to [[Universal Television]], where Schur had a development deal. Although Universal agreed to produce the show, [[NBC]] passed on airing it, so the duo sold the series to the [[Fox Broadcasting Company]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2014/06/brooklyn-nine-nine-michael-schur-creator-interview-739199/|title=EMMYS Q&A: 'Brooklyn Nine-Nine' Co-Creator Michael Schur On Comedic Cops|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=June 3, 2014|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=May 11, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn May 8, 2013, Fox placed a thirteen-episode order for the [[Single-camera setup|single-camera]] ensemble comedy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fox-comedy-series-orders-chris-519678|title=Fox Comedy Series Orders: Chris Meloni Entry, 'Brooklyn Nine-Nine,' 'Enlisted,' 'Us & Them'|date=May 8, 2013|last=Rose|first=Lacey|last2=Goldberg|first2=Lesley|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=May 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/Fox-Fall-2013-Comedy-Brooklyn-Enlisted-Jack-1065183.aspx|title=Fox Orders Brooklyn Nine-Nine, Enlisted, Us & Them and Surviving Jack|date=May 8, 2013|last=Abrams|first=Natalie|work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=May 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/05/fox-picks-up-andy-samberg-chris-meloni-comedies-us-them-and-enlisted-almost-doubles-new-series-volume/|title=Fox Picks Up Andy Samberg & Chris Meloni Comedies, 'Us & Them' And 'Enlisted', Almost Doubles New Series Volume|date=May 8, 2013|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=May 12, 2013}}</ref> On October 18, 2013, the series was picked up for a [[Season (television)#Seasons/series|full season]] of 22 episodes, and was later chosen to air with ''[[New Girl]]'' in a \"special one-hour comedy event\" as the [[Super Bowl XLVIII]] [[List of Super Bowl lead-out programs|lead-out programs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2013/10/18/brooklyn-nine-nine-full-season-super-bowl/|title=Brooklyn Nine-Nine Scores Touchdown, Snags Full-Season Pick-Up and Post-Super Bowl Berth|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|last2=Roots|first2=Kimberly|work=[[TVLine]]|date=October 18, 2013|accessdate=October 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe exterior view of the fictional 99th Precinct building is the actual 78th Precinct building at the corner of Sixth Avenue and Bergen Street. It is one block south of the [[Barclays Center]] and one block east of the [[Bergen Street (IRT Eastern Parkway Line)|Bergen Street]] station on the [[New York City Subway]]'s {{NYCS trains|Eastern west local day|type=route}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://moviemaps.org/movies/qr |title=Brooklyn Nine-Nine Filming Locations |publisher=Movie Maps |accessdate=November 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn May 10, 2018, Fox canceled the series after five seasons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/05/10/brooklyn-nine-nine-canceled/|title=Brooklyn Nine-Nine canceled after five seasons|last=Snierson|first=Dan|date=May 10, 2018|website=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref> Shortly afterwards, there were announcements that negotiations had begun with [[Hulu]], [[TBS (U.S. TV channel)|TBS]], [[NBC]] and [[Netflix]] for the possibility of reviving the show for a sixth season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/brooklyn-nine-nine-new-home-hulu-tbs-fox-cancellation-pickup-fan-reaction-1202388006/|title='Brooklyn Nine-Nine': Hulu, Others Eye Fox Comedy After Cancellation'|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=May 10, 2018|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=May 11, 2018}}</ref> The next day, [[TVLine]] reported Hulu had already passed on the series.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tvline.com/2018/05/11/brooklyn-nine-nine-hulu-cancelled-season-6-passes/|title=Brooklyn Nine-Nine: Hulu Passes on Rescuing Cancelled Fox Comedy|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|date=May 11, 2018|work=[[TVLine]]|accessdate=May 11, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Shortly after, Goor announced that NBC would pick up the series for thirteen episodes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2018/05/12/nbc-saves-brooklyn-nine-nine-after-fox-cancellation/604426002/|title=NBC rescues 'Brooklyn Nine-Nine' after Fox canceled it|work=USA TODAY|accessdate=May 12, 2018|language=en}}</ref> In a statement, NBC Entertainment chairman [[Robert Greenblatt]] expressed regret for originally passing on the series to Fox and was \"thrilled\" at its addition to NBC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/brooklyn-nine-nine-nbc-1202808064/|title='Brooklyn Nine-Nine' to Continue on NBC|first=Joe|last=Otterson|date=May 12, 2018|accessdate=May 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/brooklyn-nine-nine-expanded-18-episode-order-nbc-1202459546/|title='Brooklyn Nine-Nine' Gets Expanded 18-Episode Order On NBC|date=September 7, 2018|accessdate=September 8, 2018}}</ref> A few days later, it was announced that the series would premiere mid-season in the [[2018\u201319 United States network television schedule|2018\u201319 television season]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|last2=Petski|first2=Denise|title=NBC Fall 2018\u201319 Schedule: 'Chicago'-Branded Wednesday, 'SVU' To Thursday, 'The Blacklist' Held For Midseason, 'World Of Dance' Moves In-Season|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/nbc-fall-2018-19-schedule-upfronts-new-shows-chicago-law-order-the-blacklist-this-is-us-world-of-dance-1202389757/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=May 13, 2018|date=May 13, 2018}}</ref> In September 2018, NBC ordered an additional five episodes for season 6, bringing the order to 18.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/brooklyn-nine-nine-scores-additional-5-episode-order-at-nbc-1202932130/|title='Brooklyn Nine-Nine' Scores Additional 5-Episode Order at NBC|first=Joe|last=Otterson|date=September 7, 2018|accessdate=October 6, 2018}}</ref> The sixth season began on NBC on January 10, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2018/11/08/brooklyn-nine-nine-season-6-premiere-date-nbc-thursday/|title=Brooklyn Nine-Nine Lands Thursday Perch, Bumping Will & Grace to Later Slot in NBC Thursday Makeover|date=November 8, 2018|publisher=TVLine|accessdate=November 8, 2018}}</ref> On February 27, 2019, NBC renewed the series for a seventh season, which premiered on February 6, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/brooklyn-nine-nine-renewed-season-7-at-nbc-1203151412/|title='Brooklyn Nine-Nine' Renewed for Season 7 at NBC|last=Otterson|first=Joe|last2=Otterson|first2=Joe|date=February 27, 2019|website=Variety|language=en|accessdate=February 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/nbcbrooklyn99/status/1192882629671997440?s=19|title='Brooklyn Nine-Nine' Season 7 one-hour premiere on February 6|date=November 8, 2019|language=en|accessdate=November 8, 2019}}</ref> On November 14, 2019, NBC renewed the series for an eighth season ahead of the seventh-season premiere.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2019/11/14/brooklyn-nine-nine-renewed-season-8-nbc/|title=Brooklyn Nine-Nine Snags Very Early Season 8 Renewal at NBC|first=Michael|last=Ausiello|website=TVLine|date=November 14, 2019|accessdate=November 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Brooklyn Nine-Nine episodes}}\n{{:List of Brooklyn Nine-Nine episodes}}\n\n==Reception==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"float: right;text-align:center;margin:20px\"\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | Season\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" | Critical response\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Rating\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:9px; background:#9A222A;\"|&nbsp;\n| Season 1\n| 89% (57 reviews)\n| 7.25/10\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:9px; background:#14131A;\"|&nbsp;\n| Season 2\n| 100% (17 reviews)\n| 7.96/10\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:9px; background:#662C35;\"|&nbsp;\n| Season 3\n| 93% (14 reviews)\n| 8.19/10\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:9px; background:#095457;\"|&nbsp;\n| Season 4\n| 100% (13 reviews)\n| 8.09/10\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:9px; background:#453C11;\"|&nbsp;\n| Season 5\n| 100% (13 reviews)\n| 8.33/10\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:9px; background:#DCC89F;\"|&nbsp;\n| Season 6\n| 100% (26 reviews)\n| 8.32/10\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:9px; background:#14131A;\"|&nbsp;\n| Season 7\n| 100% (7 reviews)\n| 8.5/10\n|}\n[[Rotten Tomatoes]] gave season one a score of 89% based on 56 reviews. The consensus is: \"Led by the surprisingly effective pairing of Andy Samberg and Andre Braugher, ''Brooklyn Nine-Nine'' is a charming, intelligently written take on the cop show format.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/brooklyn-nine-nine/ |title=Brooklyn Nine-Nine: Season 1 |publisher= [[Flixster]]/Warner Bros. | work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] |date= |accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref> For Season 2, it received a score of 100% based on 17 reviews. That season's consensus is: \"''Brooklyn Nine-Nine''{{'}}s winning cast, appealing characters and wacky gags make it good comfort food.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/brooklyn-nine-nine/s02/ |title= Brooklyn Nine-Nine: Season 2 |website= Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate= March 8, 2019}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] gives the first season of the show a weighted average rating of 70/100 based on 33 reviews, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.metacritic.com/tv/brooklyn-nine-nine |title=Brooklyn Nine-Nine \u2013 Season 1 Reviews |publisher= [[CBS Interactive]] | work = [[Metacritic]] |date=September 17, 2013 |accessdate=September 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Huffington Post]]'' posted a list of \"9 Reasons You Need to Start Watching ''Brooklyn Nine-Nine''\",<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/14/brooklyn-nine-nine_n_4590850.html |author= Duca, Lauren |date= January 14, 2014 |title= 9 Reasons You Need To Start Watching ''Brooklyn Nine-Nine'' |work= [[The Huffington Post]] |quote= As it happens, \"Brooklyn Nine-Nine\" is actually pretty good. Not only does it have an excellent (and diverse!) ensemble cast, but it subverts stereotypes while delivering the kind of silliness and absurdity that perhaps only ''30 Rock'' has executed so well. Arguably, the show is still finding [its] footing, so before the entire world starts watching without you, we have some convincing to do. |accessdate= December 7, 2014}}</ref> while [[Paste (magazine)|''Paste'' magazine]] celebrated \"The 10 Best Moments from ''Brooklyn Nine-Nine''{{'}}s First Season\" in 2014.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2014/04/the-10-best-moments-from-brooklyn-nine-nines-first-season.html |last=Walters |first=Eric |date=April 16, 2014 |title=The 10 Best Moments from Brooklyn Nine-Nine's First Season |magazine=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste magazine]] |accessdate=April 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n''Brooklyn Nine-Nine'' has received praise for its forthright portrayal of [[LGBTQ]] people and the serious issues that affect them, while retaining its sense of humor.<ref name=\"LGBT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/outward/2014/02/11/brooklyn_nine_nine_is_pro_gay_andy_samberg_show_sets_bar_for_post_doma_television.html|title=On Gay Issues, Brooklyn Nine-Nine Shines|last=Lopez|first=Tyler|date=February 11, 2014|website=[[Slate (website)|Slate]]|accessdate=January 2, 2018}}</ref> Portraying Captain Ray Holt, a lead character, as an openly gay, no-nonsense black man in a same-sex interracial marriage is unprecedented in cinema and television.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebacklot.com/andre-braugher-plays-gay-on-andy-sambergs-brooklyn-nine-nine/08/2013/|title=Andre Braugher Plays Gay On Andy Samberg's \"Brooklyn Nine-Nine|last=Halterman|first=Jim|date=August 2, 2013|website=[[AfterEllen.com and TheBacklot.com#TheBacklot.com|The Backlot.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130806061932/http://www.thebacklot.com/andre-braugher-plays-gay-on-andy-sambergs-brooklyn-nine-nine/08/2013/|archivedate=August 6, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.advocate.com/arts-entertainment/television/2014/03/11/foxs-newest-cop-comedy-brooklyn-nine-nine-quietly-breaking|title=Fox's Newest Cop Comedy Is Quietly Breaking Ground|last=Brydum|first=Sunnivie|date=March 11, 2014|website=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|accessdate=January 2, 2018}}</ref> The [[coming-out]] as bisexual by detective Rosa Diaz in episode \"[[99 (Brooklyn Nine-Nine)|99]]\", the 99th episode of the series, has been described as an important representation of [[sexual orientation]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/brooklyn-nine-nine-rosa-diaz-coming-out-99th-episode-1202631575/|title='Brooklyn Nine-Nine' Team on Rosa's Coming Out and Hitting 99 Episodes|last= Nyren|first= Erin|date= December 5, 2017|website= [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=January 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\n{{Television season ratings\n| hide_18_49_rating = y\n| show_network = y\n\n| link1             = Brooklyn Nine-Nine (season 1)\n| network1          = [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n| network_length1   = 5\n| episodes1         = 22\n| timeslot1      